1051	Michele	P	Benchouk				8283 Greensboro Drive		McLean	VA	22102	86.5799999999999983	Associate	Booz Allen Hamilton	17	Michele P. Benchouk\r\nYears of Experience:  17\r\n\r\nEducation and Certifications\r\n•\tM.S., Environmental Science and Policy, Johns Hopkins University, in progress\r\n•\tB.S., Environmental Engineering Technology, Temple University, 1992\r\n\r\nSummary of Professional Experience\r\nMs. Benchouk has over 17 years of professional environmental consulting experience.  Her particular areas of expertise include hazardous and solid waste management under RCRA, CERCLA, and other regulatory programs; selection, implementation, and documentation of investigation and remediation efforts; environmental program execution; release estimation and chemical report development in compliance with EPCRA; and regulatory analysis.  Ms. Benchouk currently provides technical and project management support to EPA.  She previously supported AFCEE with technical and programmatic environmental expertise at more than ten Air Force installations nationwide and three major command headquarters.  Prior to joining Booz Allen, Ms. Benchouk completed a wide range of technical assignments for a major paper products manufacturer, a local water authority, and a private environmental consulting firm assisting EPA with implementation of Superfund activity.  Ms. Benchouk possesses a strong knowledge base of current environmental regulations and guidelines, having served for several years on the RCRA, Superfund, and EPCRA Hotlines.\r\n\r\nSignificant and Relevant Project Experience\r\n•\tJune 2000 – Present.  Conducted file reviews, compiled information, and prepared numerous Environmental Indicator (EI) CA725 and CA750 determinations for groundwater stabilization in accordance with the GPRA.  Evaluated historic and current site conditions to determine if groundwater contamination had been fully delineated and was under control.  Identified data gaps where appropriate and provided recommendations aimed at achieving positive EI determinations for the sites.  Also provided data gap analyses for sites known to fall short of complete groundwater control and strategized with EPA to determine appropriate courses of action for meeting the relevant GPRA requirements.\r\n•\tOctober 2005 – Present.  Performed a variety of data gathering and data compilation tasks for various clients, including gathering cost/benefit data on the U.S. Army’s Pollution Prevention Investment Fund, available pollution prevention technologies and techniques, state-mandated pollution prevention, and international environmental management systems. \r\n•\tJune 2007 – Present.  Lead a team of ten multidisciplinary environmental professionals in development of a standardized series of Statement of Work (SOW) templates for rapid response environmental activities at federal client sites.  Actions for which the SOWs were prepared included facility damage assessment, petroleum and hazardous substance spill response activity, provision of emergency supplies and emergency power, indoor air quality assessment, health and safety monitoring, long term environmental monitoring, mold sampling and site characterization, and threat/vulnerability assessment.\r\n•\tMay 1999 – Present.  Provided technical and engineering support for review of numerous RCRA Part B permit applications, permit modifications, draft operating and post-closure permit modules, draft Notices of Deficiency (NODs), NOD responses, and associated fact sheets for several Air Force and EPA sites.  Unit types included hazardous waste storage areas, container storage areas, landfills, tanks, surface impoundments, waste piles, incinerators, and open burn/open detonation facilities.  Identified deficiencies and recommended strategies to achieve full regulatory compliance.  Reviewed engineering drawings and waste management plans.\r\n•\tApril 1999 – Present.  Managed ten complex environmental assignments for EPA in New York, Puerto Rico, Virginia, Pennsylvania, Alaska, Utah, and Colorado.  These assignments involved corrective action support, permit reviews, permit development, laboratory evaluation, sampling and analysis, closure assistance, incinerator trial burns, risk assessment, visual site inspections, development of RCRA Facility Assessment Reports and soil investigation work plans, hydrogeology in karst and fractured rock areas, contractor negotiations, and community relations in New York.  Provided direct and timely support to numerous EPA clients and supporting technical staff.  Coordinated and oversaw subcontractor work.\r\n•\tJanuary 1996 – Present.  Reviewed and provided comments on various technical documents including work plans, sampling and analysis plans, RFAs, RFIs, imminent health risk letters, project definition reports, site characterization summaries, draft design documentation, operation and maintenance plans, groundwater monitoring reports, RI technical reports, EE/CAs, proposed plans, fact sheets, No Further Response Action decision documents, and other technical materials.\r\n•\tMarch 1999 – July 1999.  Assisted in development of internal Standard Operating Procedures for environmental sampling of soil, groundwater, surface water, sediment, air, and waste, as well as field preparation, documentation, shipping, and chain of custody.  Ensured compliance of SOPs to current requirements and guidance. \r\n•\tNovember 2003¬ – December 2004.  Reviewed Army Environmental Center records on the Pollution Prevention Investment Fund.  Compiled available information on the five-year program to allow for analysis of costs, return on investment (estimated versus actual), and installation compliance with reporting requirements.  Prepared a summary report highlighting key findings and trends.  Assisted in compilation of a pollution prevention resource table and state-specific pollution prevention requirements.\r\n•\tJanuary 1996 – April 1998.  Provided technical support for environmental investigation and restoration activities at several Air Force installations in New Mexico, Wyoming, and California.  Prepared statements of work, costs estimates, and peer review packages to facilitate AFCEE contracting.  Evaluated contractor proposals with respect to scope, technical feasibility, personnel , cost, and schedule.  Provided recommendations for cost-savings and participated in technical negotiations between AFCEE and environmental contractors.  Participated in meetings between Air Force personnel, environmental regulators, and study/remediation contractors.\r\n•\tJanuary 1996 – April 1998.  Provided technical oversight for environmental field work including major investigation efforts, UST removals, and semiannual groundwater monitoring events at various Air Force restoration sites, including fuel and solvent spills, solid and hazardous waste landfills, pesticide/herbicide sites, aircraft crash sites, paint shops, wastewater treatment plants, oil/water separators, and stormwater basins.  Technologies implemented included soil vapor extraction, groundwater extraction with air stripping, bioventing, landfarming, passive remediation via an iron filings reaction wall, soil washing, incineration, UV oxidation, and excavation for proper off site waste management and disposal.\r\n•\tJanuary 1996 – April 1998.  Coordinated with ACC Headquarters to prepare funding requests, cost estimates, and GANTT timelines for multi-million doll study and remediation projects.  Analyzed historical environmental cleanup efforts at Beale AFB and outlined an appropriate scope of work for future fiscal years, totaling an average of $9 million per year.\r\n•\tMarch 1996 – February 1998.  Supported three MAJCOMs and the Air Force Institute of Technology (AFIT) in development of various environmental restoration training materials.  Assisted AFIT in development of lesson plans and course materials for two courses on environmental restoration and program management.  Coordinate the development of training plans and environmental training handbooks, outlining required and recommended training for environmental professionals in the Air Force at both installation and MAJCOM levels.  Facilitated outsourcing of training by identifying potential training providers both internal and external to the military.\r\n•\tJanuary 1996 – July 1999.  Managed a team of environmental professionals in standardizing and updating Management Action Plans (MAPs) across Air Combat Command bases in the U.S.  Worked with representative from the MAJCOM and bases to determine specific Air Force goals and schedules.  Provided technical recommendations for each document to enhance usability and reflect the specific needs of each installation and environmental program manager.  Facilitated discussion and coordinated efforts between AFCEE, the Army Corps of Engineers, and another support contractor.  Assisted in development of supporting materials for revision of the MAP guidebook in 1998 and 1999.\r\n	2015-02-27 05:24:47.743444	2015-02-27 05:24:47.743444	281
1052	Douglas		Sarno				1055 North Fairfax Street		Alexandria	VA	22314	175	Principal	Perspectives Group Inc	20	Doug Sarno                                              The Perspectives Group\r\nProposed TASC Role: Senior Public Participation and Community Involvement Advisor\r\nLocation: Region 3; Virginia\r\n\r\nExperience Summary\r\n\r\nDoug Sarno has over twenty years of facilitation experience in community outreach and communications and has conducted more than 50 major public participation projects. He has also facilitated over 1,000 meetings and developed programs and publications to assist in evaluation and decision-making on a broad range of issues. He has managed and facilitated seven long-term stakeholder advisory boards and designed and facilitated over ten national stakeholder forums and several international forums. His articles, reports, and presentations on collaborative decision-making, stakeholder and public participation, communications, community visioning, and long-term stewardship have resulted in significant changes in the way decision-making is approached worldwide.\r\n\r\nHe has participated in task forces and advisory panels aimed at improving management and decision-making for EPA, DOE and other federal agencies, non-profit groups, the National Academies of Science, and Harvard University. He served five years as the Executive Director of the International Association for Public Participation for which he is also a licensed Master Trainer for the IAP2 Certificate Program in Public Participation.\r\nMr. Sarno holds an MBA and a BS in Civil Engineering. Before founding the Perspectives Group in 1993, he worked five years as Manager of Federal Programs for the non-profit Superfund policy group Clean Sites, served three years as an environmental engineer at EPA in the Superfund program, and worked as a civil engineer on Superfund sites for SAIC.\r\n\r\n\r\nHighlights of Experience\r\n\r\n•\tSenior analyst for EPA OSWER’s evaluation of Technical Assistance Grants (TAG) and Technical Outreach Services for Communities (TOSC) grant programs.  Oversaw process of conducting 48 interviews in nine regions across 18 sites and identified programmatic barriers, strengths and weaknesses.  Based on the analysis, served as lead analyst and writer in making recommendations for improving technical assistance.\r\n\r\n•\tDesigned and facilitated a public participation program and community visioning process to determine future land uses and cleanup levels at a 1,000-acre federal facility radioactive waste site.  PG’s process helped to provide balanced information to all stakeholders, including Native American groups, to overcome a decade of anger and mistrust and develop a consensus set of recommendations for the comprehensive cleanup of the site.  Over 150 stakeholders met in three large workshops to create a common understanding of interests and opportunities. The International Association recognized the Fernald Citizen Advisory board as “Organization of the Year” for Public Participation.\r\n\r\n•\tDesigned and facilitated a future use planning process to engage the public in determining how the 35,000-acre federal facility should be used.  The results were accepted by both the public and the Department of Energy and have been used to guide all environmental decision-making over the past five years.  Extensive public education and training conducted on a wide range of environmental issues including ground water, risk assessment, waste containment systems, nuclear criticality, fate and transport, chemistry, and hydrology.\r\n\r\n•\tDesigned and facilitated a process to determine the appropriate location to dispose of Mill Tailings, overcoming years of indecision in facilitating a plan that was made and implemented.  Mediation spanned two months and involved hundreds of citizens from two Utah cities and several Native American tribes.\r\n\r\n•\tLead a team of facilitators to gather input from nearly 200 stakeholders to help design public participation in the implementation of dredging on the Hudson River in New York, a 200-mile long Superfund site.\r\n\r\n•\tDesigned and implemented an exercise called FutureSite™ that allowed citizens to directly explore options for waste excavation and disposal.  The three-dimensional model allowed a breakthrough in thinking at the site and became a touchstone throughout the DOE as a decision-making aid.  \r\n\r\n•\tWorked with two other experts to create a tool describing the levels of public participation for the International Association for Public Participation.  The result was the IAP2 Public Participation Spectrum that is now used worldwide to help people understand how to select the appropriate level of public participation.  \r\n\r\n•\tRedesigned a course on working with stakeholders for the Fish and Wildlife Service.  Created a detailed model of collaboration to help students understand how the collaborative process works.  The course has become one of the most popular and highest rated now offered and both the Office of Personnel Management and the Environmental Protection Agency have adopted the Collaborative Model from this course for their training.\r\n\r\nMr. Sarno has used his technical and scientific background to create materials, events and programs that allow citizens to not only understand issues but also to provide meaningful input to decision making. He has designed and implemented many information tools, exercises and workshops to enhance understanding and dialogue and has achieved consensus on highly technical and controversial topics. Finally, he has trained over 2,000 individuals in public participation, collaboration, public information and communication, and facilitation and will be able to work with designated Technical Assistance Specialists and Technical Experts to improve their facilitation and public collaboration skills.\r\n	2015-02-27 05:24:47.866213	2015-02-27 05:24:47.866213	282
