tion, staff training and supervision, agency management, and university classroom teaching.  I have substantial experience in the design, delivery, and evaluation of training programs for professional, paraprofessional, and lay audiences. I have developed expertise in training on cultural competence; community needs assessment; program planning and design; community engagement; and program evaluation and sustainability. \r\n\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\tSince 1988, I have been a member of the staff of the Center for Community Health Resource Development with the School of Public Health of the University of Alabama at Birmingham.  As a program manager with the center, I have worked with a variety of local, state, and regional/national agencies and communities around such diverse issues as HIV and other STDs treatment and prevention; migrant and seasonal farm worker health care needs; home fire safety and fire prevention; adolescent foster care; Latino/a health promotion; and environmental health. \r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\tDuring my time with the Center, I have had the opportunity to serve as a project director or coordinator with several community-based academic research projects.  The first set of projects addressed prevention of HIV infection and other sexually transmitted diseases, specifically gonorrhea. In the field of injury prevention, I served for three years as the state coordinator and two years as the project evaluator/community facilitator for the Alabama Smoke Alarm Initiative, which is a home fire safety/prevention project.  \r\n\r\nIn the field of environmental health, since 2001, I served as Project Manager for the UAB’s Center of Excellence in Environmental Health project, “Developing Communities of Excellence in Environmental Health” from October, 2001 through September, 2004. With this program, I became a trainer for the Protocol for Assessing Excellence in Environmental Health (PACE EH).  I provided training in Alabama and Tennessee, as well as for the Indian Health Service. \r\n\r\nI served as Project Director for the, “Southeast Region Environmental Public Health Academic Center” from October, 2004 – September, 2007. For that project which involved provision of technical assistance, consultation, and training, I had the responsibility for day-to-day implementation of all facets of the project, particularly in those areas involving establishing and maintaining operations relating to the project’s partnerships with the environmental public health leadership in 10 southeastern states and two U.S. territories.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRESUME of Thomas C. Struzick\t\t\t\t\t\tPage Three\r\n\r\nI presently serve (since October, 2007) as the Training Facilitator and Project Evaluator for a CDC-funded, three-year, $325,000, capacity building project.  This project addresses formation of collaborative partnerships to implement a best-practice, community-based mosquito control project.   I wrote the grant application \r\nfor this project for the Jefferson County Department of Health. \r\n\r\n\tMy work with these research projects has broadened my vision on issues which need to be addressed in the design, implementation, management, and \r\nevaluation of health promotion and disease/injury prevention programs, with a particular emphasis on communication between providers and consumers of public health services.\r\n\r\n\tIn March, 2000, I was appointed to the position of Associate Director of the Center for Community Health Resource Development.  In that position, I am responsible for providing administrative and management support to the Center Director and the Center staff.  In 2009, I was appointed as the Director of Training for the UAB Prevention Research Center.  \r\n\r\nI have served on several university-wide committees addressing research and training for cultural competence; health literacy; obesity and diabetes; religion and spirituality in health research work group; and the integrated medicine (CAM) partnership. \r\n\r\nI am a diversity training specialist with the UAB Human Resources Organizational Development Office.  As such, I serve on the instructional design team and an instructor with the DIVERSITY UAB programs.  I have taught the Basic Concepts class and the Diversity Awareness Education 2-hour employee orientation class.  I am certified by the Franklin Covey program to teach, “Championing Diversity”.  I am also working with several UAB departments/schools on developing training resources to cultural competence. I have provided training for graduate and undergraduate students in dentistry, health care professions, and public health. \r\n\r\nI also have a faculty appointment as a Research Assistant Professor for our university’s bachelor social work education program in the School of Social and Behavioral Science.  I have taught social work practice courses since 1993.  Those courses include generalist social work practice with an emphasis on the strengths-based perspective and field seminar; social work ethics and values; HIV and Social Work; Cultural Diversity and Social Work Practice; Social Work in Health Care Settings; and Social Welfare Policy Analysis.  I also served our BSW program as the Field Instruction Coordinator for two and a half years.  \t \r\n\r\n\r\nCOMMUNITY SERVICE\r\n\r\n\tI have served on several boards of directors and have done volunteer work for many different health and human service agencies. Presently, I am a founding member of the board of directors for Times Out, Inc., a 501 (c) (3) organization providing companionship services for persons with severe and chronic physical and \r\nRESUME of Thomas C. Struzick \t\t\t\t\t\tPage Four\r\n\r\nmental illnesses. I am a founding member of the Jefferson County Children’s Policy \r\nCouncil and serve at the chairperson for the Health Committee. I also serve on the Children’s Hospital’s Advisory Committee for the Comprehensive Health Education Center for Kids (C.H.E.C.K.).  I serve as a volunteer social work advisor for Birmingham AIDS Outreach supervising social workers and conducting training for agency staff. \r\n\r\n\r\nPROFESSIONAL ORGANIZATIONS\r\n\r\n\tI am a member of the National Association of Social Workers and the Academy of Certified Social Workers.  For public health and environmental health, I am a member of the National Environmental Health Association. \r\n\r\n\r\nPUBLICATIONS\r\n\r\nOn Environmental Health: \r\n\r\nReport:\r\n\r\n1.  Tom Struzick. Environmental Public Health Practice in the Southeastern United States: Environmental Public Health Practice Profiles for Ten Southeastern States.  Report submitted to the Division of Emergency and Environmental Health Services, National Center for Environmental Health, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention\r\n\r\nPublication: \r\n\r\nLCDR Molly Patton, REHS, MPH and Tom Struzick, MSW, M.Ed.  “The Indian Health Service and PACE EH”.  NACCHO Exchange, Vol. 6, No. 2, Spring, 2007.\r\n\r\nCurricula:\r\n\r\nCommunities Working for Environmental Health:  A Guide for Public Health Environmentalists.  A seven module training program available online at:  www.se-rac.uab.edu (training resources tab). Developed for the CDC’s National Center for Environmental Health by the Southeast Regional Academic Center for Environmental Public Health. \r\n\r\nThe Environmental Public Health Certificate Program.  A 15-course training program being developed in partnership with the Jefferson County Department of Health and the South Central Center for Public Health Preparedness. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRESUME of Thomas C. Struzick \t\t\t\t\t\tPage Five \r\n\r\nPeer-Reviewed Publications:\r\n\r\nOn Religion and Spirituality:\r\n\r\n1.  David E. Vance, Tom Struzick, and Toya Russell.  Spiritual and Religious Implications of Aging with HIV: A Conceptual and Methodological Review.  Journal of Religion, Spirituality and Aging.  Vol. 19, No. 2, 2007\r\n\r\n2.   Vance, D. E., Antia, L., Blanshan, S., Bodner, E., Heirs, K., Smith, B., & Stru