1059	Jon		Townsend				PO Box 167		West Linn	OR	97068	250	Facilitator	AgreementsWork	35	Jon Townsend, MA\r\nPartner, AgreementsWork \r\n\r\nJon Townsend has worked for more than 35 years in the fields of mediation, facilitation, negotiation, diversity and cross-cultural conflict resolution, and peacemaking.  His consulting firm, AgreementsWork, provides training and consultation in the areas of collaborative-based negotiation, workplace mediation, cross-cultural mediation, business negotiation, inter-cultural communication and workforce diversity, labor-management negotiation, and community and organizational development.  \r\n\r\nThroughout the United States and in Indian Country, Jon has assisted hundreds of organizations to diversify their workforce, negotiate and mediate “win-win” agreements, successfully manage intercultural conflict, and utilize and value differences in the workforce and community.  His experience includes work with large businesses, with state, local and federal and tribal governments, as well as non-profit organizations, communities, unions and individuals.  Jon has taught and teaches at a variety of schools and universities, including Humboldt State University’s Institute for Study of Alternative Dispute Resolution (ISADR); and Sonoma State University, where he co-developed the Conflict Resolution Program and teaches negotiation, mediation and cultural diversity courses.\r\n\r\nJon is the founder of the national award-winning Clackamas County Dispute Resolution Center, and served as the Center’s Advisory Chair for twelve years.  He both writes and lectures to professional audiences, and co-authored “Power and Dispute Resolution in Indian Country”, which appeared in the journal Mediation Quarterly.   Jon’s most recent article, The intercultural mediator: Nexus of practice and theory appeared in the December 2002 issue of the Pacific Mountain Network News.\r\n\r\nInternationally, Jon has conducted numerous workshops and provided consultations and training in Nicaragua, Mexico, Costa Rica, the former USSR, Russia, Guatemala, Ecuador, Cuba, Canada, Australia and Poland and England.   On his fourth trip to the Russian Republic, Jon led an American delegation assisting with the reorganization of the Russian Employment Service. The assistance included seminars and consultation on such subjects as downsizing the workforce, job creation and job training, outplacement and retraining, customer service and dispute resolution issues.  In April 1995, Jon was a senior team consultant and trainer in an historic dispute resolution training session with the Cuban Ministry of Foreign Affairs, in Havana, Cuba.   In 2005, 2006, 2007 and 2008 Jon trained English mediators for England’s largest community-based mediation program in beginning and advanced mediation and advanced negotiation.\r\n\r\nJon is a member of the Association for Conflict Resolution and the Oregon Mediation Association.  He currently serves as the President of the Board of Directors for the Rural Community Assistance Corporation.  He is the recipient of numerous awards, including a Presidential citation for his work in the area of job retraining, and the designation “Mediator of the Decade” by a national Native American Dispute Resolution organization, presented for his many years teaching and consulting in Indian Country.  He has worked with over eighty Tribal Nations and tribal organizations on a variety of issues providing a range of services.\r\n\r\nJon is a citizen of the Muscogee (Creek) Indian Nation.  He has a Master’s Degree in Psychology from Sonoma State University and is a member of the United Association of Labor Educators (UALE).\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSome related examples of work:\r\n\r\nThe National Bison Range Complex.\r\n\r\nThis complex negotiation began in 2007.  I first assessed the project and then designed and facilitated the process of negotiation.  The project resulted in a signed agreement in September of 2008.  As the lead trainer and lead facilitator, I helped the parties identify where their respective interests were similar, where they were different (yet not conflicting) and where there were potentially conflicting interests.  I helped the parties develop strategies and processes for maximizing similar and different interests while minimizing and/or overcoming potentially conflicting interests.  As lead facilitator, I also helped the parties develop meaningful procedural ground rules and substantive proposals for mutual gain.  I also helped the parties develop and implement dispute resolution processes, and establish on-going review stages to insure continuous improvement and agreement monitoring.  \r\n\r\nAfter five months of facilitated meetings and substantive negotiations, Confederated Salish and Kootenai Tribes of the Flathead Reservation and the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service signed an historic annual funding agreement (AFA) for the National Bison Range Complex.  The Complex is located in Moiese, Montana, within the boundaries of the Flathead Indian Reservation.  On June 19, 2008, the Tribes and the Fish and Wildlife Service signed a three-year funding agreement, representing a government-to-government partnership to share management responsibilities for the National Bison Range.   Outcome: After a 90-day Congressional review period by the Senate Indian Affairs Committee and the House of Representative’s Natural Resources Committee, the Annual Funding Agreement became final on September 24, 2008.  \r\n\r\nThe Timberline Lodge Compact.  The Timberline Lodge Compact (TLC) is a Public/Private Partnership between RLK, Inc. and the USFS.  TLC is a thirty-year (30) agreement developed through a series of facilitated meetings in November and December of 2007.  The Compact Agreement expresses the parties’ intentions and serves as the working document for this innovative, long-term and viable public/private partnership.  \r\n\r\nAs the trainer and facilitator, I helped the parties identify where their respective interests were similar, where they were different (yet not conflicting) and where they held potentially conflicting interests.  I then helped the parties develop strategies and processes for maximizing similar and different interests while minimizing and/or overcoming potentially conflicting interests. I also helped the parties develop meaningful procedural ground rules; processes to deal with conflicts throughout the life of the agreement; and processes to update and improve their agreements with on-going review at certain stages.  The agreement covers, but is not limited to: organization and staffing; financial resources and needs; revenues, fees and appropriations; gratuities and surcharges; and funding.   Outcome:   Private-Public Agreement-February 2008.\r\n\r\n\r\nDefense Dept./Tribal Governments Project: Government-to-Government Consultation: 2006 – current.  I serve as a trainer and as a facilitator for these training and problem solving projects.  I designed the intercultural communication portion and IBN portion of this multi-faceted project. I am the facilitator between DoD personnel and Tribal participants.  The program is designed to increase DoD and Tribal awareness of each other and of their cultures.  The best government-to-government consultation practices are explored and current problems or questions that parties are experiencing are discussed and problem-solved. Locations have included Anchorage, Seattle, Tulsa, Elmendorf Air Force Base, Silverdale, Washington, and Fairbanks.  Parties have included Air Force, Coast Guard, Army, Navy personnel, numerous federal and state government participants and a variety of tribal governments and personnel.   Outcomes:  Training Completion and/or Facilitated Agreements.\r\n\r\nUSEPA, Navajo EPA and Navajo Grassroots Groups:  Served as principle trainer and facilitator for EPA-OEJ project that worked with the Navajo Government, Navajo EPA and four Navajo grassroots groups: Dine Care, Black Mesa Water Coalition, C’Aquifer for Dine, and the Indigenous Waters Network.  Outcome:  This 8 month project led to the creation of a preliminary agreement on the Protocols on Communication and Collaboration between the Navajo Environmental Justice Grassroots Organizations and the Navajo Nation EPA on January 30th, 2007.\r\n\r\n\r\nOregon DEQ/Use Attainability Analysis: \r\nI served as co-facilitator on this complex case involving the EPA, Oregon DEQ and tribal, federal, private business, citizen groups and other state agencies regarding the Clean Water Act. Purpose: To create a document intended to describe the information Oregon Department of Environmental Quality (ODEQ) staff should review to determine (1) whether a designated use change is appropriate, (2) what use is attainable in the water body and (3) that appropriate criteria are established to support the new designated use. The developed document guides the ODEQ in applying existing statutes and rules related to a Use Attainability Analysis.  Parties included, but were not limited to the following.  NGO: River Network, American Rivers, Columbia River Intertribal Fish Commission; Federal agencies: NOAA, BPA, USFWS, USBR, Army Corp of Engineers, USFS; State agencies: ODA, Oregon Dept. of Forestry, Oregon DEQ; and Tribes: Confederated Tribes of Grand Ronde, Confederated Tribes of Siletz, Warm Springs. The first workgroup meeting occurred on June 30, 2004.  Five additional meetings were scheduled for August through November of 2004.  A final draft of the guidance document was made available in November 2004.    Outcome:  State Guide developed and operational in 2005.   \r\n\r\nPortland General Electric/Hydropower Re-licensing:  \r\nI served as primary trainer and secondary facilitator in this yearlong project involving the re-licensing of the Willamette Falls Hydroelectric Project.  The issues were scientific, environmental, political, financial and legal.  Environmental issues ranged from water quality and water quantity, the impact of the Endangered Species Act, the Clean Water Act, the Oregon Water Quality Act, and more.  Participants included Portland General Electric, Blue Heron Paper Company, the National Marine Fisheries Service, US Fish and Wildlife Service, Oregon Department of Water Resources, the Oregon Department of Environmental Quality, Oregon Fish and Wildlife, The Confederated Tribes of the Warm Springs Reservation of Oregon, The Confederated Tribes of Siletz Indians, The Confederated Tribes of the Grand Ronde Community of Oregon, American Rivers, The Native Fish Society, Oregon Trout, and others.  Outcome: Hydropower re-license obtained.\r\n\r\nPortland General Electric/Hydropower Negotiation Training and Facilitation:  \r\nProvided a series of negotiation training and facilitation for Portland General Electric, the US Forest Service, Oregon State DEQ, FERC, the Oregon HART group, Oregon Tribes and others on hydropower related issues and re-licensing concerns related to the Willamette and Clackamas Rivers. Outcome: All parties trained.\r\n\r\nDept. of Interior and Southern Plains Tribes Project:\r\nProvided a series of facilitated discussions on the development of various models and processes that would allow tribes to address their own leadership disputes without resorting to tribal or federal courts.  The models and processes ultimately developed would not replace any existing tribal laws and tribes would not be required to use them.  Rather, models and processes would be an option available for a tribe having difficulty communicating effectively, or wanting to deal internally with leadership disputes.  The processes and models were collaboratively developed by tribal leaders, federal and state officials, law enforcement agencies, and tribal or CFR court representatives, and had an emphasis on process flexibility and cultural relevancy. Parties included the Caddo, Kaw, Iowa Tribe of Oklahoma, Citizen-Pottawatomie, Comanche, Sac & Fox Nation of Oklahoma, DOI, BIA -CFR Court, and the Southern Plains Regional Office and Washington D.C. offices of the BIA.  Outcome:  Model developed.\r\n\r\nPort of Portland and Citizens Noise Advisory Committee: November 1999 to January 2001.  I provided a series of IBN training and subsequent facilitation services for the Port of Portland and the Citizens Noise Advisory Committee (CNAC) regarding noise pollution and airline flight routing.   The focus was on parties working together collaboratively to finding solutions. CNAC representatives included the City of Vancouver, Washington, the City of Portland, Oregon Multnomah County, Oregon, Clark County, Washington, and neighborhood spokespersons, the Port of Portland and several environmental groups. Outcome:  Agreement reached.\r\n\r\n Oregon State Department of Forestry: June 2001 to November 2001: \r\nI provided IBN training and facilitated a series of meetings for the Oregon State Department of Forestry in Astoria and Forest Grove, Oregon.  Parties included representatives from the State of Oregon, counties, cities, tribes, private citizens, environmental groups and privately owned timber and forest products companies.  The goal was to provide a focus group forum where representatives with diverse viewpoints can discuss implementation plans and advise Oregon Department of Forestry districts on plan alignment with the NW Oregon State Forests Management Plan. Both groups provided a written report and a series of jointly -developed recommendations to respective District Foresters and the Department of Forestry as end products.  Outcome: Jointly developed District Reports and Recommendations.\r\n\r\nState of Oregon and the 9 Oregon Tribes: Served as the principle facilitator on the development and implementation of government-to-government negotiations between the State of Oregon and 8 of the 9 Oregon Tribes. The process involved preparing the representatives of the Oregon tribes to sit down with the negotiation team representing all state agencies to create a framework and protocols for developing and managing government-to-government consultations.\r\nOutcome:  A two-day meeting between the nine Tribes and the State of Oregon was facilitated at which time a new consultation and negotiation framework was developed to ensure improved relationships and government-to-government protocols.  Oregon was the first state to initiate this type of process.\r\n\r\n\r\n	2015-02-27 05:24:48.735948	2015-02-27 05:24:48.735948	306
