1061	Douglas	G	Streaker				2081 Clipper Park Road		Baltimore	MD	21211	0	Water Resources Engineer	Biohabitats, Inc.	12	Douglas G. Streaker, PE\r\nEmployment\r\n2007 - Present\tBiohabitats, Inc., Water Resources Engineer\r\n1999 – 2007\tGreenman-Pedersen, Inc, Water Resources Engineer\r\nSummer 2001\tWestern Slope Environmental Resource Counsel, GIS Intern\r\n1998  \tLancaster Laboratories, Instrumental Water Quality Department, Senior Laboratory Technician\r\nEducation\r\nB.S., Biological Systems Engineering - Concentration in Land and Water Resources, Virginia Tech, Blacksburg, Virginia 1998\r\nProfessional Registration\r\nMaryland Registered Professional Engineer #30734/2004\r\nExperience\r\nMr. Streaker is a water resource engineer specializing in stream restoration and stormwater management design.  He has performed geomorphic assessments of numerous degraded streams, and has designed, prepared construction documents and specifications, and coordinated permitting for many stream restoration projects. He has also designed numerous stormwater BMP’s, pond retrofits and stormwater wetlands.  He has performed construction inspection for stream restoration and SWM projects.  His computer skills include MicroStation CAD, MS Access, ArcView GIS applications, and hydraulic and hydrologic modeling (GIS-Hydro, TR-20, HEC-1, HEC-2 and HEC-RAS).\r\nTechnical Training\r\nWildland Hydrology, Rosgen Level I-IV Stream assessment-Natural channel design/2004-2006\r\nNatural Rivers: Mechanisms, Morphology and Management, R. Hey/2003\r\nAnne Arundel County Coastal Plain Outfall Design Training/2007\r\nAmerican Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE) Urban Watershed Best Management Practices (BMPs)/2002\r\nMaryland Green Card for Sediment and Erosion Control/2001\r\nOccupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) Confined Space Entry/2002\r\nMaryland Transportation Technology Transfer Center Construction Inspection Training/2003\r\nMaryland State Highway Administration GISHydro Training/2007\r\nRelevant Project Experience\r\nLower Lower Stony Run, Baltimore, MD. As project engineer, Mr. Streaker is part of the Biohabitats team that conducted stream geomorphic surveys on the approximately 4,000 linear feet restoration project for the Baltimore City Department of Public Works, Bureau of Water and Wastewater.  The survey consisted of collecting stream cross section, profile, planform geometry, and characterization of the streambed of the existing incised channel.  This will support the natural channel design techniques utilized in the design plans to stabilize the degraded stream channel.  The project goals are to improve water quality by reducing the introduction of sediment into the stream system by stabilizing actively eroding banks and improving aquatic and riparian habitat. \r\nPoplar Spring Court Stream Restoration, Fairfax County, VA.  As project engineer, Mr. Streaker worked collaboratively to develop a restoration plan for a degraded stream.  The design approach emphasized raising the incised stream to connect to the available floodplain, realign the stream from threatened properties, and enhance vegetation in the wooded corridor.  Mr. Streaker was an integral part of creating preliminary design plans that include a grading plan, profile, typical sections, and construction details.  \r\nBridle Path Lane Stream Restoration, Fairfax County, VA.  As project engineer, Mr. Streaker worked collaboratively to develop a restoration plan for a degraded stream.  The design approach emphasized raising the incised stream to connect to the available floodplain, creating a two-staged channel, and enhance vegetation in the wooded corridor.  Mr. Streaker was an integral part of creating preliminary design plans that include a grading plan, profile, typical sections, and construction details.  \r\nCrofton Tributary Stream Restoration, Anne Arundel County, MD.  Mr. Streaker is the project engineer for the Biohabitats team to develop a stream restoration design for the tributary. The goal of the project is to restore watershed process including recharging the groundwater table to regenerate spring seeps by reconnecting the stream channel to its floodplain.  This approach in turn eliminates high and eroding banks, improves water quality and creates conditions favorable for native Anne Arundel County coastal plain biota, while naturally controlling invasive species.  As project engineer, Mr. Streaker was integral in the restoration design, grading plan, and construction details.  He also performed the hydraulic analysis, comparing existing to proposed conditions.\r\nRuppert’s Ravine Phase II Tributary Restoration, Anne Arundel County, MD.  Mr. Streaker is the water resources engineer as part of the Biohabitats team tasked with developing a stream restoration design for the tributary. The design proposes converting the incised and headcutting stream channel into a stable seepage wetland ecosystem well linked to its historic floodplain.  Recharging the groundwater table will help support a number of threatened plant species associated with Anne Arundel County’s native acid seep wetland systems.  \r\nWindsor Ridge Road Stream Stabilization, Anne Arundel County, MD. Mr. Streaker is the water resources engineer for the Biohabitats team that is contracted to provide full design and construction plans as well as construction oversight services for this approximately 2,000-ft long stream restoration project.   The stream is currently intermittent and incised approximately 12-ft, and originates at a dual 48-in barrel culvert.  With Mr. Streaker’s input, the team developed a stream restoration concept plan that fills the incised channel with porous granular material (sand) held in place with grade control weirs and cobble riffles.  \r\nHanson Road Channel Restoration Preliminary Concept, Harford County, MD.  As project engineer, Mr. Streaker assessed the existing conditions of the site and developed a restoration concept approach, schematic design, cost, and report for a severely eroding channel that originates below an existing stormwater management pond.  The goal of the project is to provide both stable conveyance and treatment of stormwater runoff, while minimizing impacts to the adjacent buffer and maximizing the restoration of the channel and riparian habitat.  The concept developed incorporates regenerative stormwater conveyance techniques to achieve the stated goals. As project engineer, Mr. Streaker developed a concept report that summarized existing conditions and the approach proposed. It also included preliminary hydrologic and hydraulic computations, an engineer’s cost estimate and concept plan, profile, and details.\r\nDorsey Run Fish Passage, Maryland State Highway Administration.  As project engineer, Mr. Streaker developed the preliminary design options for the creation of two separate fish passage sites.  Fish blockages along Dorsey Run in Anne Arundel County and Howard county MD will be removed at a low head dam and culvert, using a combination of channel realignment and rock weir structures to raise water surface elevations above these blockages and improve channel stability and habitat.  In addition, Mr. Streaker performed a field assessment and developed the hydrologic and hydraulic analysis to analyze channel stability and flooding impacts for this project.  \r\nEnvironmental Mapping/Ecological Assessment/Infrastructure Planning for the Carolina North Property, Chapel Hill, NC.  As water resources engineer, Mr. Streaker provided analysis for identifying potential stormwater management opportunities on this significant planning effort for approximately 1000 acres at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. The scope of work focuses on understanding the ecological processes currently influencing the 1,000-acre property, valuing the complex array natural resources, and proposing guidelines for land development activities that are ecologically sustainable long into the future. Biohabitats produced GIS maps illustrating all ecological attributes, ecological conditions, and suitability of development and resource protection. This information will be fed into the Master Plan Initiative, where Biohabitats will focus on sustainable and regenerative design principles.\r\nShore (Belt) Parkway Water Quality Best Management Facilities, New York City, NY. As water resources engineer, Mr. Streaker designed two stormwater facilities as part of the Biohabitats design team to develop final construction drawings for stormwater quality best management practices (BMPs) to be incorporated into planned roadway improvement projects associated with bridge crossings on the Belt Parkway, located in Jamaica Bay.  The BMPs emphasize vegetative filtering and uptake followed by infiltration through the sandy soils.  The design team is addressing several site constraints , including avoiding a force main, high groundwater table, tree avoidance, and adapting to the roadway conveyance system without compromising safety considerations.     \r\nPike Creek at Independence School Stream Restoration, New Castle County, DE. As water resources engineer for this project, Mr. Streaker provided construction oversight of the realignment and restoration of 3175 linear feet of a severely degraded trout stream and 4 acres of wetland restoration. \r\nIntercounty Connector Baseline Assessment and Restoration Design, Montgomery County, MD. Mr. Streaker as a member of the Biohabitats’ design team is responsible for the stream design on this contract. Biohabitats and Century Engineering are working together on the baseline assessment and restoration design of approximately 50 acres of wetlands, 30 acres of reforestation, and approximately 1-1/2 mile of stream in Montgomery County as compensation for the impacts associated with the SHA's ICC project.   \r\nMaryland State Highway Administration (SHA) On-Call Remedial Wetland Mitigation and Stream Restoration Design, Construction and Associated Services (BCS 2000-05), Harford County, Magness Farm Restoration, Maryland State Highway Administration. As water resources engineer for this mitigation services contract for with MSHA, Biohabitats is responsible for the mitigation design of an approximately 7-acre wetland and 800-ft long creek.  Mr. Streaker’s work includes final construction plans and handling markups from agency comments, as well as construction oversight.\r\nCrestwood Lake, Westchester County, NY. Mr. Streaker is project engineer on this Westchester County, NY lake restoration job. Crestwood Lake is an online lake on the Bronx River near Tuckahoe that suffers from excess sediment deposition.  Biohabitats is working with Westchester County Department of Planning to develop a series of restoration alternative concepts.  Mr. Streaker is performing a hydraulic assessment of the different alternatives to assess their impacts and effectiveness.   \r\nMinebank Run Post Construction Monitoring, Baltimore County, MD.  Mr. Streaker led the first year post construction assessment of the Minebank Run Stream Restoration.  Using repetitive field survey, stream cross sections, structure surveys, and qualitative stability and vegetation assessments, Mr. Streaker developed a comprehensive assessment report of the stream for the first year of a three year monitoring period.\r\nRelevant Project Experience Prior to Biohabitats, Inc.\r\nCrofton Pond Stormwater Management Pond Retrofit, Anne Arundel County, MD. Mr. Streaker designed a retrofit of an existing stormwater management (SWM) pond to provide water quality treatment according to County and Maryland Department of the Environment (MDE) Stormwater Design Manuals to meet a National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System (NPDES) water quality treatment goal. His design included adding a forebay and grading micropools to provide water quality treatment storage through a combination of permanent pool storage for sediment settlement and water quality treatment from a wetland area in the micropool. A native vegetative community of various wetland plants was specified to provide shade conditions to reduce thermal impacts, promote biological uptake of nutrients, and improve aesthetics. He prepared design plans and sediment control plans, as well as a dam breach analysis and a hydrogeologic (HGL) analysis of the receiving close storm drain system. \r\nSevern Village SWM Pond Retrofit, Anne Arundel County, MD. Mr. Streaker prepared construction documents, specifications, cost estimates, and provided permit coordination to retrofit an existing SWM pond to provide water quality treatment.  Doug’s H&H computations indicated that the pond could be classified as a roadway embankment, and did not need to meet MD378 requirements.  His design included creation of a large stormwater wetland with permanent pools, a low flow stream channel, cobble weirs, and zoned palustrine and wetland plantings.  \r\nIntercounty Connector Stream Mitigation and Environmental Stewardship Monitoring and Design, Maryland State Highway Administration Mr. Streaker led a two year geomorphic assessment of 28,000 linear feet of stream channel based on Rosgen methodologies of assessment and field validation. As Project Manager, his duties included data management and quality control of all the field data using GIS, Rivermorph and various custom made spreadsheets. He was responsible for the data analysis, including bankfull verification, historical photo comparisons, validation of estimated results, entrainment, and changes in channel cross section and longitudinal profile. Mr. Streaker was in charge of the concept plan submittal, including plan and profile creation, construction details, engineer’s estimate, and assessment findings report. \r\nChartwell Stream Restoration, Anne Arundel County, MD. Mr. Streaker prepared contract documents and directed the construction inspection to restore 800 feet of stream eroded by unmanaged flows from a SWM pond.  Mr. Streaker calculated bankfull and larger flow reductions in the stream resulting from the retrofit of the SWM pond using TR-20, and designed stable channel cross sections using geomorphic and hydraulic principles.  Mr. Streaker’s design included modifications to the channel profile to reduce the slopes of culvert crossings and reduce channel shear stresses.  Furnished streambed material remains stable during all in-bank flows, boulder cascades maintain grade control in steeper stream reaches, and terraces above the bankfull elevation and bioengineering create a stable, natural channel.\r\nWhite Marsh and Western Run Stream Restorations, Baltimore County, MD. Mr. Streaker performed geomorphic assessments and prepared concept through final construction plans, specifications, and cost estimates for the restoration of approximately 10,000 LF of channel.  His designs included creating stable C channel reaches to protect private properties and sanitary sewers, while maintaining the current volume of sediment transport.  Mr. Streaker designed channel stabilization, including bank and point bar grading, using reference reach data.  He also designed rock and log vanes, furnished streambed material sizing, and prepared bioengineering and riparian area plant specifications.  He designed rock cross vane grade control, and boulder step pipe protection to protect at-grade sanitary sewer crossings in the stream channel.  Doug used HEC-RAS to determine 100-year flood elevations.\r\nWestern Run Watershed Stream Assessment, Baltimore City, MD.  Mr. Streaker coordinated and led the assessment of over 5 miles of stream within the Western Run watershed to identity potential stream stabilization projects.  His duties included documenting existing stream conditions, managing the base and field collected GIS data, analyzing stream restoration needs, prioritizing stabilization projects, preparing conceptual restoration sketches and cost estimates, and preparing a final report that serves as a tool for the City to easily identify the projects with the best ecological and cost-benefit potential.\r\nBrock Bridge Stream Restoration, Anne Arundel County, MD.  Mr. Streaker performed a Rosgen Based Level II and III geomorphic assessment, alternatives/cost benefit analysis, and schematic design through Contract Documents to restore a severely incised G stream channel to a B channel by raising the stream invert.  His design included step pools, riffle sections designed using reference reach data, log vanes, bioengineering, and riparian plantings.  He coordinated MHT, wetland delineations, tree surveys, prepared and processed environmental permits, and supervised construction oversight. Construction oversight includes clarification of plans, minimizing construction impacts, material approval, ensuring proper material handling and installation, verifying quantities, approving invoices, preparing Daily Reports, and coordinating with the County.\r\nAlta Vista Stream Restoration, Montgomery County, MD.  Mr. Streaker performed a stream assessment, designed, and prepared construction documents to stabilize 2,000 feet of a sediment supply limited, eroded stream.  Mr. Streaker performed all the hydrologic and hydraulic computations necessary to ensure a stable design.  The restoration design included bank grading, installation of bioengineering, and riparian plantings for bank stabilization and protection from freeze/thaw erosion.  In-stream structures include step pools, rock baffles, cross vanes, rock packing, log vanes, and imbricated rip rap walls.\r\nMS4 Drainage/SWM Inventory, Maryland State Highway Administration.  Assisted with managing data QA/QC efforts for SHA’s Anne Arundel County roadway storm drain inventory and BMP inspection data.  Supported office and field inventory of storm drains and BMPs along SHA’s roadways in Anne Arundel County.  Performed outfall screening for illicit discharge and BMP inspections, as well as management of GIS/database model.  Prepared Annual NPDES Report and supplemental SWM Facilities Summary.\r\n\r\nNPDES Industrial Permitting Program, Maryland State Highway Administration.  Served to assist with SWPPP preparation and wastewater discharge permit preparation for various State Highway maintenance facilities.  Tasks included site inspections, preparation of SWPPPs and relative site plan with drainage areas using Microstation.  \r\n\r\n\r\n	2015-02-27 05:24:48.922707	2015-02-27 05:24:48.922707	308
