ion, with an hour to spare.\r\nUnion Square Traffic and Streetscape Improvements, Somerville, MA; Ongoing. Mr. Kindsvatter served as the urban design lead for Von Grossmann & Company (working as integrating urban systems Through design subconsultants) on this complicated urban node. Seven roads converge on Union Square and conflicts between pedestrians, drivers and bicyclists reduce the quality of life in this vital commercial center. Mr. Kindsvatter developed a number of roadway and sidewalk alternatives that simplified and shortened pedestrian crossings, provided additional sidewalk width for outdoor cafe seating, and preserved links to a proposed Green Line station. Currently the City of Somerville is working to select a preferred alternative that will be taken through preliminary design.\r\nAshland, MA Downtown and Rail District Master Plan, and Feasibility Study for 125 Front Street Site; 2005 Mr. Kindsvatter lead an interdisciplinary team to work with the Ashland community to identify its desirable characteristics, urban design and development issues, and the strategies for addressing these issues. At the core of the study is a community desire to direct new development in ways that support transit use and a vibrant, walkable community. Products included a development strategy for the 125 Front Street, city-owned parcel at the core of the downtown; a reuse strategy for a historic fire station; pedestrian/bicycle path and greenway network planning, reuse of a downtown mill, and land use planning and streetscape enhancements throughout the project area.\r\nKnoxville Central Station Transportation Center, Knoxville, TN; 2008. Mr. Kindsvatter developed conceptual designs, and prepared alternative evaluations for a 22-bay bus transit facility that will form the foundation for a future mixed-use, air-rights development on a site in the heart of downtown Knoxville.\r\nHenderson Intermodal Transfer Terminal, Henderson, NV; 2005. Mr. Kindsvatter was the urban designer 