 1986-1996\r\n?Louisiana Governor-Elect Roemer’s Transition Environmental Advisory?Panel, 1987\r\n?EPA Class II Injection Well Advisory Committee, 1990 to 1993\r\n?Chairman of the Review Committee for Louisiana Proposed Solid Waste?Regulations, 1991\r\n?Member of the IOGCC Review Team for the Pennsylvania State Oil and Gas?Waste Program, 1991 to 1992?Louisiana Governor-Elect Edwin Edwards Environmental Transition Team,?1991 to 1992?\r\nLouisiana DEQ NORM Committee to develop regulations and disposal?options for Oil and Gas NORM Waste, 1992?National Commission on Superfund, 1993 to 1995?\r\nEPA Common Sense Initiative, Petroleum Refining Sector Subcommittee,?1994 to 1999\r\n?DEQ Recycling and Solid Waste Reduction Committee, 1995?\r\nEPA Permit Reform Committee, 1997\r\n?EPA Toxics Data Reporting Committee of the National Advisory Council for?Environmental Policy and Technology, 1997 to 1999\r\n?EPA RCRA Remedial Waste Policy Advisory Committee 1997?to 2000?\r\nEPA National Advisory Council for Environmental Policy and Technology (NACEPT), 1999 to 2005, \r\nVice-Chair?EPA NACEPT Standing Committee on Sectors, Co-Chairperson, 1999 to?2002\r\n?EPA NACEPT Petroleum Refining Sector Workgroup, 1999 to?2002?\r\nEPA National Advisory Committee (NAC) to the U.S. Representative to the?Commission for Environmental Cooperation (CEC) 2000 to 2005?\r\nEPA National Environmental Justice Advisory Council (NEJAC), 2001 to?Sep. 2006?\r\nEPA National Advisory Council for Environmental Policy and Technology?(NACEPT), Superfund Subcommittee, 2002 to 2003\r\n?EPA National Environmental Justice Advisory Council (NEJAC), Pollution?Prevention Work Group, Co-Chair, 2002 to 2003\r\n?EPA National Environmental Justice Advisory Council (NEJAC) Cumulative Risk/Impacts Work Group, 2003-2005?State Review of Oil and Natural Gas Environmental Regulations Board  (STRONGER), 2004 to present?\r\nEPA National Environmental Justice Advisory Council (NEJAC) Gulf Coast Hurricanes Work Group, 2005-2006?Vice-Chair of Board of State Review of Oil and Natural Gas Environmental Regulations, 2007??\r\nAWARDS?Women of Achievement Award from Connections, 1989.?\r\nLouisiana Wildlife Federation’s Governor’s Conservation Achievement?Award, 1989.\r\n?MacArthur Fellowship Award from John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation, 1999.?\r\nVolvo for Life Award, Environmental Category, one of three national finalists?2004.???\r\n\r\nTechnical Experience of Wilma Subra and Subra Company??     \r\nSubra Company is a woman owned small business formed in May 1981 and began operation in June 1981.  Subra Company is an environmental consulting firm which specializes in providing services to citizens groups and  environmental organizations.??    Wilma Subra and Subra Company have performed a large number of projects which have dealt with various aspects of hazardous and toxic waste issues associated with contaminated air,  surface and ground water, soil and sediment, biota and humans in general and Superfund Sites in particular.  Since May 1981, she has been the Technical Advisor  to the Vermilion Association to Protect the Environment (VAPE) under the EPA Technical Assistance Grant Program (TAG) for the three Superfund Sites in Vermilion Parish, Louisiana.  The three TAGs were the first awarded in the State of Louisiana to citizens groups living near Superfund sites.  Ms. Subra has provided technical assistance to VAPE on the three Superfund sites as well as 50 plus additional sites in Vermilion Parish since 1980.  The Gulf Coast Vacuum Superfund site was a truck transportation facility and became a Superfund site on March 31, 1989.  Oil field waste and hazardous waste were disposed of in pits on the site and waste was dumped into coulees and streams surrounding the site.  The remedy selected was incineration to address the organic constituents of the waste followed by stabilization to address the heavy metals and on site disposal.  After the Record of Decision (ROD) was signed, an alternative remedy was proposed which replaced incineration with bioremediation.  The revised ROD was issues with incineration as a fall back if bioremediation failed to meet clean up levels.??     The PAB Oil Superfund site was a permitted commercial oilfield disposal facility in Vermilion Parish and became a Superfund Site on March 31, 1989.  The remedy selected was bioremediation of the organic waste, stabilization of the heavy metals and on site disposal. The D. L. Mud Superfund site in Vermilion Parish was a mud mixing facility that was listed as a Superfund site in October 1989.  Under emergency removal actions, the majority of the waste was disposed of off site.  The ROD included off site disposal of organic hot spots, restricted access to prevent contact with slightly elevated heavy metals in the surface soils,  and reopener clauses if the groundwater contamination increased in severity.?                                          ?     Wilma Subra was the Technical Assistant under the TAG program to the Coalition for Community Action an environmental justice community in Alsen, Louisiana for the Petro Processors Superfund site from July 1992 to September 1994.  The Petro Processors site was a commercial hazardous waste disposal facility which received waste from the petrochemical facilities along the Mississippi River.  The initial remedy involved the construction of an on-site lined disposal vault, excavation of the waste and  disposal of the waste in the vault.  During the waste excavation activities, air emissions caused workers at adjacent plants and community members to become ill.  The remedy was stopped and the second remedy involved covering the site (two separate waste disposal areas) with clay caps.  Under the second remedy, the waste is being extracted through sumps and recovery wells and is being treated on site through incineration. After the initial three year TAG grant period, the Coalition for Community Action decided not the renew the grant due to difficulties within the community group in administering the business aspects of the grant.  Since the end of the TAG contract period, technical assistance has continued to be provided to the Coalition for Community Action on a pro bono basis by Ms. Subra.??     In 1995, Wilma Subra began serving as one of the Technical Advisors to Slidell Working Against Major Pollution (SWAMP) for the Bayou Bonfouca Superfund site in Slidell, Louisiana.  The Bayou Bonfouca site was an old creosote treating facility.  The remedy selected by EPA was incineration of the waste, sludge and bayou sediments.  The incineration of the Bayou Bonfouca waste has been completed and the incinerator residue landfilled on the Superfund site.  Ground water remediation is  in progress utilizing the pump and treat method. ??     In May 1995, Wilma Subra began serving as the Technical Advisor for Slidell Working Against Major Pollution (SWAMP) on the Southern Shipbuilding Superfund site, in Slidell, Louisiana.   The?Southern Shipbuilding site was an abandoned ship building operation with extensive contamination of the ground, ground water,  and surface water resources in the area and down stream of the facility.  The remedy was excavation of the waste, incineration at the Bayou Bonfouca incinerator, and  disposal of the waste in an on site cell. The remainder of the site was cleaned up to residential  standards and developed as a residential subdivision.  ??     In 1995, Uncertain Audubon hired Wilma Subra as their Technical Advisor for the Longhorn Army Ammunition Superfund site in Karnack, Texas.  The Ammunition military site was utilized to produce a large variety of army arsenals and to dispose of explosives, ammunition and Persian Missiles.  The facility has in  excess of fifty individual sites that were investigated for the presence of hazardous waste.  Old landfill areas on the site have contaminated groundwater with free phase solvents.  Waste from one old waste disposal area has migrated into Harrison Bayou which flows into Caddo Lake.  Caddo Lake serves as the drinking water source for Shreveport, Louisiana.  Industrial facilities on the site have  been identified as sources of surface water contamination by perchlorate.  This is an emerging military contaminant issue receiving extensive investigation at the national level.  The Longhorn Army Ammunition Superfund site has utilized the Restoration Advisory Board (RAB) process, the Community Advisory Group (CAG) process and the Technical Assistance Grant?(TAG) processes to evaluate the issues and proposed remedial actions at the site.  The property on the Ammunition site and the remedial activities associated with reuse designations has been designated for wildlife management preserves,  reuse as commercial property and recreational areas.  Evaluation of these reuse options drove the remedial activities at the site.  ??     In 2001, Citizens Against Toxic Exposure (CATE) selected Wilma Subra as the Technical Advisor for the Escambia Treating Company (ETC) Superfund site in Pensacola, Florida.  The ETC site is an abandoned wood treating facility in an environmental justice community.  Under the Superfund process the ETC site has had the relocation of two sets of environmental justice communities.  The waste from the wood treating facility has contaminated the groundwater off site for four miles from the site.  The waste from the site has been excavated, solidified and replaced in cells on the site.  The site is now being developed for reuse as commercial  and small business facilities.  ??     In 2000, Southwest Workers Union requested technical assistance from Wilma Subra for the Kelly Air Force Base in San Antonio, Texas.  Kelly was undergoing Base Realignment  (BRAC) and the reuse of the facility was a controversial topic with the  environmental justice community of hispanics living in the area surrounding Kelly.  Kelly was the oldest air force base continuously operating in the United State.  A large number of organics, solvents, heavy metals and radioactive contaminants had  contaminated surface and subsurface soils, surface water bodies and aquatic organisms, and groundwater with free phase materials. The shallow groundwater off site was contaminated with organic solvents for four miles off site under the residential area of San Antonio.  The shallow groundwater contaminants off gas into the homes over the contaminated groundwater plume.  The Kelly site has as RAB.  The hispanic community is for the most part excluded or silenced by the RAB and have to depend on additional technical assistance from  Ms. Subra to deal with the impacts of the Kelly facility on their health and environment.  Meanwhile Kelly now known as Kelly USA is operating with military contractors performing similar activities as was conducted when the base was Kelly Air Force base.  The operations of Kelly USA are having extensive negative impacts on the hispanic communities along with the historical negative impacts of the previous operations. ?                                             ?     In 1993 and 1994, Wilma Subra served as a Technical Advisor to the National Commission on Superfund.  The commission consisted of broad based representation of the various stakeholders in the Superfund process (industry, federal agencies, state agencies, local government, insurance companies, national environmental organizations, grass roots environmental groups, Native American tribes, and environmental justice representatives).  Wilma Subra serves as the Technical Advisor to the minority grass roots representative on the Commission and served on many key policy committees.  The commission was formed to make recommendations for the reauthorization of the Superfund legislation based on their broad based experience of working within the Superfund process since its inception.??     In 2002 and 2003, Wilma Subra served on the EPA National Advisory Council for Environmental Policy and Technology (NACEPT), Superfund Subcommittee.  The Superfund Subcommittee consisted of a broad spectrum of governmental officials, regulatory agencies, industries involved in the Superfund process and environmental, environmental justice  and non-governmental representatives.  Wilma Subra served as the NACEPT official representative to the Superfund Subcommittee.  The Subcommittee was formed to oversee the Superfund process and make recommendations for the immediate and long term future of Superfund.  The recommendations were presented to the NACEPT Council and forwarded to the Administrator of EPA. \r\n	2015-02-27 05:24:50.259975	2015-02-27 05:24:50.259975	319
