1201	Dexter		Albert	dexter@intrinsicinfo.com	928-522-6015		PO Box 336		Flagstaff	AZ	86002	115	Owner/Manager	Intrinsic Consulting, LLC	13	June 3, 2011\r\nCheryl Little\r\nSkeo Solutions\r\nclittle@skeo.com\r\nDear Ms. Little:\r\nI am pleased to submit the enclosed qualifications, resume and rate structure to provide\r\ntrainings to tribes/indigenous organizations on or near the Oneida Nation, Wisconsin, in July\r\n2011. Specifically, I am proposing to develop training materials and deliver training to tribal\r\ncommunities on collaborative problem-solving (CPS) and appropriate dispute resolution\r\n(ADR).\r\nMy company, Intrinsic Consulting LLC, is a Native American- and woman-owned public\r\ninvolvement company with offices in Flagstaff, Arizona, and Wimberley, Texas. Intrinsic\r\nspecializes in community infrastructure, environmental and transportation projects. Services\r\ninclude facilitation, process design, public involvement/participation, issue advocacy,\r\ncommunity relations and public education, public meeting organization, issue mapping and\r\nstrategic planning. Intrinsic’s mission is to generate and act on ideas that offer intrinsic value\r\nto our customer organizations, capitalizing on our collective skills and experience.\r\nI have ample experience working with tribes and tribal communities on issues of\r\nenvironmental and public health concerns utilizing skills in problem-solving and dispute\r\nresolution. Specific projects have addressed and incorporated environmental justice\r\nprinciples, and I have facilitated a variety of processes to resolve environmental and public\r\nhealth disputes involving tribes and tribal communities. I have also developed and delivered\r\na number of trainings and presentations nationwide on working with tribes and tribal\r\ncommunities.\r\nThank you for this opportunity. I look forward to working with Skeo Solutions and the EPA’s\r\nOffice of Environmental Justice to design and provide this training.\r\nSincerely,\r\nDexter Albert, Owner/Manager\r\nIntrinsic Consulting, LLC\r\nDexter Albert Qualifications\r\nTribal Training Consultant\r\nJune 3, 2011\r\nQualifications\r\nIntrinsic Consulting, LLC, is a Native American- and woman-owned public involvement firm and is\r\ncertified as a Disadvantaged Business Enterprise (DBE) in the state of Arizona. Intrinsic’s mission is to\r\ngenerate and act on ideas that offer intrinsic value to customer organizations, capitalizing on our\r\ncollective skills and experience. Intrinsic has extensive experience working with tribes and tribal\r\ncommunities on numerous public involvement, stakeholder facilitation, citizen outreach and conflict\r\nresolution projects.\r\nIntrinsic has developed and delivered local and nationwide presentations and trainings on topics such as\r\nopportunities to connect with tribal communities, communication processes and decision-making in\r\ntribal communities, relationship-building with tribal nations, mediation processes and tribal culture, and\r\ncultural sensitivity. Intrinsic is adept at coordinating with tribal agencies at all levels of tribal\r\ngovernments to involve them in planning processes, and has assisted in the development of\r\npartnerships and agreements between tribes and public agencies. Through extensive research and work\r\nwith dozens of tribes, Intrinsic has identified and implemented best practices on communication and\r\ncollaboration with tribes and tribal communities. Some examples include employing multi-faceted\r\ncommunication methods when working with tribes; allowing flexibility in the project schedule to\r\naccommodate internal tribal practices and typically already overwhelming workloads; acknowledging\r\nthat tribes are socially, culturally and politically diverse and cannot be perceived as homogenous; and\r\nrecognizing that tribes tend to approach problem-solving and decision-making more holistically than the\r\ndominant society and government agencies.\r\nSome examples of Intrinsic’s work with tribes include:\r\n?? A nationwide study regarding collaborative efforts between transportation agencies and tribal\r\ncommunities for the National Transportation Research Board in 2009-2010;\r\n?? A statewide survey of tribal transportation officials in Arizona as part of a Rural Transit Needs\r\nStudy for the Arizona Department of Transportation (ADOT) in 2006-2007;\r\n?? Facilitating meetings in Phoenix, Dallas and Chicago for a national workgroup comprised of\r\nrepresentatives from tribes and the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) to develop and\r\nimplement a national underground storage tank compliance strategy for the EPA in 2004-2005;\r\n?? An EPA-funded Community Master Plan for the Gila River Indian Community in 2009;\r\nDexter Albert Qualifications\r\nSkeo Solutions/EPA – Tribal Training Consultant\r\nPage 2\r\n?? Tribal involvement and government-to-government consultation during the development of a\r\nnational planning rule for the Southwestern Region of the US Forest Service in 2010;\r\n?? Roadway safety improvements on Route 6 for the San Carlos Apache Tribe in 2010-2011;\r\n?? And an ongoing project to conduct regional workshops with tribes nationwide regarding\r\nrevisions to land use regulations for the Bureau of Indian Affairs.\r\nAdditionally, Intrinsic has worked with government agencies to provide tribal relations, public\r\ninvolvement/outreach and partnership building on numerous transportation projects throughout Indian\r\nCountry during the past six years, including feasibility studies, environmental studies, Design Concept\r\nReports, final design projects, scenic byways planning, educational campaigns, and roadway\r\nconstruction outreach.\r\nDexter Albert, owner and manager of Intrinsic, is an experienced facilitator, community organizer,\r\noutreach specialist and event planner. He has worked on many rural and tribal relations projects in\r\nnorthern Arizona, the Southwest and throughout the country. Both clients and the public have\r\nconfirmed Dexter’s superior organizational skills, as well as responsiveness and sensitivity in dealing\r\nwith public concerns. Dexter is an enrolled tribal member who grew up on a tribal reservation, giving\r\nhim a unique perspective and direct exposure to the work Intrinsic does. He has a living knowledge of\r\nlocal American Indian cultures and is respected for his ability to be inclusive and to reach out across\r\ntribal affiliations. Dexter brings with him expertise in working with multiple tribes and facilitating\r\ndifferent ideas so that a diverse group can come to consensus around a topic or concept. Ultimately, he\r\naims to work with stakeholders and project teams to achieve mutual understanding and outcomes that\r\nare beneficial to all participants.\r\nDexter’s experience includes\r\n?? Co-facilitating a listening session with tribes regarding the development of mutual trust,\r\neffective communication and cooperation to improve government-to-government relations and\r\naddress common natural and cultural resource issues in the Southwest for the Bureau of Land\r\nManagement in 2006;\r\n?? Developing a comprehensive Tribal Involvement Plan as part of a forest plan revision project for\r\nthe Coconino and Kaibab National Forests in 2006-2007;\r\n?? Facilitating a multi-day work session with grazing officials, chapter officials, council members,\r\ncommunity members and tribal and federal officials to work toward a common understanding\r\nof Navajo Partitioned Land grazing regulations for the Bureau of Indian Affairs in 2007;\r\n?? Coaching, mentoring, training and capacity-building services for the Gila River Indian Community\r\non a Community Action for a Renewed Environment (CARE) project for the EPA in 2008;\r\n?? And facilitating dialogue between agency decision-makers and tribal leaders at a Bald Eagle\r\nTribal Consultation Meeting for the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service in 2008.\r\nDexter holds a certificate from the International Association for Public Participation (IAP2) for public\r\nparticipation training. He is also a member of the U.S. Institute for Environmental Conflict Resolution’s\r\n(USIECR) National Roster of Environmental Dispute Resolution and Consensus Building Professionals, the\r\nDexter Albert Qualifications\r\nSkeo Solutions/EPA – Tribal Training Consultant\r\nPage 3\r\nUSIECR Native Dispute Resolution Network, the Environmental and Public Policy Section of the\r\nAssociation for Conflict Resolution, the Coconino County Inter-Tribal Advisory Council, the Grand Canyon\r\nChapter of IAP2, and the New Mexico Mediators Association.\r\nRelated Experience\r\nDexter has worked on numerous projects related to the upcoming training. The following case studies\r\noffer insight into his prior experience and qualifications related to the current effort.\r\nPROJECT WORK\r\nGila River Indian Community (GRIC) CARE Program: The purpose of the project was to create a\r\ncommunity partnership within GRIC to identify and prioritize environmental toxics, with the ultimate\r\ngoal of developing a community risk reduction plan. EPA Region IX retained Dexter Albert of Intrinsic as\r\na third party neutral to coach the GRIC CARE team and help prepare them for the community\r\ninvolvement process. By coaching, mentoring, training and demonstrating various skills, including\r\nfacilitation, strategic planning, outreach, visioning and mapping exercises, Dexter was able to provide a\r\nboost to the overall CARE process. In addition, Dexter worked to develop structure and instill leadership\r\nin internal team meetings and helped to create a strategic plan and timeline. At the conclusion of\r\nDexter’s role in the project, he prepared a detailed report of his activities including lessons learned and\r\nrecommendations for further activity.\r\nUnderground Storage Tank Strategy – Tribal Facilitation: In August 2005, the U.S. EPA was given one\r\nyear to develop and present to Congress a nationwide strategy, in coordination with Indian tribes, to\r\ngive priority to Underground Storage Tanks (UST) that present the greatest threat to human health or\r\nthe environment. The EPA Office of UST developed a workgroup consisting of both EPA staff and Native\r\nAmerican representatives. The EPA wanted to develop a clear understanding of what a national strategy\r\nfor USTs on tribal lands should include based on the views of both EPA and tribal workgroup members.\r\nDexter’s role was to garner participation from at least 50 tribes (out of more than 500 tribes\r\nnationwide), as well as EPA headquarters and staff from 12 different regions under extreme deadline\r\npressure. He had to ensure that one particular region or tribe did not dominate the discussion, and the\r\nworkgroup had less than one year to complete the strategy and present its findings. Dexter helped\r\nfacilitate a series of meetings between EPA officials and tribal representatives to develop and implement\r\nthe national UST compliance strategy, including meetings in Phoenix, AZ; Dallas, TX; and Chicago, IL. He\r\nassisted participants in articulating their interests, identifying areas of agreement, and recommending\r\nsolutions. He also helped to keep the parties talking, listening, and moving toward the goal of the\r\nprocess. The national workgroup worked on a draft of the strategy, and the final strategy was submitted\r\nto Congress on time.\r\nDexter Albert Qualifications\r\nSkeo Solutions/EPA – Tribal Training Consultant\r\nPage 4\r\nSonoran Bald Eagle Tribal Consultation: In 2007, the US Fish & Wildlife Service (USFWS) arranged a\r\nmulti-tribal consultation meeting with Arizona tribes regarding the petitioned and court ordered\r\ndetermination on whether or not to recognize the Sonoran bald eagle as a distinct population and\r\nwhether or not protection under the Endangered Species Act was warranted. A number of tribes were\r\nconcerned that the USFWS could only accept scientific and commercial information as part of its\r\ndetermination. While purely cultural/religious information falls outside of what can be considered, tribal\r\ntraditional information regarding biology, status or threats to bald eagles may be considered. Dexter\r\nAlbert of Intrinsic Consulting was retained as a third-party facilitator to ensure that all tribes had an\r\nopportunity to fully participate in the consultation meeting. Dexter assisted the USFWS in developing\r\nthe meeting agenda design and format and methods for eliciting and recording feedback. He facilitated\r\nthe meeting in a manner that encouraged the sharing of information, recognized speakers in an orderly\r\nand respectful manner, assessed expectations of all parties and strived to meet those expectations\r\nwithin the limits of the meeting and comment-period time frames. Following the meeting, Dexter\r\nprovided a review of the proceedings and made recommendations for improving the multi-tribal\r\nconsultation format for future consideration by the USFWS.\r\nHomestake Mining Superfund Site Facilitation: Dexter Albert of Intrinsic was retained by EPA Region VI\r\nto co-facilitate a community meeting in Grants, New Mexico, together with Lucy Moore. The issues\r\nfacing the agencies and community were extremely complex, including a lack of safe drinking water;\r\nincreasing contamination of groundwater migrating toward municipal supplies; compromise of the\r\nimpermeable cover on the tailings pile; possible airborne contaminants; possible health conditions\r\n(cancers, birth defects) related to the Superfund site; plummeting property values and the inability to\r\nsell contaminated parcels; unclear negotiated agreements with the responsible party; and multiple\r\nsources of contamination not included in the Superfund site, but impacting residents. There existed a\r\nlong history of abuse as perceived by the community, which had often been frustrated by the reluctance\r\nof the agencies to communicate with the community and answer questions. The lay public also was\r\nunable to understand the high degree of difficult technical information related to the site. The meeting\r\nhighlighted for the agencies the importance of providing clean drinking water for the residents as soon\r\nas possible, and helped bring the resources to focus on the issue. Anecdotal evidence and evaluations\r\nshowed that community members were pleased with the degree of communication that occurred. They\r\nwere especially pleased with the way the meeting was facilitated successfully, and meeting evaluation\r\nforms suggested a high degree of satisfaction with the facilitators (average rating of 4.2 out of a scale of\r\n5). At the conclusion of the project, Dexter and Lucy prepared a report summarizing the comments\r\nheard at the meeting and providing recommendations for future steps.\r\nTRAININGS\r\nWorking with Native Communities: A Practical Guide to Better Communication: Dexter Albert has\r\noffered various iterations of this training throughout the United States during the past six years for the\r\nInternational Association of Public Participation, the Southwest Community Impact Assessment, and the\r\nUS Environmental Protection Agency, as well as annually for the past three years for Coconino County,\r\nDexter Albert Qualifications\r\nSkeo Solutions/EPA – Tribal Training Consultant\r\nPage 5\r\nArizona. Each presentation has been tailored to the area in which it was given. The presentation focuses\r\non practical advice and tips for working in and communicating with tribal communities, as well as\r\ngeneral cultural sensitivity guidance based on field experience, research and personal knowledge. The\r\nobjective is to help attendees better understand cultural differences between Native Americans and\r\nnon-Native Americans and is most beneficial for those relatively new to working with tribes in general.\r\nHowever, this interactive session is eye-opening even to the more experienced.\r\nGila River Indian Community Master Planning: Cultural Sensitivity Training: Dexter co-presented this\r\ntraining for consultants and staff members working with the Gila River Indian Community to develop\r\nMaster Plans for each of seven districts. In addition to providing practical advice and tips for working\r\nwith the Gila River Indian Community, the presentation offered specific details about the community’s\r\nhistory, structure and operations. The objective is to prepare consultants and their staff members to\r\nwork successfully with the Gila River Indian Community as they developed the Master Plans. Dexter copresented\r\nthis training with an Intrinsic partner, who is a member of Salt River Pima-Maricopa Indian\r\nCommunity as well as the Menomonee and Oneida nations of Wisconsin.\r\nTribal Mediation and Negotiation Processes: Dexter co-presented this training at the 2007 Association\r\nfor Conflict Resolution conference in Phoenix, Arizona. This presentation explores how tribes approach\r\nconflict resolution differently from other ethnic groups by focusing on the areas of Navajo social\r\nconstruct, customary governance, peacemaking and traditional problem solving. The objective is to offer\r\nparticipants insight into traditional processes, how those processes can support collaborative decisionmaking\r\nand how dispute resolution methods are driven by the cultures of the negotiating parties.\r\nThird-Party Roles in Deliberative Democracy and Consensus Building in Native American Communities:\r\nDexter co-presented this training at the 2007 Environmental and Public Policy Conflict Resolution\r\nConference in Jupiter, Florida. This presentation focuses on the decision-making process and presents a\r\ncomparison/contrast between consensus and deliberative democracy in Native American communities.\r\nThe objective is to identify how our work leading collaborative efforts and building consensus help\r\npromote deliberative democracy. We discuss Navajo Chapter Houses as the epicenter of decision\r\nmaking in Navajo Country and offer comparisons of the Chapter House meeting to the Vermont-style\r\ntown hall meeting. We describe how Chapters are the democratic focal point of Navajo communities\r\nand how the Chapter has become institutionalized in the Navajo political arena.\r\nRate Structure\r\nDexter’s rate is $115/hour for all services rendered.\r\nResume Attached\r\nDEXTER ALBERT BIOGRAPHY & RESUME\r\n928-522-6015 ? dexter@intrinsicinfo.com ? PO Box 336 ? Flagstaff, AZ 86002\r\nBiography:\r\nDexter is an experienced facilitator, community organizer, outreach specialist and event planner. He has\r\nworked on many rural and tribal relations projects in northern Arizona and the Southwest. Both clients\r\nand the public have confirmed Dexter’s superior organizational skills, as well as responsiveness and\r\nsensitivity in dealing with public concerns. He is an avid writer and strategic thinker, and he has worked\r\non many environmental, transportation and community infrastructure projects and presented at many\r\nconferences and symposia throughout the U.S.\r\nIn 1999, Dex received a B.S. in public relations from Northern Arizona University, with a minor in\r\nAmerican Indian Studies. He graduated with honors from Window Rock High School in Fort Defiance,\r\nnear the Navajo Nation capital. He also has completed coursework toward a master’s degree in applied\r\ncommunication and holds a certificate from IAP2 for public participation training.\r\nPrior to launching his own business, Dex worked extensively in public service. He was a paralegal for\r\nCoconino Legal Aid and DNA People’s Legal Services; communications assistant for the Northern\r\nArizona University Institute for Native Americans; outreach coordinator for the Welfare to Work Task\r\nForce; an assistant at Northern Arizona University for the Office of the President for Multicultural Affairs,\r\nOffice of the Dean of the College of Creative and Communication Arts, and the Career Services\r\nMulticultural Satellite Office. In addition, he was an executive assistant for Coconino County Board of\r\nSupervisors member Liz Archuleta.\r\nSpecial Skills:\r\nMULTI-TASKING. Managed numerous tasks at various levels with many daily interruptions.\r\nORGANIZATION. Organized many events and activities for diverse populations; maintained a highly\r\neffective and efficient office system; kept detailed knowledge of work-progress.\r\nWORK ETHIC. Persevered as a highly committed, results-oriented, self-motivated, detail-inclined fasttaught\r\nproblem-solver.\r\nHIGH ENERGY. Sustained a well-balanced life of full-time employment, part-time work, full-time\r\ngraduate schooling and full-time family life, with time left over still for socializing.\r\nCOMPUTERS. Gained experienced knowledge of PCs and Windows-based applications, as well as\r\nword processing, email and Internet applications; experienced with Macintosh and\r\ngraphics applications; knowledgeable of troubleshooting and advanced operations.\r\nLANGUAGE. Exercised fluent knowledge of English, semi-fluent knowledge of Navajo and\r\nknowledge of Spanish; trained to read and write Navajo language.\r\nLEADERSHIP. Served on many organizations and committees; possessed excellent communication\r\nskills and outstanding writing ability; involved with community.\r\nDEXTER ALBERT BIOGRAPHY & RESUME\r\nPage 2 of 4\r\nSTRATEGY. Demonstrated strategic outlook with a keen aptitude for tactical planning and\r\nexecution, especially while working with rural and Native American communities.\r\nACCOUNTING. Administered multiple project budgets and managed company finances and resources\r\nfor small business with $250,000 in annual revenues.\r\nEducational Background:\r\nMay 2005 -. Northern Arizona University. Flagstaff, Ariz.\r\nPresent Master of Arts Degree: APPLIED COMMUNICATION;\r\nCompleted 15+ hours toward coursework.\r\nMay 1999. Northern Arizona University. Flagstaff, Ariz.\r\nBachelor of Scien