icy for its small loan program for multifamily residential properties.\r\nSuperfund Redevelopment Initiative (SRI)\r\n•\tAssisted in evaluation of the hypothesis that reuse at cleaned-up Superfund sites can protect the remedy.  Participation included research, analysis, and writing a report outlining the methods and results.  The results of the study suggest that sites in reuse may be less prone to destructive behaviors than sites not in reuse.  There are several ways that this analysis could be expanded to give a more definitive conclusion.\r\n•\tParticipated in technical assistance for the Barker Chemical site in Inglis, Florida.  Activities involved participation in conference calls, developing and researching questions related to regulations governing real estate transactions of contaminated properties, and developing materials in support of meetings between the state of Florida, EPA, and stakeholders.\r\n•\tResearched and developed a Reuse Case Study for the Murray Machinery site in Stettin, Wisconsin.  Activities involved Web research, developing questions, conducting interviews with the EPA On Site Coordinators (OSCs), and writing the case study.  \r\n•\tResearched and developed a draft fact sheet for property owners and prospective purchasers of contaminated property addressing the tools available to deal with issues related to third party tort liability concerns.\r\n•\tResearched the use of SRI tools at Superfund Alternative Sites to evaluate the need for communications to encourage the use of these tools by those in charge of these sites.\r\n•\tProvided technical analysis for the Kansas City Structural Steel and Des Moines TCE site reuse planning processes.\r\nSuperfund Five-Year Reviews\r\n•\tAssisted with Five-Year Reviews for the Peppers Steel and Alloys, Trans Circuits, Escambia, Distler Farm, Distler Brickyard, A.L. Taylor, and T.H. Agriculture and Nutrition sites.\r\n•\tProvided technical analysis and coauthored the Five-Year Reviews for the Tower Chemical Company, Tri-City Disposal Co., Miami Drum Services, and Alpha Chemical sites.\r\nSuperfund and Removals Benefits Analyses\r\n•\tDeveloped a list of potential methods for quantifying the ecological benefits of Superfund, as part of the Superfund Benefits Analysis (SBA). \r\n•\tConducted research in support of the Removals Benefits Analysis on water contamination, heavy metal and PCB contamination in fish. \r\nPerformance Measures and Economics\r\n•\tConducted research on the HRS Rule that was used in the development of a “Populations Protected” performance measure developed for the Office of Management and Budget.\r\nInstitutional Controls (IC)\r\n•\tConducted research and analysis to help assess the status of Institutional Controls (ICs) at sites for which Ready for Reuse determinations had been issued.\r\n•\tReviewed and made suggestions for the integration of ICs into the draft directive on “Integrating Reuse Considerations into Superfund Response Actions at Fund-Lead and Private Party-Lead Sites”.  \r\n•\tAssisted with planning and on-scene organization for the 2007 Long Term Stewardship Roundtable and Training.\r\nOffice of Underground Storage Tanks (OUST)\r\n•\tServed as a Work Assignment Manager (WAM) and participated in research and analysis related to guidance document development and regulatory support for technical issues such as secondary containment, delivery prohibition, state fund soundness, state fund diversion, operator training, financial responsibility, and tribal underground storage tanks.\r\n•\tManaged all aspects of the contract, including client relationship, business development, budgeting, staffing, deliverable preparation, review, and delivery.\r\n\r\nUniversity of Virginia, Department of Environmental Sciences (7/98 to 8/04) \r\nActed as a laboratory research assistant, including maintenance and sample analysis using mass spectrometers, chemical extractions, statistical analysis, participation in fieldwork, biological sample collection and preparation, development of three grant proposals, presentations at 14 conferences, and supervision of undergraduate student research (2001 and 2003).  Served as a teaching assistant (2000 and 2001) and head teaching assistant (2003) for an introductory biology class.  Responsibilities and activities included preparing laboratory lectures and activities, preparing exams, proctoring exams, conducting office hours, and grading.  \r\n\r\nPublications and Reports\r\n\r\nKnoff, A.J., S.A. Macko, and A.A. Hohn.  2008.  Ontogenetic diet changes in bottlenose dolphins \r\n(Tursiops truncatus) reflected through stable isotopes.  Marine Mammals, accepted for publication.  \r\n\r\nKnoff, A.J., S.A. Macko, R.M. Erwin, and K.M. Brown. 2002. Stable isotope analysis of \r\ntemporal variation in the diets of pre-fledged Laughing Gulls. Waterbirds 25(2): 142-148.\r\n\r\nKnoff, A.J., S.A. Macko, and R.M. Erwin. 2001. Diets of nesting Laughing Gulls (Larus\r\natricilla) at the Virginia Coast Reserve: Observations from stable isotope analysis. Isotopes in Environmental and Health Studies 37: 67-88.  \r\n\r\n	2015-02-27 05:24:34.327425	2015-02-27 05:24:34.327425	17
