ts that reviewed more than 20 operating ground water restoration systems under the program and developed recommendations that potentially could save millions in annual operating costs while maintaining or improving environmental performance.  Directed the development of several guidance documents to help guide regional site managers to effectively operate and manage ground water restoration systems, applying lessons learned from the pilot reviews.\r\n\r\n\tProject Delivery Mechanisms – Directed the development and implementation of numerous innovative contract mechanisms used by the EPA regional offices to conduct Superfund work.  Implemented innovative approaches for contract type, size, duration, and other features to provide the flexibility needed to meet critical program needs.  Lead efforts to evaluate the performance of the contract infrastructure to ensure continuous improvement.  Directed an initiative to implement “performance based contracting” on selected Superfund cleanup construction projects.  Also served as the program lead for an interagency agreement with the US Army Corps of Engineers.  The Corps has provided critical construction management expertise to Superfund site managers for over 20 years.  They have successfully completed several billion dollars of cleanup work, and are recognized as an integral partner in the implementation of the program.\r\n\r\n1971 – 1977\tNaval Facilities Engineering Command\r\n\tU.S. Navy\r\n\t200 Stovall St\r\n\tAlexandria VA  22332\r\n\r\n\tServed as a project engineer for Navy environmental protection programs.  Procured oil spill cleanup equipment for use by naval shore installations.  Developed guidance documents on the implementation of oil spill prevention regulations.\r\n\r\nEducation\r\n\r\n1971\t\t\tB.S., Civil Engineering\r\n\t\t\tUniversity of New Hampshire\r\n\r\n1977\t\t\tMasters, Engineering Administration\r\n\t\t\tGeorge Washington University\r\n\r\nAwards\r\n\r\nU.S. EPA\t\tLee M. Thomas Excellence in