1002	James	L	Wilkinson	jwilkinson@e2inc.com	4349756700 ext. 225	4344650981	2417 Northfield Rd.		Charlottesville	VA	22903	0	Senior Associate	E2 Inc.	9	James Wilkinson is a Senior Planner with more than nine years of experience in rural community development, sustainable natural resource management, and community involvement and collaborative decision-making processes. Mr. Wilkinson leads E² Inc.’s Community Planning and Design Team, which provides technical support to communities as they generate and evaluate options for local and regional land use planning, resource restoration and conservation, and revitalization initiatives for environmentally impaired properties. Since 2001, the Team has provided technical assistance to more than 60 communities spanning nine EPA Regions nationwide. Mr. Wilkinson has visited and served as a researcher, trainer, project manager, and facilitator at most of these sites, and has authored twelve reports as part of these community-based projects.\r\n\r\nThe community restoration and revitalization projects have addressed both rural and urban areas, with a focus on opportunities for the restoration or creation of innovative recreational and ecological land uses. Each of the projects has included a significant community involvement component; many of the projects are managed by community-based committees that work with the consulting team to address potential areas of conflict and develop future land use and conservation strategies that address multiple community needs and priorities. Prior to joining E2 Inc., Mr. Wilkinson worked as a researcher at the Institute for Environmental Negotiation at the University of Virginia, as a journalist for the Northern Virginia Daily newspaper, and as a freelance editor in Washington, D.C. Mr. Wilkinson has a master’s degree in Urban and Environmental Planning from the University of Virginia, a master’s degree in American Literature from Cambridge University, and a bachelor’s degree in English and History from the College of William and Mary. \r\n\r\nSenior Associate, E² Inc. (5.5 years in position; 10 years experience in field of expertise)\r\nDescription:  Provides technical, regulatory, and policy support for major EPA contracts including community and stakeholder involvement, meeting coordination and facilitation, legislative and regulatory policy analysis, technical support, strategic planning, reuse planning, communications outreach, training and conference support, writing and editing services, and the development of decision support tools. Manages projects and work assignments.\r\n\r\n• Author, 2008 EPA Guidebook Planning for Superfund Site Reuse – a Guide for Local Governments.\r\n• Author, 16 reuse planning reports for community-based projects for EPA Regions and EPA Headquarters, 2002-2007. \r\n• Contributor, EPA Region 4 Site Reuse Fact Sheets, US EPA, January – December 2005 \r\n• Author, South Point Plant Ready for Reuse Determination, E² Inc., October 2004.\r\n• Author, Wind Energy Case Study: A Breath of Fresh Air for American’s Abandoned Mine Lands – Alternative Energy Provides A Second Wind, E² Inc., July 2003.\r\n• Author, MDI Superfund Site Case Study, E² Inc., March 2008.\r\n\r\nMr. Wilkinson has management and project experience across all task areas of the PWS, with particular emphasis on Task Areas #s 2 & 8.\r\n\r\nTask Area #2: Research and Analysis\r\n\r\n• Managed project, conducted research, developed case studies and graphics, and developed 37-page guidebook for OSRTI and SRI. EPA’s 2007 Planning for Superfund Site Reuse – a Guide for Local Governments guidebook provides a resource for local government staff and elected officials interested in Superfund site reuse.\r\n\r\n• Co-authored the Environment Chapter of the City of Charlottesville, Virginia’s 2007 Comprehensive Plan, which included consideration of local brownfields.\r\n\r\n• Authored 16 reuse planning project reports for EPA Regions, EPA Headquarters, and the Superfund Redevelopment Initiative. Reports were created for the G&H Landfill (Utica, MI), Central Chemical (Hagerstown, MD), Himco Dump (Elkhart, IN), Hudson River PCBs (Fort Edward, NY), American Creosote Works (Louisville, MS), Picayune Wood Treating (Picayune, MS), Plainwell Paper (Plainwell, MI), Scovill Industrial Landfill (Waterbury, CT), South Point Plant (South Point, OH), St. Regis Paper (Cass Lake, MN), Velsicol Chemical Corporation (St. Louis, MI), St. Louis River (Duluth, MN), Upper Tenmile Creek (Helena, MT), and Eagle Zinc (Hillsboro, IL) Superfund sites.  These planning reports were the outcome of in-depth, community-based projects that resulted in the development of site reuse plans to guide EPA’s remedial planning activities and local community planning efforts and help ensure the long-term protectiveness and stewardship of site remedies. \r\n\r\n• Conducted situation assessments and authored situation assessment reports for 13 Superfund sites, including the Rockwell International (Allegan, MI), Memorial Drive Dump (Muncie, IN), Woolfolk Chemical (Fort Valley, GA), Organic Chemicals, Inc. (Belvidere, IL), Cannon Road Drum (Social Circle, GA), Augustus Hook (Frankfort, IN), Butterworth Landfill (Grand Rapids, MI), Clare Water Supply (Clare, MI), Davis Timber Company (Hattiesburg, MS), Gilt Edge Mine (Lead, SD), Lammers Barrel (Beavercreek, OH), and North Cavalcade (Houston, TX) Superfund sites. The situation assessment reports reviewed the current remedial and reuse status of these Superfund sites, documented stakeholder concerns and priorities, and identified key site reuse considerations, including potential opportunities and limitations.\r\n\r\n• Conducted research, interviewed stakeholders, and authored in-depth (12+ page) case studies and white papers of Superfund site reuse success stories, including the Murray Smelter and California Gulch sites for OSRTI and SRI.  Also developed reports for EPA’s Abandoned Mine Lands Team focused on recreational opportunities and wind energy resources at abandoned mine lands. \r\n\r\n• Managed project, conducted research, interviewed stakeholders, and developed 40 reuse fact sheets for EPA Region 4.  The purpose of the fact sheets is to provide interested parties (community members, developers, local governments) with targeted information on a site’s potential for use.  Fact sheets included detailed case studies of sites that have successfully been returned to use in Florida.\r\n\r\n• Co-authored the 2003 Virginia Department of Emergency Management (VDEM) Hazard Mitigation Guidebook for Virginia localities as part of a collaborative project with the University of Virginia’s School of Architecture. The guidebook examined how the natural hazard mitigation planning process can be tailored to address environmentally impaired areas.\r\n\r\n• Authored the October 2004 Ready for Reuse (RfR) Determination for the South Point Plant Superfund site, the first RfR Determination for industrial site reuse issued by EPA. \r\n\r\n• Served as a primary editor for initial chapters of the Superfund Benefits Analysis (2000 – 2002) assessing the local economic benefits associated with health benefits and ecological and recreational use provided by Superfund site cleanup and reuse. \r\n\r\nTask Area #8: Strategic Planning and Community Facilitation\r\n\r\n• Managed five-person reuse planning team that has worked on more than 60 reuse planning projects for EPA Regions 1-8 and Region 10 and Headquarters from 2001-2007. Team responsibilities included program, project, and work assignment management, oversight of project resources and deliverables across multiple clients, guidance of and involvement with project research and land use analyses, community involvement and outreach, and stakeholder facilitation and conflict resolution.\r\n\r\n• Organized and co-facilitated EPA’s 2006 Sustainable Brownfields Development Quantification Strategy Meetings in Urbana, Illinois.\r\n\r\n• Presented and led panel discussion at the 2005 EPA Community Involvement Conference in Buffalo, New York. The session focused on how community involvement and planning efforts can incorporate land use planning tools within the context of reuse planning at Superfund sites.\r\n\r\n• Coordinated and facilitated 23-member Land Use Committee and community meetings, and conducted land and market analyses for reuse planning of wood treating site in support of EPA’s Land Revitalization effort for OSRTI and EPA Region 4 for the American Creosote Works Superfund site, located in Louisville, Mississippi.  Project resulted in the creation of the project’s final report: Planning for the Future: A Reuse Planning Report for the American Creosote Works Superfund Site.\r\n\r\n• Coordinated and facilitated 15-member Land Use Committee and community meetings, and conducted land and market analyses for reuse planning of wood treating site in support of EPA’s Land Revitalization effort for OSRTI and EPA Region 4 for the Picayune Wood Treating Superfund site, located in Picayune, Mississippi.  Project resulted in the creation of the project’s final report: Planning for the Future: A Reuse Planning Report for the Picayune Wood Treating Superfund Site.\r\n\r\n• Coordinated and facilitated a series of public meetings and site reuse design sessions for the Butterworth Landfill Superfund site, located in Grand Rapids, Michigan. The project involved more than 100 community members and identified opportunities for multiple recreational opportunities for the site, including soccer fields, an environmental education center, a bicycle motorcross park, model aviation flying facility, a boat launch, and walking trails.\r\n\r\n• Managed and helped design Communityplan.net: A Forum for Community-Based Future Land Use Processes. This interactive online resource provides an opportunity for community members involved in reuse planning projects at Superfund sites to access project-related information, share community documents, engage in