rojects (Concord Weapons Naval Station, Alameda Naval Air Base, McClellan AFB); technical reviews of innovative clean-up technologies (published by CPEO as the Tech Tree); assessments of  the environmental conditions of DoD bases in Panama; analysis of plutonium use at LLNL; evaluation of contamination and O&M procedures at Brownfield sites, including three New York City School sites; and, conducted numerous environmental reviews and studies on behalf of community organizations. Mr. Strauss also has provided expert witness testimony in California, Illinois, New York and New Jersey. \r\nPrior to founding PM Strauss & Associates, Mr. Strauss was the Director of Environmental Management with MHB Technical Associates in San Jose, CA.  He was the project manager for nine US EPA-sponsored Technical Assistance Grants, and performed various studies relating to toxic discharges from power plants, low-level radioactive waste, nuclear decommissioning, and storage and disposal of spent nuclear fuel.  In many cases, Mr. Strauss has been requested to evaluate the adequacy of Environmental Impact Statements.  He has conducted studies to determine financial responsibility for cleaning up contamination at over 60 manufactured gas plant sites in New Jersey and California. Mr. Strauss also has provided expert witness testimony regarding the environmental effects of large construction projects in San Francisco, Livermore and Los Angeles. Mr. Strauss also has provided expert witness testimony in California, Illinois, Pennsylvania, Vermont, Texas and New Jersey.\r\nPrior to joining MHB, Mr. Strauss assisted industrial and governmental clients to develop hazardous waste programs and environmental compliance plans. He assisted several state governments to develop hazardous waste and solid waste regulations (New Hampshire and Connecticut, advising Massachusetts). From 1981 to 1983, Mr. Strauss was a Senior Environmental Engineer with Utah International, Inc., an international mining corporation. He analyzed the effects of proposed environmental regulations on the Company and helped it be responsive to environmental regulations. \r\nFrom May 1977 through April 1980, Mr. Strauss was a consultant with Resource Planning Associates, Inc. (RPA), a management consulting firm specializing in energy, environmental policy and technology. \r\nMr. Strauss received a Bachelor of Arts Degree from the University of Wisconsin in 1970 and a Master of Science Degree in Managerial Science and Policy from the College of Environmental Science and Forestry, State University of New York in 1977.\r\nMr. Strauss is a member of the Interstate Technology and Regulatory Council (ITRC), where he was involved in the following technology teams: vapor intrusion, radionuclides, natural attenuation of inorganics, permeable reactive barriers, small arms firing ranges, constructed and mitigated wetlands, and phytoremediation. Mr. Strauss has numerous presentations on cleanup related issues before several community groups, Restoration Advisory Boards and internationally. EPA honored Tri-Valley CAREs (a client of Mr. Strauss' since 1989) in 2000 as the "Most Effective Hazardous Waste Community".  \r\n	2015-02-27 05:24:36.958224	2015-02-27 05:24:36.958224	32
