ate in Management; Mandel Fellow, Case Western Reserve University, Cleveland, OH\r\nMasters in Business Administration, University of San Francisco, San Francisco, CA\r\nMasters in Public Administration, California State University, Northridge, CA; City University of New York, Baruch College, New York, NY\r\nBachelors of Science – Communications Studies and Political Science, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL\r\n\r\n\r\nOTHER RELEVANT EXPERIENCE\r\n\r\nCredentialed as a city manager by the International City/County Management Association. Certified in civil and divorce mediation (ADR, FL).  Orally bi-lingual Spanish.\r\n\r\n\r\nPUBLICATIONS\r\n\r\nDissertation Quantitative Research: Who we are drives what we do:  The Interplay of Identity on Workplace Behaviors (July 2007); Dissertation Qualitative Research:  Employee Self-Limiting Behaviors in Non-Dominant Culture Organizations (December 2005); Public Management magazine, “Pushing Another Envelope” (June 2004); Health Issues Staff writer, City Flight magazine (various articles 2005 and 2006).\r\n\r\n\r\nMEMBERSHIPS\r\n\r\nInternational City/County Management Association (ICMA)\r\nAcademy of Management (AoM)\r\nAssociation for Research on Non-Profit Organizations and Voluntary Action (ARNOVA)\r\nThe PhD Project (KPMG)\r\n	2015-02-27 05:24:37.499915	2015-02-27 05:24:37.499915	33
1012	Steve		Ackerlund	steve.ackerlund@arcadis-us.com	406-449-7001 x 18	406-461-6354	1610 B Street		Helena	MT	59601	0	Project Scientist	ARCADIS	22	Steve Ackerlund, MS\r\nPrincipal Scientist\r\n\r\nMr. Ackerlund has more than 20 years of professional consulting experience providing technical, process and project management services for environmental projects at industrial and mining sites throughout the United States and Mexico.  He is frequently called upon to develop and negotiate cost-effective strategies for achieving environmental compliance that are tailored to site-specific, risk-based conditions and that respond to multi-stakeholder concerns.  He has also provided expert testimony in support of litigation, and he has provided testimony on a variety of State of Montana legislature and regulatory development needs. \r\n\r\nMr. Ackerlund has extensive experience in the practical application of the following laws and related regulations, particularly as they pertain to site investigation requirements, chemical cleanup level determinations, industrial wastewater discharge requirements, and the integration of these technical assessments with stakeholder involvement needs:\r\n\r\n•\tSuperfund (CERCLA), which includes Brownfields\r\n•\tResource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA), which includes underground storage tank sites and landfills\r\n•\tSafe Drinking Water Act (SDWA)\r\n•\tClean Water Act (CWA) and NPDES permitting\r\n•\tRelated laws and regulations for hazardous waste cleanup and permitting in numerous states\r\n\r\nProcess Management and Stakeholder Involvement\r\n\r\nVoluntary Remediation Work Plans, Risk Assessment, and Remedy Development\r\nSinclair Oil, Sinclair, Wyoming\r\nOngoing, Project Cost: $200,000 (Mr. Ackerlund’s fees only)\r\nProvided strategic project direction, report writing skills, and risk assessment and regulatory compliance expertise for an RFI at an active oil refinery.  Common contaminants among the 35 SWMUs and areas of concern include various historical petroleum by-products and possibly metals.  After Sinclair struggled for several years to move the project forward with the Wyoming DEQ, Mr. Ackerlund was hired to augment the existing team of consultants.  Working closely with Sinclair, Mr. Ackerlund has assisted in advancing a novel, cost-effective investigation and remedy under Wyoming’s Voluntary Cleanup Program.  Tasks completed include: preparing a Framework Plan to guide the multi-year effort, preparing human health and environmental risk screening reports to prioritize various elements of this large project, preparing data collection work plans, preparing an integrated remedy evaluation report and site-specific, post-remedy risk assessment.  Project work has involved extensive support in establishing a collaborative process that has allowed for effective negotiations and ultimately successful forward progress with the investigation.\r\n\r\nTechnical Assistance Grant Advisor for Superfund Project\r\nRimini Community Inc., Lewis and Clark County, Montana\r\n2007, Project Cost: $120,000\r\nServed as the technical advisor for Rimini community residents regarding the Upper Tenmile watershed investigation and remediation.  This highly contested Superfund project involved:  remediation and reclamation of numerous historic mines and affected drainages, residential yard remediation of historic mine tailings, development of alternative drinking water supply and development of a community wastewater system.  Tasks included responding to residents’ technical questions, developing a strategic plan for multi-stakeholder engagement, assisting in multi-party negotiations with USEPA, Montana DEQ, Lewis and Clark County and other stakeholders, facilitating meetings and discourse within the community, and supporting public relations efforts of the community.  The project culminated in a collaborative Joint Fact Finding approach, conceived and facilitated by Mr. Ackerlund, which achieved multi-stakeholder consensus regarding the final remedies.\r\n\r\nAir Quality Permitting for Combustion of Tire-Derived Fuel\r\nMontana Department of Environmental Quality, Trident, Montana\r\n2007, Project Cost: $80,000 (Mr. Ackerlund’s fees only)\r\nHolcim seeks air quality permit amendments to use tire-derived fuel to augment fuel supplies to a cement kiln.  Initially provided review of the permit application and risk assessment completed by Holcim contractors.  The project subsequently underwent an environmental impact statement (EIS), funded by the DEQ, in response to substantial expressed public concern.  Primary responsibilities included preparing a risk assessment addressing baseline and cumulative impacts associated with future potential exposure to Hazardous Air Pollutants (HAPs) associated with the use of tire-derived fuel.  The risk assessment responded to numerous public concerns, such as potentially contaminated food ingestion pathways.  Mr. Ackerlund also provided risk communication support, attended public hearings regarding the draft EIS for which the risk assessment serves as an appendix, and is ultimately expected to provide expert testimony in the event of a lawsuit.\r\n\r\nAbandoned Mine Investigations, Risk Assessment and Risk Communication\r\nUSDA Forest Service, Northern Region, Missoula, Montana\r\n2006, Project Cost: $60,000\r\nSupported development of a public risk communication plan and supported the Forest Service in its negotiations with a mining company regarding site remediation needs.  Completed a human health and ecological risk assessment of radionuclide and metals contamination resulting from historic uranium mines in South Dakota.  Risk assessment results were presented at public meetings.  Other project work elements involved evaluating existing data completeness for risk assessment use, work plan development, and field work oversight.\r\n\r\nBrownfields Site Assessment and Public Risk Communication\r\nCity and County of Missoula, Montana\r\n2003, Project Cost: $80,000\r\nUnder a USEPA Brownfields grant, prepared a work plan, managed data collection activities, prepared a site characterization report and provided expert support as a toxicologist for a public hearing.  The site involved historic releases of dioxin and pentachlorophenol from a wood treatment facility in residential areas.  Data were collected in residential soils, community groundwater supply wells and indoor dust.  Considerable one-on-one communications with residents was required to achieve private property access and otherwise earn resident trust that the issue was being properly addressed.  The results were used by the Montana DEQ to complete an HHRA.\r\n\r\nActive Mine Water Quality Compliance Plan\r\nZortman Mining Inc., Zortman, Montana\r\n1997, Project Cost: $400,000 (planning and engineering only)\r\nServed as project manager for a multi-year, negotiated effort to prepare a Compliance Plan for achieving compliance with Montana water quality regulations and obtaining a discharge permit from the Montana DEQ.  The plan used extensive existing information to conduct compliance evaluations and identify engineering design, construction, water quality monitoring and water quality standards development tasks needed to achieve compliance.  This highly controversial project involved mine related water discharges of varying sources and quality into seven drainages.  The mine bordered native lands.  Extensive negotiations with multiple state, federal and tribal entities were required to successfully develop this framework strategy for achieving compliance.\r\n\r\nMine Permitting and Historic Mine Remediation\r\n\r\nAbandoned Mine Lands Risk Assessment\r\nUpper Blackfoot Mining Complex, Lincoln, Montana\r\n2007, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nProvided human health and ecological risk assessment support in accordance with the Montana DEQ Risk-Based Cleanup Guidelines for Abandoned Mine Sites.  The assessment addressed mine tailings, waste rock and impacted soils within the flood plain of the headwaters of the Blackfoot River.  Multiple types of recreational uses that are specific to the area were evaluated.  The risk assessment was performed in support of an engineering evaluation/cost analysis (EE/CA) that addressed the removal of substantial amounts of the abandoned mine materials.\r\n\r\nAbandoned Mine Investigations, Risk Assessment and Risk Communication\r\nUSDA Forest Service, Northern Region, Missoula, Montana\r\n2006, Project Cost: $60,000\r\nSupported development of a public risk communication plan, and has supported the Forest Service in its negotiations with a mining company regarding site remediation needs.  Completed a human health and ecological risk assessment of radionuclide and metals contamination resulting from historic uranium mines in South Dakota.  Risk assessment results were presented at public meetings.  Other project work elements involved evaluating existing data completeness for risk assessment use, work plan development, and field work oversight.\r\n\r\nGem Portal Mine Drainage Streamlined Risk Evaluation\r\nProject Client: ASARCO Incorporated, Wallace, Idaho\r\n2005, Project Cost: $5,000\r\nCompleted a streamlined human health and ecological risk assessment of untreated and treated mine audit drainage as part of an EE/CA report. The EE/CA evaluated numerous options for treating acid mine drainage from the historic Gem Portal.\r\n\r\n303(d) De-Listing\r\nTroy Mine, Kalispell, Montana\r\n1997, Project Cost: $10,000\r\nEvaluated existing water quality information for a 303(d)-listed stream and prepared the necessary documents for submittal to MDEQ to demonstrate that the water body was not “water quality limited” so that it would be removed from the 303(d) list and not be subject to TMDL requirements.\r\n\r\nHistoric Mine Site Characterization\r\nHeritage Minerals Inc., Lakehurst New Jersey\r\n2002, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nPrepared a site characterization report in general accordance with the NJDEP (1999) Site Remediation Program, Technical Requirements for Site Remediation.  The primary objective was to define the nature and extent of any soil, stormwater and groundwater quality criteria exceedances at the site and evaluate if remedial actions were needed.  Contaminants of concern included PCBs, fuel residuals and metals.\r\n\r\nEnvironmental Information Document\r\nRed Dog Mine, Kotzebue, Alaska\r\n1998, Project Cost: $70,000\r\nServed as project manager for one of several consultant companies teaming on the project in the development of the environmental information document.  The document was completed using an EIS framework, and was prepared to support the USEPA in NPDES permit re-issuance actions for the mine.  Major sections completed included water quality, soils, erosion and reclamation.  Additionally, managed the preparation of a water balance report, which statistically evaluated the potential for tailings pond overflow under various discharge flow scenarios.\r\n\r\nHuman Health and Environmental Risk Assessment\r\nMontana Tunnels Mining Inc. (MTMI), Jefferson City, Montana\r\n1998, Project Cost: 40,000\r\nUnder the State of Montana Voluntary Cleanup and Redevelopment Act (VCRA), prepared a human health and environmental risk assessment for historic abandoned mine tailings on property now owned by MTMI.  The risk assessment was part of an overall remediation proposal, and established a range of post-remediation surface soil concentrations, based on a review of cleanup levels proposed for other similar sites throughout the nation.  Receptors of concern included on-site trespassers, off-site residents, effects on aquatic life in Corbin Creek, and terrestrial flora and fauna.  Acceptance of the assessment was facilitated through a series of negotiating meetings with the State of Montana.\r\n\r\nWater Quality Compliance Plan\r\nZortman Mining Inc., Zortman, Montana\r\n1997, Project Cost: $400,000\r\nServed as project manager for a multi-year effort to prepare a Compliance Plan for achieving compliance with Montana water quality regulations and obtaining a discharge permit from the Montana DEQ.  The plan outlined design, construction, water quality monitoring and water quality standards development tasks.  The construction tasks were designed to improve the quality of water released from the site.  The monitoring tasks described surface water monitoring requirements during construction of various water management facilities, and evaluated compliance with water quality standards.  Tasks related to standards development included metals bioavailability studies, stream biosurveys, use attainability studies and water effect ratio studies.  These studies were intended to form the basis for site-specific MPDES water quality standards.\r\n\r\nHazard Ranking System Evaluation\r\nCrown Butte Mines, Inc., Cooke City, Montana\r\n1998, Project Cost: $10,000\r\nEvaluated the possibility of an abandoned mine becoming a Superfund site.  The site was evaluated using the USEPA’s PRESCORE software for calculating hazard ranking system (HRS) scores.  Evaluation results were used to supply the property owner with information on the types of mitigation procedures that could be performed to reduce USEPA’s future HRS score, and thereby reduce the likelihood of the site receiving Superfund status.\r\n\r\nCorbin Flats Abandoned Mine Tailings Remediation\r\nMontana Tunnels, Jefferson City, Montana\r\n1998, Project Cost: $40,000\r\nUnder the Montana Voluntary Cleanup and Redevelopment Act (VCRA), participated in the development of work plans for the remediation and reclamation of the Corbin Flats abandoned mine tailings site.  The plan provided for consolidation of tailings into a reclaimed repository and redevelopment of the Corbin Creek stream channel.  Specific responsibilities included development of excavation cleanup levels protective of human health and the environment.\r\n\r\nDevelopment of Storm Water Management Plans and Sampling and Analysis Plans\r\nZortman Mining Inc., Zortman, Montana\r\n1997, Project Cost: $35,000\r\nManaged the preparation of a stormwater management plan for a large hard rock open pit mine site.  The plan specified best management practices, as well as plans for records management, monitoring, personnel training, annual site surveys, etc.  The SAP identified water quality and flow data collection procedures at storm water discharges, mine drainage discharges, groundwater compliance points, and ambient (in-stream) monitoring points.\r\n\r\nDevelopment of Site-Specific Water Quality Standards\r\nZortman Mining Inc., Zortman, Montana\r\n1997, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nPrepared a work plan for developing site-specific water quality standards for incorporation into an MPDES permit.  The plan provided for the collection of background water quality data, proposed models for calculating background water quality, and proposed studies for establishing concentrations protective of aquatic life.\r\n\r\nDesign of Water Quality Improvement Facilities\r\nZortman Mining Inc., Zortman, Montana\r\n1998, Project Cost: $100,000\r\nProvided project management for the design of numerous water quality improvement facilities in seven drainages, including capture ponds, pumps, ditches, and treatment plants, to ensure designs would achieve water quality improvement objectives.\r\n\r\nRisk Assessment\r\n\r\nOil Refinery Risk Assessment in Support of Commercial Redevelopment\r\nFormer CENCO Refinery, Santa Fe Springs, California\r\n2008, Project Cost: $50,000\r\nLead the preparation of a human health risk assessment for a former oil refinery in support of property redevelopment plans.  The assessment was conducted in accordance with the requirements of the Los Angeles Regional Water Quality Board, California EPA Department of Toxic Substances Control (DTSC) and Human and Ecological Risk Division (HERD).  On-site exposure focused on commercial use scenario and future potential leaching to groundwater.  Off-site residential exposure was also evaluated.  An aggressive schedule was maintained to meet property redevelopment construction schedules.\r\n\r\nRailyard Risk Assessment and Expert Witness Support\r\nTrinity Railcar Inc., Miles City, Montana\r\n2007, Project Cost: $30,000\r\nThe Miles City railyard has a long history of use that has left the site contaminated by lead, petroleum products and possibly other contaminants.  Sandblasting operations resulted in elevated lead concentrations in surface soil, and multiple leaks and spills resulted in soil and groundwater contamination by diesel.  Responsibility for cleanup was litigated between multiple prior owners.  Mr. Ackerlund was retained as a subcontractor to provide risk assessment support and expert witness services for Trinity.  Areas of support included: scoping the magnitude of the problem, identifying immediate data collection needs identifying likely remedies, and assisting legal staff with deposition preparation.  Trinity prevailed, and subsequent work was completed to scope the risk assessment. \r\n\r\nAbandoned Mine Lands Risk Assessment\r\nUpper Blackfoot Mining Complex, Lincoln, Montana\r\n2007, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nProvided human health and ecological risk assessment support in accordance with the Montana DEQ Risk-Based Cleanup Guidelines for Abandoned Mine Sites.  The assessment addressed mine tailings, waste rock and impacted soils within the flood plain of the headwaters of the Blackfoot River.  Multiple types of recreational uses that are specific to the area were evaluated.  The risk assessment was performed in support of an engineering evaluation/cost analysis (EE/CA) that addressed the removal of substantial amounts of the abandoned mine materials.\r\n\r\nHuman Health and Ecological Risk Assessment for Combustion of Tire-Derived Fuel\r\nMontana Department of Environmental Quality, Trident, Montana\r\n2007, Project Cost: $80,000\r\nMontana Department of Environmental Quality, Trident, Montana\r\n2007, Project Cost: $80,000 (Mr. Ackerlund’s fees only)\r\nHolcim seeks air quality permit amendments to use tire-derived fuel to augment fuel supplies to a cement kiln.  Initially provided review of the permit application and risk assessment completed by Holcim contractors.  The project subsequently underwent an environmental impact statement (EIS), funded by the DEQ, in response to substantial expressed public concern.  Primary responsibilities included preparing a risk assessment addressing baseline and cumulative impacts associated with future potential exposure to Hazardous Air Pollutants (HAPs) associated with the use of tire-derived fuel.  The risk assessment responded to numerous public concerns, such as potentially contaminated food ingestion pathways.  Mr. Ackerlund also provided risk communication support, attended public hearings regarding the draft EIS for which the risk assessment serves as an appendix, and is ultimately expected to provide expert testimony in the event of a lawsuit.\r\n\r\nAbandoned Mine Investigations, Risk Assessment and Risk Communication\r\nUSDA Forest Service, Northern Region, Missoula, Montana\r\n2006, Project Cost: $60,000\r\nSupported development of a public risk communication plan, and has supported the Forest Service in its negotiations with a mining company regarding site remediation needs.  Completed a human health and ecological risk assessment of radionuclide and metals contamination resulting from historic uranium mines in South Dakota.  Risk assessment results were presented at public meetings.  Other project work elements involved evaluating existing data completeness for risk assessment use, work plan development, and field work oversight.\r\n\r\nMixed Low-level Waste Risk Assessment\r\nPacific Ecosolutions (PEcoS), Richland, Washington\r\n2006, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nProvided strategic direction in the development of a rationale for meeting risk assessment needs of a thermal treatment facility to be operated at a DOE facility.  The risk assessment supported a Phase I Permit Modification Request (PMR) for a mixed low-level waste (MLLW) thermal treatment facility owned by PEcoS, which requested an expedited review, comment and approval of the rationale prior to proceeding with more detailed analysis. The proposed approach made extensive use of previously conducted risk assessment work to provide an effective and streamlined process for meeting risk assessment needs.\r\n\r\nGem Portal Mine Drainage Streamlined Risk Evaluation\r\nProject Client: ASARCO Incorporated, Wallace, Idaho\r\n2005, Project Cost: $5,000\r\nCompleted a streamlined human health and ecological risk assessment of untreated and treated mine audit drainage as part of an EE/CA report. The EE/CA evaluated numerous options for treating acid mine drainage from the historic Gem Portal.\r\n\r\nBrownfields Risk Assessment and Regulatory Compliance\r\nLower Brule Sioux Tribe (LBST), South Dakota\r\n2005, Project Cost: $50,000\r\nProvided quality assurance review of risk-based cleanup goals and regulatory standards applicable to the cleanup of a historic, unlined municipal-type landfill.  The project was supported by an EPA Brownfields Assessment Grant.\r\n\r\nMultiple Risk Assessment Review at Missile Launch Facilities\r\nAir Force Center for Environmental Excellence, Vandenberg AFB, California\r\n2006, Project Cost: $90,000\r\nConducted third-party review of site characterization and human health and ecological risk assessments for numerous Remedial Facility Investigation (RFI) project sites at the base.  Common contaminants included metals, petroleum-related contaminants and trichloroethylene. Also providing strategic direction and supporting regulatory negotiations for projects entering into the feasibility study phase.\r\n\r\nMultiple Risk Assessments and an RFI Risk Assessment at a Refinery\r\nExxonMobil, Billings, Montana\r\n1994, Project Cost: $30,000\r\nProvided risk-based human health and ecological assessments in support of site investigation reports for several solid waste management units (SWMUs).  Also at the refinery, under RCRA, provided statistical data interpretations and prepared a Phase I preliminary health and environmental assessment (HEA).  Also prepared Phase II work plans including the health and environmental assessment work plan, the sampling and analysis work plan, and the quality assurance project plan.\r\n\r\nHuman Health Risk Assessment at Zinc and Copper Smelters\r\nIndustrial Minera Mexico, San Louis Potosi, Mexico\r\n2001, Project Cost: $25,000\r\nCompleted an HHRA to meet the requirements of PROFEPA but in general accordance with USEPA guidelines.  The assessment addressed on-site and residential off-site risks from exposure to sulfur dioxide, arsenic, lead, copper and zinc.  The sources of these elements are fugitive and stack emissions.\r\n\r\nEast Helena Residential Risk Reassessment\r\nASARCO Incorporated, East Helena, Montana\r\n1998, Project Cost: $5,000\r\nPrepared an HHRA in response to a revised USEPA Administration Order on Consent (AOC) regarding remediation plans and schedules. The assessment addressed arsenic, cadmium and lead in air and residential soils.\r\n\r\nBaseline Risk Assessment for Refueling Facility\r\nMalmstrom AFB, Montana\r\n2002, Project Cost: $75,000\r\nCompleted data collection work plans and a baseline risk assessment, and evaluated risks for various remediation options identified in a feasibility study for a former airplane refueling underground storage tank (UST) site.  The work was completed in accordance with the newly developed risk-based Corrective Action guidance document prepared by the Montana DEQ.\r\n\r\nRisk Assessments at Two Zinc Smelters\r\nASARCO Incorporated, Kusa and Henryetta, Oklahoma\r\n 2001, Project Cost: $25,000\r\nCompleted risk assessments for these historic zinc smelters in accordance with a voluntary cleanup action regulated by the Oklahoma Department of Environmental Quality.  Also supported negotiations with the agencies regarding acceptable cleanup requirements.\r\n\r\nRisk Assessment at Copper Smelter\r\nASARCO Incorporated, El Paso, Texas\r\n1998, Project Cost: $25,000\r\nCompleted a risk assessment under State of Texas Risk Reduction Rules to establish initial remedial objectives at the end of Phase I of an RFI.  Parameters of concern were arsenic and other metals.  The investigation included both on-site workers and off-site residents and workers.  Substantial ongoing risk assessment and site investigation services have been provided in support of numerous residential and on-site environmental needs.  Also supported negotiations with the agencies regarding acceptable cleanup requirements.\r\n\r\nRisk-Based Corrective Action\r\nASARCO Incorporated, El Paso, Texas\r\n1997, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nCompleted two Risk-Based Corrective Action (RBCA) reports of fuel contamination of groundwater in accordance with Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission (TNRCC) requirements.  Site closures were achieved.\r\n\r\nRisk Assessment at Lead Smelter\r\nASARCO Incorporated, Murray, Utah\r\n1996, Project Cost: $20,000\r\nProvided review of risk assessment work completed by the USEPA for a former lead smelter in the Salt Lake City area.  Documents reviewed included:  Baseline Risk Assessment for the Murray Smelter Superfund Site - Site Wide Evaluation; Baseline Risk Assessment for the Murray Smelter Superfund Site - Streamlined Evaluation of Risks to Workers at the Proposed Murray Police Training Facility; and Bioavailability of Lead in Slag and Soil Samples from the Murray Smelter Superfund Site.  These assessments were done to identify media and exposure pathways of concern.  Under the EE/CA framework, a mediated process was used to expeditiously establish remedial objectives to protect human health and the environment.  As part of the comments, Monte Carlo and other more sophisticated risk assessment methods were proposed as an alternative to the point estimate method selected by the USEPA.\r\n\r\nRisk Assessment Expert Witness Services\r\nYellow Bay, Flathead Lake, Montana\r\n1995, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nEvaluated long-term health risks to residents from residual levels of gasoline in soil and groundwater spilled from a tanker truck, and served as an expert witness in a jury trial.\r\n\r\nHuman Health and Environmental Risk Assessment\r\nMontana Tunnels Mining Inc. (MTMI), Jefferson City, Montana\r\n1998, Project Cost: 40,000\r\nUnder the State of Montana Voluntary Cleanup and Redevelopment Act (VCRA), prepared a human health and environmental risk assessment for historic abandoned mine tailings on property now owned by MTMI.  The risk assessment was part of an overall remediation proposal, and established a range of post-remediation surface soil concentrations, based on a review of cleanup levels proposed for other similar sites throughout the nation.  Receptors of concern included on-site trespassers, off-site residents, effects on aquatic life in Corbin Creek, and terrestrial flora and fauna.  Acceptance of the assessment was facilitated through a series of negotiating meetings with the State of Montana.\r\n\r\nHuman Health Risk Assessment at a Superfund Site\r\nASARCO Incorporated, Amarillo, Texas\r\n1994, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nPrepared the HHRA to support the selection of the preferred alternative as part of the feasibility study at this CERCLA site, a refinery.  Future potential on-site and off-site risks to residents were evaluated based on estimated exposures to trace metals in surface soil. The risk assessment methods used were based in part on Texas Risk Reduction Rules.\r\n\r\nStatistical Data Evaluation for a Risk Assessment at Lead Refinery\r\nASARCO Incorporated, East Helena, Montana\r\n1992, Project Cost: $20,000\r\nProvided data management and statistical data evaluations for a risk assessment of residential exposure to trace metals in surface soil.  Data evaluations were performed using concentrations measured in approximately 1,000 residential yards.  Also provided peer review of the risk assessment completed using the data.\r\n\r\nHuman Health and Environmental Risk Evaluation\r\nHelena Landfill, Helena, Montana\r\n1996, Project Cost: $10,000\r\nPerformed an evaluation of potential risks to human health and the environment from exposures to a volatile organic chemical in groundwater.  The evaluation was used in part to develop a regulatory compliance strategy for the landfill, which relied on institutional controls.  The evaluation was conducted in accordance with Montana solid waste landfill regulations. A public meeting was held to explain the project and obtain feedback.\r\n\r\nData Evaluations and Human and Ecological Risk Assessment\r\nAnchor Glass, Antioch, California\r\n1992, Project Cost: $25,000\r\nProvided data evaluations and completed a human and ecological risk assessment for an unlined landfill site.  Both chemical and bioassay data were used to evaluate risks to humans on site and to sensitive environmental receptors in an adjacent wetland.  The risk assessment was undertaken as an independent action designed to reduce the total volume of soil and groundwater that would require remediation.  While regulators were asking for cleanup to background concentrations, the risk assessment was able to demonstrate that remediation to background concentrations was not necessary for protection of human health and the environment.\r\n\r\nHuman Health and Ecological Risk Evaluation\r\nFred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center, Seattle, Washington\r\n1991, Project Cost: $10,000\r\nEvaluated the potential human health and aquatic hazards associated with trace metal and fuel contamination of soil and groundwater at a proposed construction site.\r\n\r\nCERCLA Human Health and Ecological Risk Assessment\r\nU.S. Navy, Seattle, Washington\r\n1991, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nPrepared an HHRA and ERA in accordance with CERCLA guidelines, which formed part of a larger RI/FS report.  The RI/FS addressed ordinance chemicals in groundwater, which had migrated more than 3/4 of a mile from the point of release in a surface impoundment.\r\n\r\nRemedial Investigation\r\nVoluntary Remediation Work Plans, Risk Assessment, and Remedy Development\r\nSinclair Oil, Sinclair, Wyoming\r\nOngoing, Project Cost: $200,000\r\nProviding strategic project direction, report writing skills, and risk assessment and regulatory compliance expertise for an RFI at an active oil refinery.  Common contaminants among the 35 SWMUs and areas of concern include various historical petroleum by-products and possibly metals.  After Sinclair struggled for several years to negotiate an acceptable approach to move the project forward with the Wyoming DEQ, Mr. Ackerlund was hired to augment the existing team of consultants.  Working closely with Sinclair, Mr. Ackerlund has assisted in advancing a novel, cost-effective investigation and remedy under Wyoming’s Voluntary Cleanup Program.  Tasks completed or in progress include: preparing a Framework Plan to guide the multi-year effort, preparing human health and environmental risk screening reports to prioritize various elements of this large project, preparing data collection work plans, preparing a site-specific risk assessment and a remedy evaluation report.  Project work has involved extensive support in establishing a collaborative process that has allowed for effective negotiations and ultimately successful forward progress with the investigation.\r\n\r\nBrownfields Site Assessment and Public Risk Communication\r\nCity and County of Missoula, Montana\r\n2003, Project Cost: $80,000\r\nUnder a USEPA Brownfields grant, prepared a work plan, managed data collection activities, prepared a site characterization report and provided expert support as a toxicologist for a public hearing.  The site involved historic releases of dioxin and pentachlorophenol from a wood treatment facility in residential areas.  Data were collected in residential soils, community groundwater supply wells and indoor dust.  Considerable one-on-one communications with residents was required to achieve private property access and otherwise earn resident trust that the issue was being properly addressed.  The results were used by the Montana DEQ to complete an HHRA.\r\n\r\nBrownfield Site Characterization Review and Oversight\r\nASARCO Incorporated, Murray, Utah\r\n1996, Project Cost: $10,000\r\nProvided oversight and peer review of data collection, data reporting and data interpretation tasks for a large Brownfield redevelopment site regulated under CERCLA.  The reviews were intended to ensure that the site characterization work supported a comprehensive human health and environmental risk assessment conducted by the USEPA.  Also provided review of the feasibility study to ensure that the proposed remedies were protective of human health and the environment.\r\n\r\nGroundwater Monitoring\r\nMalmstrom AFB, Great Falls, Montana\r\n2004, Project Cost: $25,000\r\nServed as project manager for a groundwater sampling project at a historic UST site on base.  Prepared a data summary report with recommendations for additional sampling.\r\n\r\nSite Characterization and Water Treatment Evaluation\r\nAlpha Explosives, Lincoln, California\r\n2003, Project Cost: $120,000\r\nProvided project leadership and coordination of site investigation and groundwater treatment evaluations for a site impacted by nitrates and perchlorate.  Activities included bench-test treatability studies, groundwater quality studies, hydrogeologic site characterization, pilot-scale in-situ treatability studies and regulatory interface.\r\n\r\nHistoric Mine Site Characterization\r\nHeritage Minerals Inc., Lakehurst New Jersey\r\n2002, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nPrepared a site characterization report in general accordance with the NJDEP (1999) Site Remediation Program, Technical Requirements for Site Remediation.  The primary objective was to define the nature and extent of any soil, stormwater and groundwater quality criteria exceedances at the site and evaluate if remedial actions were needed.  Contaminants of concern included PCBs, fuel residuals and metals.\r\n\r\nSite Characterization and Remediation Plans\r\nBurlington Northern Railroad, Spokane, Washington\r\n1996, Project Cost: $30,000\r\nProvided peer review of site characterization results and plans for remediating a site prior to a property transfer.  The site contained PCBs, volatile organics and metals.  The review evaluated the adequacy of the site characterization for supporting excavation and disposal plans, and identified regulatory requirements and standards for both soils remaining on-site and soils to be landfilled.\r\n\r\nSite Characterization and Soils Treatability Work Plans\r\nASARCO Incorporated, Omaha, Nebraska\r\n1999, Project Cost: $20,000\r\nPrepared sampling and analysis plans (SAP) to identify the degree and extent of metals contamination in soils and groundwater at a lead refinery.  Prepared work plans for evaluating the feasibility of using lime and/or cement additions to soil to reduce the environmental mobility of metals in soils.\r\n\r\nSite Investigation Work Plans\r\nASARCO Incorporated, Amarillo, Texas\r\n1999, Project Cost: $10,000\r\nPrepared a SAP for evaluating metal and organic chemical concentrations in surface soil in accordance with RCRA regulations.\r\n\r\nData Evaluation and Data Collection Plan\r\nHelena Landfill, Helena, Montana\r\n1995, Project Cost: $30,000\r\nProvided statistical evaluations of groundwater data for the landfill in accordance with 1993 amendments to Montana’s Solid Waste Management regulations.  Both parametric and non-parametric procedures were used to perform the statistical evaluations in conformance with both RCRA and State of Montana regulations and guidance.  Subsequent to the evaluation, a monitoring plan was prepared to provide data on metals and organic chemical concentrations in groundwater, in accordance with the Solid Waste Management regulatory requirements.\r\n\r\nMonitoring Plan to Support Remediation\r\nASARCO Incorporated, East Helena, Montana\r\n1998, Project Cost: $12,000\r\nCompleted a groundwater monitoring plan to monitor water quality during remediation of lake sediments, and to demonstrate compliance with cleanup concentrations specified in the USEPA record of decision.  Also responsible for ensuring proper implementation of the monitoring plan, including taking corrective actions to ensure data generated was of acceptable quality.\r\n\r\nRFI Work Plan for a Wood Treatment Facility\r\nPacific Wood Treatment Corporation, Ridgefield, Washington\r\n1992, Project Cost: $25,000\r\nWrote a Quality Assurance Project Plan (QAPP) and Risk Assessment Work Plan for a RCRA feasibility study at a wood treatment facility.\r\n\r\nData Quality Review of Data Collected at Multiple Abandoned Mine and Smelting Sites\r\nARCO, Butte, Montana\r\n1993, Project Cost: $150,000\r\nCompleted contract laboratory program (CLP) data validation under CERCLA for an abandoned mine site.  Interpreted chemistry data collected at an abandoned mine site based on statistical evaluations.  Completed a background comparison evaluation for metals in soil and groundwater using statistical methods.  Provided recommendations on chemical laboratory selection and methods of chemical analysis.\r\n\r\nSoil Remediation Plan\r\nBurlington Northern Railroad, Seattle, Washington\r\n1992, Project Cost: $40,000\r\nPrepared a sampling plan and budget to determine the extent of lead-contaminated soil.  Managed field sampling and analysis activities during site investigations and during soil removal and remediation activities.  Prepared the final closure report.\r\n\r\nMarine Sediment Investigation\r\nPort of Seattle, Seattle, Washington\r\n1991, Project Cost: $70,000\r\nInvestigated marine sediment quality at a site in Puget Sound in accordance with Puget Sound Dredged Disposal Analysis (PSSDA) regulations.  Provided interpretations of chemical analyses and bioassays, and determined the volume of soil required for remediation.\r\n\r\nSite Investigations and Determination of Cleanup Levels\r\nVarious Clients, Seattle, Washington\r\n1992, Project Cost: $Not Applicable\r\nCompleted data evaluations using geostatistical, parametric, and non-parametric statistical methods at numerous landfill sites, UST sites, sediment contamination sites and groundwater contamination sites.  Determined chemical cleanup levels in accordance with Washington State Model Toxic Contract Act risk-based procedures for more than 10 sites throughout Washington.  Provided data quality assurance/quality control  (QA/QC) reviews of laboratory results for numerous chemistry investigations.\r\n\r\nSampling and Analysis Plans\r\nU.S. Army Corps of Engineers, Anchorage, Alaska\r\n1989\r\nPrepared more than 20 SAPs for investigating hazardous waste contamination.  Developed technical procedures for the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers Alaska District’s first hazardous waste remediation contract under the Defense Environmental Restoration Account.\r\n\r\nPermitting\r\nAir Quality Permitting for Combustion of Tire-Derived Fuel\r\nMontana Department of Environmental Quality, Trident, Montana\r\n2007, Project Cost: $80,000 (Mr. Ackerlund’s fees only)\r\nHolcim seeks air quality permit amendments to use tire-derived fuel to augment fuel supplies to a cement kiln.  Initially provided review of the permit application and risk assessment completed by Holcim contractors.  The project subsequently underwent an environmental impact statement (EIS), funded by the DEQ, in response to substantial expressed public concern.  Primary responsibilities included preparing a risk assessment addressing baseline and cumulative impacts associated with future potential exposure to Hazardous Air Pollutants (HAPs) associated with the use of tire-derived fuel.  The risk assessment responded to numerous public concerns, such as potentially contaminated food ingestion pathways.  Mr. Ackerlund also provided risk communication support, attended public hearings regarding the draft EIS for which the risk assessment serves as an appendix, and is ultimately expected to provide expert testimony in the event of a lawsuit.\r\n\r\nSafe Drinking Water Act Review\r\nRhone-Poulenc Basic Chemicals Company, Butte, Montana\r\n1997, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nCompleted a review of Safe Drinking Water Act requirements applicable to the Silver Bow facility.  Also provided a microbiological monitoring plan for the site’s drinking water supplies.\r\n\r\nIndustrial Wastewater Treatment\r\nTreatment of Oil Field Produced Water\r\nStocker Resources, California\r\n2002, Project Cost: $70,000\r\nServed as the sales manager in the identification and development of this project.  The project piloted a patented High Efficiency Reverse Osmosis (HERO) system to treat wastewater from an oil field in southern California.  The objective was to recover more than 80% of the water for discharge or agricultural reuse.  The reject stream is to be reinjected to support existing steam flood operations.  The water is high in silica, oil and grease, and other potential membrane foulants.  The water also contained high boron that must be removed to low levels for agricultural reuse, but has poor rejection using traditional RO methods.  A bench scale test was conducted previously, which met project objectives.\r\n\r\nTreatment of Coal Bed Methane Produced Water\r\nJ.M. Huber Corporation and Crestone Energy, Price, Utah\r\n2002, Project Cost: $120,000\r\nServed as the sales manager in the identification and development of this project, which successfully operated a HERO pilot system treating coal bed methane produced water for two months in the Price, Utah region.  The water has high hardness, TDS, oil and grease, coal fines, iron and other problematic parameters.  There are limited existing deep-well wastewater disposal facilities in this area.  The test objective was to demonstrate that HERO could operate efficiently without membrane failure, provide water for discharge, and provide a reject stream amenable to deep-well disposal.  The system demonstrated that dramatically reduced water management and disposal costs could be achieved, while providing high-quality water.  Hydrometrics had previously completed bench-scale treatment of wastewater from this site.\r\n\r\nTreatment of Metal Finishing Wastewater\r\nHoneywell, Kansas City, Missouri\r\n2003, Project Cost: $40,000\r\nServed as the sales manager in the identification and development of this project, which piloted the HERO process on pre- and post-clarified water from the Honeywell facility.  This facility includes a large and diverse metal finishing operation associated with manufacture of military defense systems.  The wastewater was principally from rinsing operations, with a smaller component being process waste.  The test objective was to demonstrate that HERO could achieve 95% recovery of wastewater, provide high-purity water for reuse, and produce a reject stream meeting sewer disposal requirements.  Hydrometrics had previously completed bench-scale testing.\r\n\r\nTreatment of Coal Bed Methane Produced Water\r\nBP, Durango, Colorado\r\n2002, Project Cost: $20,000\r\nServed as the sales manager in the identification and development of this project.  Hydrometrics successfully completed bench-scale testing of the Hydro process for Coal Bed Methane derived water.  The test objective was to produce low dissolved solids water suitable for stream discharge.  The water treatment system must be cost-effective when compared to developing additional deep-well disposal sites at this expanding methane production site. \r\n\r\nTreatment of Metal Finishing Wastewater\r\nBoeing, Seattle, Washington\r\n2003, Project Cost: $40,000\r\nServed as the sales manager in the identification and development of this project, which successfully completed a bench-scale test of wastewater generated from a metal finishing operation associated with airplane wing manufacture.  The test objective was to demonstrate that HERO could achieve 95% recovery of wastewater, provide high-purity water for reuse and produce a reject stream meeting sewer disposal requirements.  Pretreatment in front of HERO will involve a clarifier and multi-media filter. \r\n\r\nTreatment of Coal Bed Methane Produced Water\r\nJ.M. Huber Corporation, Sheridan, Wyoming\r\n2002, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nServed as the sales manager in the identification and development of this project, which successfully completed bench-scale testing of the Hydro process for Coal Bed Methane derived water from the Tongue River drainage.  The test objective was to produce a low TDS, low SAR water suitable for stream discharge.\r\n\r\nTesting of Coal Bed Methane Produced Water\r\nBP, Wamsutter, Wyoming\r\n2003, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nServed as the sales manager in the identification and development of this project.  BP was seeking alternative, cost-effective options for managing increased wastewater water generation.  The objective was to identify options competitive to development of new deep-well underground injection and allow for reuse of treated water.  Wastewater treatment was challenged by the widespread use of emulsifiers during gas/water production.  Hydrometrics completed initial bench-scale testing.\r\n\r\nSite Characterization and Water Treatment Evaluation\r\nAlpha Explosives, Lincoln, California\r\n2003, Project Cost: $120,000\r\nProvided project leadership and coordination of site investigation and groundwater treatment evaluations for a site impacted by nitrates and perchlorate.  Activities included bench-test treatability studies, groundwater quality studies, hydrogeologic site characterization, pilot-scale in-situ treatability studies and regulatory interface.\r\n\r\nExpert Witness\r\nRailyard Risk Assessment and Expert Witness Support\r\nTrinity Railcar Inc., Miles City, Montana\r\n2007, Project Cost: $30,000\r\nThe Miles City railyard has a long history of use that has left the site contaminated by lead, petroleum products and possibly other contaminants.  Sandblasting operations resulted in elevated lead concentrations in surface soil, and multiple leaks and spills resulted in soil and groundwater contamination by diesel.  Responsibility for cleanup was litigated between multiple prior owners.  Was retained as a subcontractor to provide risk assessment support and expert witness services for Trinity.  Trinity prevailed, and subsequent work was completed to scope the risk assessment support has thus far been used to scope the magnitude of the problem, identify likely remedies and assist legal staff with deposition preparation.  Also assisted in identifying immediate data collection needs.\r\n\r\nRisk Assessment Expert Witness Services\r\nYellow Bay, Flathead Lake, Montana\r\n1995, Project Cost: $15,000\r\nEvaluated long-term health risks to residents from residual levels of gasoline in soil and groundwater spilled from a tanker truck, and served as an expert witness in a jury trial.\r\n\r\nTechnical Training\r\n•\tHazwoper 40-Hour Training\r\n•\tAnnual First Aid and CPR Training, Red Cross\r\n•\tJoint Fact Finding, MIT/USGS\r\n•\tThe Risk Communication Challenge, George Gray, Harvard University\r\n•\tMulti-Criteria Decision Analysis,  Society of Risk Analysis Short Course\r\n•\tThe Use of Soil Ingestion Data in Risk Assessment Practices, Soil Ingestion Workshop, \r\n•\tEdward Calabrese and Edward Stanek, University of Massachusetts\r\n•\tTopics in Advanced Risk Assessment, Environmental Education Enterprises\r\n•\tGeochemical Processes in Groundwater Movement, Environmental Education Enterprises\r\n•\tAquatic Bioassessment and Biocriteria, Society of Environmental Toxicology and Chemistry short Course\r\n•\tSoil and Plant Toxicity Assessment, Society of Environmental Toxicology and Chemistry Short Course\r\n•\tAir Surveillance for Hazardous Materials, USEPA\r\n•\tClient Oriented Writing, Gardiner Davis Seminars\r\n•\tTime Power, Time Management Seminar, Charles R. Hobbs Corporation\r\n\r\nSelected Publications and Presentations\r\nAckerlund, W.S. and Saha, R, 2008.  Exploring Public Participation Choices, Part 1: Development of an Expert Model, Platform presentation at the U.S. Institute for Environmental Conflict Resolution annual conference in Tucson, Arizona, May.\r\nAckerlund, W.S.  2007.  Options for Managing Public Participation on Controversial Projects. Platform presentation provided at the annual Montana Mine Association meeting, May.\r\nAckerlund, W.S.  2003.  RCRA Vision Paper Suggests the Future of Waste Materials Management, Hazardous Waste Consultant, March.\r\nAckerlund, W.S.  2003.   MOU Between EPA and NRC to Clear Dual Regulatory Confusion.  Hazardous Waste Consultant, January. \r\nAckerlund, W.S.  2003.  EPA Guidance Explains CERCLA Liability Limitations for Prospective Purchasers Under the New Brownfields Law.  Hazardous Waste Consultant, January. \r\nAckerlund, W.S.  2003.  Monthly contributor for the ISO 14000 Update section of the journal Business and the Environment. \r\nAckerlund, W.S.  1996.  Petroleum Vapors - Transport and Fate, Derivation of Cleanup Levels, and Toxic Effects.  Presentation at the RBCA Steering Committee Meeting held by the Underground Storage Tank Program within the Montana Department of Environmental Quality, December. \r\nAckerlund, W.S.  1996.  Scientific and Regulatory Thoughts Supporting and Improved MPDES Permitting Program.  Presentation at the Montana Environmental Technology and Services Network (METSNET) annual meeting, February, Missoula, Montana. \r\nAckerlund, W.S.  1995.  Opportunities for Development of Site-Specific Water Quality Standards.  Presentation at the Second Annual Montana Water Law Conference, September, Helena, Montana. \r\nAckerlund, W.S., and Botz, M.K.  1995.  Montana’s Water Quality Laws Fully Protect Water Uses.  Published by Western Education Foundation for Resources, Inc., Helena, Montana, Issue Paper No. 2, October. \r\nDills, R.L., Ackerlund, W.S., Kalman, D.A., and Morgan, M.S.  1993.  Blood/Air Partition Coefficient Determinations: Automation and Improvement of the Equilibrium in Partitioning of Closed Systems Method.  J. Exp. Anal. Env. Epi., 3(4). \r\nDills, R.L., Ackerlund, W.S., Kalman, D.A., and Morgan, M.S.  1994.  Inter-individual Variability in Blood/Air Partitioning of Volatile Organic Compounds and Correlation with Blood Chemistry.  J. Exp. Anal. Env. Epi., 4(2). \r\nDills, R.L., Enderline, C., Ackerlund, W.S., Kalman, D.A., and Morgan, M.S.  1994.  Investigation of the Relationship Between Chemical Concentration and the Blood/Air Partition Coefficient.  Method, J. Exp. Anal. Env. Epi., 4(3). \r\nAckerlund, W.S.  Master’s thesis, Variability in Blood/Air Partitioning of Volatile Organic Compounds: Effect of Concentration and Correlation with Blood Chemistry.\r\n\r\n	2015-02-27 05:24:37.975699	2015-02-27 05:24:37.975699	34
1013	John		Belin	belin_john@bah.com	404-658-8054		230 Peachtree Street NW	Suite 2100	Atlanta	GA	30303	0	Associate	Booz Allen Hamilton	11	Mr. Belin, an Associate with Booz Allen Hamilton Inc. (Booz Allen), received a B.S. in Biology and a M.S. in Environmental Health Science with an emphasis on aquatic toxicology from the University of Georgia.  Mr. Belin has over 10 years of professional experience, which includes comprehensive experience in site investigation, human health and ecological risk assessment, and cleanup associated with RCRA, CERCLA, and various state environmental programs.  \r\n\r\nAt Booz Allen, Mr. Belin provides comprehensive technical support, including human health and ecological risk assessment expertise, and management for various Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and Department of Defense (DoD) projects.  In addition, he has experience supporting strategic outreach and communication projects associated with EPA’s Resource Conservation Challenge (RCC) such as developing fact sheet targeted at specific stakeholders and performing an analysis of multiple EPA voluntary programs to identify programs that align with the RCC national priority areas.\r\n\r\nHis project experience includes risk assessment support for US EPA settlement litigation; technical review of human health and ecological risk assessments; review and analysis of toxicological data; development of comprehensive risk-based screening levels; preparation of a site-specific risk assessment project plan; evaluation of risk assessments associated with delisting petitions, RCRA Facility Investigations, and Corrective Measures Studies; review of Subpart X Permit Applications; and generation of several screening level ecological risk evaluations.  In addition, his experience includes preparation of numerous RCRA Facility Assessment documents and litigation support documents.  Mr. Belin also has experience in conducting risk calculations associated with total petroleum hydrocarbon releases and the Johnson and Ettinger model for estimating exposure to indoor air contaminated by vapor intrusion from subsurface soils.\r\n\r\nMr. Belin also has experience managing and serving as a key technical contributor for a significant environmental sustainability effort with a leading global food and beverage manufacturer.  Multiple projects have been performed with the end goal of the support identifying and better managing risks posed to global food production and bottling operations by environmental and sustainability related issues such as major factors effecting water quality including source water protection, water scarcity/conservation, bottling plant treatment, chemical and equipment suppliers, sampling and testing, disinfection by-products, and other potential contaminants. \r\n\r\nMr. Belin has also served as a manager of a significant amount of work for EPA Region 4 over the last 8 years and has recently be tasked as the REPA Zone 2 Region 4 Regional Manager.  Past work that he has managed for EPA Region 4 has included:\r\n\r\n• Developing communication and outreach materials to promote EPA’s Resource Conservation Challenge (RCC) national priorities to the Department of Defense (DoD) and DoD Installations\r\n\r\n•  Designing, developing, and presenting training courses on an assortment of RCRA-related topics, coordinating arrangements with meeting facilities, and facilitating meeting activities, logistics, and presentation support\r\n\r\n•  Providing a wide variety of RCRA corrective action environmental indicator (CA725, CA750, CA400, and CA550) support including development of data gap assessments, conducting field sampling, implementing interim corrective measures to protect human health, and preparation of environmental indicator checklists.  \r\n\r\nMr. Belin currently manages two task orders for EPA Region 4 associated with resource conservation and materials management.  These task orders are:\r\n\r\n•  Develop outreach materials in support of Region 4’s efforts under the Resource Conservation Challenge (RCC) to conserve natural resources and energy by managing materials more efficiently.  This is accomplished through the development of a Municipal Government Tool Kit which is comprised of fact sheets and brochures populated with information regarding local government recycling and reuse programs.  The Tool Kit also requires the development of an interactive internet-based system to make outreach materials available to the public.\r\n\r\n•  Preparing an analysis of recycling markets Another task order we are supporting for EPA Region 4 involves compiling a comprehensive database of recycling entities in the southeast including haulers, processors, and end-users.  A market analysis is being performed based on the database for both the City of Atlanta and the Region 4 states.  The end result of this work will be to provide EPA Region 4 with two things -- a database that can be queried to provide focused data on recycling entities and a preliminary analysis of the recycling markets in the southeast.  Booz Allen support will also identify data gaps in the available data and provide recommendations on strategies to address these gaps with future studies.  This work is being performed in partnership with Atlanta Recycles.\r\n\r\nPROFESSIONAL EXPERIENCE\r\nBOOZ ALLEN HAMILTON, Associate\r\n\r\nSupported a leading beverage manufacturer in the planning of an environmental sustainability program for its worldwide food production and bottling operations in over 100 countries.  Currently leading a team that is evaluating alternatives to upgrade all of the manufacturer’s water treatment systems to meet future water quality requirements.  Developed and working to implement a risk assessment methodology focused on evaluating water quality.  The end goal of support is to ensure that the bottling operations have water of sufficient quality and quantity to ensure sustainable, future business operations.  Two specific tasks 