shwater mussels after varying lengths of exposure to swine wastewater collected during either the winter or summer months.  These tissue samples were examined for DNA strand breakage, tissue lipid content, and tissue water content.  Results from this experiment may be used to help fine tune the construction of future wetlands designed to treat wastewater.\r\n\r\nPUBLICATIONS, PRESENTATIONS, AND REPORTS\r\n\r\nBelin, J.I. et al.  Evaluating the Efficiency of Toxicity Abatement in a Constructed Wetland with Ceriodaphnia dubia.  Journal of Toxicology and Environmental Health, 2000\r\n\r\nBlack, M.C. and Belin, J.I., Evaluation of Sublethal Indicators of Toxicity Following an In-situ Exposure of Asiatic Clams in an Urban Stream, Environmental Toxicology and Risk Assessment, 1998\r\n\r\nBlack, M.C. and Belin, J.I., Biomarker Assessment of Environmental Contamination: In-situ Studies with Freshwater Bivalves, Proceedings of the 1997 Georgia Water Resource Conference, 1997\r\n\r\nBelin, J.I., Evaluating the Efficiency of Toxicity Abatement in a Constructed Wetland Using Freshwater Organisms.  Presentation given to American Society of Testing and Materials, Annual Conference, Atlanta, GA, April, 1998\r\n	2015-02-27 05:24:38.364215	2015-02-27 05:24:38.364215	35
