re that high-quality deliverables are prepared in a cost-effective manner.\r\n--Supported EPA and the Department of Justice in technical reviews associated with RCRA facility litigation.  Developed ecological conceptual site model, and estimated ecological risks to five terrestrial species and three aquatic species.  Contaminants of concern included dioxins, furans, PCBs, and metals.  Made recommendations on additional data collection efforts to better understand potential risks and impacts to shorebirds in the Great Salt Lake area.\r\n--Reviewed screening-level ecological risk assessments for two combustion facilities in Region 3 to ensure compliance with recent EPA guidance.\r\n--For an Ohio RCRA facility where contaminated groundwater discharges to a nearby creek, developed a site-specific guidance document detailing methods for deriving groundwater clean-up goals to protect benthic biota.\r\n--For four facilities in EPA Regions 2 and 5, conducted reviews of technical documentation related to CA725 Environmental Indicator (EI) status to identify data gaps and/or evaluate the adequacy of facility-prepared EI determinations.  Advised EPA on steps the facilities should take to achieve a positive determination. Subsequently prepared the CA 725 EI determination for one of these facilities.  \r\n--Developed Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) and accompanying data sheets for rapid ecological assessments of four different ecosystem types from strawman assessment methods drafted by EPA Region 5.  These SOPs provided detailed instructions for four-hour field events, and included fauna observations, flora surveys, and human impact surveys. \r\n\r\nNovember 2007 – Present.  Booz Allen Hamilton, Inc.  For EPA Region 2, assisting in the development of an environmental assessment for an expansion to the Snapperfarm, Inc. offshore concentrated aquatic animal production facility in Culebra, Puerto Rico. \r\n\r\nJune 2005 – Present.  Booz Allen Hamilton, Inc.  Providing reachback risk assessment support to the Air Force under the GEITA contract.  Evaluated the adequacy of ecological risk assessments performed on World War II era landfills at Bellows Air Force station in Oahu, Hawaii.  Ensured that CERCLA ecological risk guidance was adequately followed, and recommended additional risk analyses to ensure the protection of all relevant receptors.  Evaluated human health risks from lead-contaminated soil at Hickam Air Force Base using the Integrated Exposure Uptake and Biokinetic (IEUBK) Model for Lead in Children, and made recommendations for soil clean-up and risk communication.\r\n\r\nDecember 2005 – Present.  Booz Allen Hamilton, Inc.  Supporting a variety of short-term projects for the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) Environmental Cleanup Program (ECU).  Assisted in the development of a sampling and analysis plan at Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport.  Helped develop a Site Prioritization Model that assigned scores to FAA ECU sites based, in part, on environmental risk, and was designed to aid in the prioritization process for funding decisions.\r\n\r\nApril 2006 – March 2007.  Booz Allen Hamilton, Inc.  Supported the Department of Defense Office of the Undersecretary of Defense by developing updated Ecological Comparison Values for the Munitions Response Site Prioritization Protocol (MRSPP).  Compiled ecological screening values for surface water and sediment for a large number of constituents from a wide variety of accepted State and Federal sources.  The Comparison Values are used by the DoD to determine the relative risks potentially present at any new Installation Remediation Program (IRP) sites.\r\n\r\nDecember 2004 – March 2007.  Booz Allen Hamilton, Inc.  Served as Assistant Editor for EPA Currents, a quarterly internal Booz Allen newletter.  Gathered and wrote articles, and helped assemble and edit the newletter for publication.\r\n\r\nOctober 2005 – September 2006.  Booz Allen Hamilton, Inc.  Supported the U.S. Postal Service in developing and maintaining a database of energy data for USPS facilities nationwide.\r\n\r\nJune 2004 – May 2006.  Booz Allen Hamilton, Inc.  Supported the U.S. Army Environmental Center by researching, summarizing, and developing tools for installations to access information related to pollution prevention regulations and technical guidance.\r\n\r\nApril 2001 – June 2003.  University of Michigan.  Conducted Master’s degree research examining spatial and temporal patterns in community composition of Dytiscid beetles in ephemeral ponds and wetlands of southeastern Michigan.  Conducted surveys in the summer of 2002, identified and enumerated adult and larval beetles, and analyzed a data set comprising six years of surveys.  Particular emphasis was given to two closely related species to evaluate a possible tradeoff between dispersal and reproduction.\r\n\r\nSeptember 1998 – May 2001.  Environmental Protection Agency, Office of Water.  Headed the first two years of a long-term project to revise the nationally recommended aquatic life criteria for copper.  Led a team effort to integrate the Biotic Ligand Model (BLM), a mechanistic model that predicts metals toxicity to aquatic organisms, into the water quality criteria program.  Supervised contractors in developing BLM software and technical reference documents.  Evaluated the BLM’s predictive performance and developed methods for its implementation in the copper criteria.  Coordinated a Science Advisory Board Review of the BLM.  Managed three concurrent work assignments with two different contractors, comprising an annual budget of over $100,000.  Worked closely with other members of the Ecological Criteria Team to set priorities for our approximately $1 million annual budget.  Regularly responded to inquiries from a variety of stakeholders, and provided technical assistance to regional EPA offices and state water quality programs.  Prepared written responses outlining scientific arguments for rejection 