1022	Robert	j	Schreiber	rschrei45@aol.com	5736570839		12401 englewood rd		Ashland	MO	65010	0	President	Schreiber Yonley and Asociates	37	Robert J. Schreiber, Jr., P.E.\r\n\r\n\r\nAshland Office:\t12401 Englewood Drive\tBusiness:\t16252 Westwoods Business Park Drive\r\n\tAshland, MO  65010\t\tEllisville, MO  63021\r\n\t(573) 657-0639\t\t(636) 256-7200\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nActive P.E. Registrations\r\n\r\nState of Missouri, 1977\t\tState of New Jersey, 1993\tState of No. Carolina, 1994\tState of Arizona, 2003\r\nState of Illinois, 1987\tState of N. Hampshire, 1993\tState of Nebraska, 1995\tState of Idaho, 2003\r\nState of Kansas, 1988\tCommonwealth of P.R., 1993\tState of Oklahoma, 1995\tState of Indiana, 2003\r\nState of Georgia, 1989\tState of So. Carolina, 1993\tState of Kentucky, 1996\tState of Iowa, 2003\r\nState of Arkansas, 1991\tState of Alabama, 1993\tState of Texas, 1997\tState of Nevada, 2003\r\nState of Pennsylvania, 1991\tState of Colorado, 1993\tState of Connecticut, 2002\tState of Oregon, 2003\r\nState of Maryland, 1991\tState of New York, 1993\tState of Louisiana, 2002\tState of New Mexico, 2004\r\nState of Virginia, 1991\tState of Mississippi, 1994\tState of Tennessee, 2002\tState of Wyoming, 2004\r\nState of California, 1991\t\tState of Montana, 1994\tState of Utah, 2002\tState of South Dakota, 2005\r\nState of Florida, 1992\t\tState of Ohio, 1994\tState of Washington, 2002\r\nEducation\r\nMay 1972\tBachelor of Science: Chemical Engineering, University of Missouri-Columbia \r\n\tColumbia, Missouri\r\nEngineering Achievement\r\nDuring the span of his career, Mr. Schreiber has achieved success as a leader in the Missouri Department of Natural Resources, as a co-founder and principal of an environmental engineering firm, and as an internationally recognized speaker on technical issues related to dioxin and the cement industry.  While working for the state of Missouri, he coordinated the efforts on dioxin research and supervised the design, construction and operation of a dioxin research facility that identified and demonstrated the first technology to totally destroy dioxin.  He also provided technical expertise to the Department Director, elected officials and local citizens to send one voice to the U.S. Department of Energy to bring about a commitment of $1 billion to clean up the Weldon Spring's waste problem.  \r\n\r\nAs an entrepreneur, Mr. Schreiber has been involved with the start-up of four companies.  His leadership in business strategies, combined with technical expertise as an engineer and agency regulator, has enabled the success of these companies in a very competitive market.  In addition, he has developed an international presence in the cement industry as a expert in environmental issues.  This role has afforded him the opportunity to provide technical assistance to cement manufacturers from several countries and to be involved in the development of regulations related to the environmental concerns of the industry.\r\n\r\nProfessional Experience\r\nMay 1992 -- Present\t\t\tPresident, Schreiber, Yonley & Associates\r\nSchreiber, Yonley & Associates, formerly Schreiber, Grana & Yonley and Lafser & Schreiber, Inc., is a full-service environmental engineering firm located in St. Louis, MO.  Under Mr. Schreiber's management, the firm has currently over 25 engineers, scientists and support staff.  As a result of this growth, the company now provides services on a national basis with a clientele consisting of industrial and commercial companies, including many Fortune 500 companies.  Mr. Schreiber's responsibilities include development of business strategies, regulatory interpretation, project oversight, and development of long-term client relationships.  As a result of his many years of experience and technical background, Mr. Schreiber is often utilized as an expert witness in environmental damage cases.  He is an internationally recognized speaker and has provided technical guidance in the development of regulations governing the cement industry, both in the United States and abroad. \r\n\r\n1988 -- 1992\t\t\t\tVice President, Resource Recovery, Inc.\r\nAs Vice President in charge of design and regulatory compliance, Mr. Schreiber developed special designs and patents for a waste fuel blending and recycling operation serving Continental Cement Company in Hannibal, Missouri.  Mr. Schreiber was responsible for permitting the state-of-the-art hazardous waste management facility that processes in excess of 80,000 tons of hazardous waste fuel per year.  Expansion of this operation was accomplished while having a compliance record with excellent local support.  During his tenure, he oversaw the recycling of over 500,000 tons of waste to produce a quality commodity that is widely used, cement.\r\n\r\n1986 -- Present\t\t\t\tVice President, Perma-Fix Kiln Services, Inc.\r\n\t\t\t\t\t(formerly Industrial Waste Management, Inc.)\r\nIn this position, Mr. Schreiber is responsible for identification, development, and permitting of new facilities through proper management of hazardous waste in cement kilns.  In this capacity, he reviews the market to plan and forecast sources for developing niche recycling activities that make economic sense.  In addition, he is also responsible for assessing regulatory hindrances that must be overcome for successful ventures to proceed.  \r\n\r\n1986 -- 1989\t\t\t\tVice President, Solvent Recovery Corp.\r\nMr. Schreiber developed a system to improve the regulatory compliance and waste handling system at a treatment, storage, and disposal facility in Kansas City, Missouri.  During his tenure, major improvements in laboratory capabilities, computer tracking, process controls, and monitoring were achieved while increasing personnel safety.\r\n\r\nJanuary 1987 -- May 1992\t\tPresident, Lafser & Schreiber, Inc.\r\nApril 1986 -- December 1986\t\tVice President, Lafser & Schreiber, Inc.\r\nOctober 1985 -- April 1986\t\tPrincipal, Lafser & Schreiber\r\nIn 1985, Mr. Schreiber co-founded and served as principal for Lafser & Schreiber, Inc.  Originally located in Jefferson City, MO, the firm was moved to St. Louis and within one year had grown to eight professionals.  By 1992, when the company became Schreiber, Grana & Yonley, Inc., there were 30 employees serving a broad customer base.  Mr. Schreiber's management lead the company to develop expertise in providing services related to the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA) and the Clean Air Act (CAA), with a particular emphasis on cement kiln operation and treatment, storage and disposal operations.  \r\n\r\nJune 1980 -- September 1985\t\tDirector, Division of Environmental Quality\r\n\t\t\t\t\tMissouri Department of Natural Resources\r\nMr. Schreiber was responsible for managing and coordinating eight environmental programs within the division, encompassing six major programs (Air Pollution Control, Solid and Hazardous Waste Management, Land Reclamation, Soil and Water Conservation, Water Pollution Control and Public Drinking Water) and two support programs (Regional Office Programs and Laboratory Service).  While performing these duties, Mr. Schreiber supervised 385 full time employees.  His major accomplishments included organization and coordination of the Weldon Spring Site Remedial Action Project; coordination of the goals and actions of multiple agencies toward a unified directive; coordination of the Missouri dioxin cleanup program; and development of a pilot project for parks and soil conservation.  A tax proposition was passed in support of the parks and soil conservation project and remains in effect to date.\r\n\r\n\tAnnual Budget:\tOperating Budget\t$ 9,500,000.00\r\n\t\tGrants Budget\t$49,000,000.00\r\n\t\tConstruction Grants\t$62,000,000.00\r\n\r\nMarch 1978 -- June 1980\t\t\tStaff Director, Air Pollution Control Program\r\n\t\t\t\tMissouri Department of Natural Resources\r\nIn this position, Mr. Schreiber was responsible for supervising a staff of 40; preparing and conducting monthly Air Conservation Commission meetings; acting as liaison between the Air Conservation Commission and the Department; and reviewing petitions for variances and submitting recommendations to the Department and the Commission.  He served on the Governor’s Advisory Committee for Missouri coal.  He accomplished the development of approvable state implementation plans for St.  Louis and Kansas City that required extensive work with the Missouri Legislature to assure the passage of legislation necessary for plan approval.  \r\n\r\n\tAnnual Budget:\tOperating Budget\t$800,000.00\r\n\t\tGrants Budget\t$975,000.00\r\n\r\nJanuary 1979 -- May 1979\t\tInstructor, University of Missouri - Columbia\r\nTaught the graduate course "Health Aspects of the Environment" in the Department of Family & Community Medicine.  Attending students were pursuing Health Services Management or Family & Community Medicine degrees.  The syllabus included topics concerning health risks due to environmental hazards that exist in society.\r\n\r\nDecember 1977 -- March 1978\t\tChief of Enforcement\r\n\t\t\t\t\tMissouri Department of Natural Resources\r\nResponsible for the inspection of major facilities in the state; directed enforcement actions against industries who failed to comply with the regulations; supervised three Air Pollution Control Inspectors; provided technical assistance to regional offices; and prepared new regulations for the State of Missouri.\r\n\r\nMarch 1974 -- December 1977\t\tEnvironmental Engineer\r\n\t\t\t\t\tMissouri Department of Natural Resources\r\nResponsible for conducting and computerizing a statewide emission inventory; prepared new regulations for the State of Missouri for inspections of facilities to verify compliance with state air pollution control; supervised three Air Pollution control inspectors; and provided technical assistance to regional offices on regulations.\r\n\r\nAugust 1973 -- March 1974\t\tEnvironmental Engineer I\r\