1027	Kevin	L	Dixon		770-751-7517		1120 Sanctuary Parkway		Alpharetta	GA	30009	195	Water Quality Supply, Treatment and Distribution System Operations	B&V	26	Kevin L. Dixon\r\nSpecialization:\r\n Water Quality Supply, Treatment and Distribution System Operations\r\nOffice Location\r\nAlpharetta, GA\r\nEducation \r\nM.S. Environmental Science and Engineering, Virginia Tech, Blacksburg, VA\r\nB.S. Biology/Environmental Science, Gannon University, Erie, PA \r\nTotal Years Experience: \r\n26\r\nJoined B&V: \r\n2004\r\nProfessional Associations\r\nAmerican Water Works Association\r\nPast Chairman - New Jersey Section AWWA\r\nChairman - AWWA Radionuclides Technical Advisory Workgroup\r\nAWWA Lead & Copper Rule Technical Advisory Workgroup\r\nAWWA – Inorganic Contaminants Research Committee\r\nAWWA –Treatment Plant O&M Committee\r\nCitizenship:\r\nUnited States of America\r\nLanguage Capabilities\r\nEnglish\r\nKevin has more than 26 years of experience in potable water supply, treatment and distribution system operations, with a focus on the water quality aspects of these areas. \r\nKevin managed the Water Quality Department at New Jersey-American Water Company for 10 years.  In that capacity, he was responsible for the operation of two dozen facilities designed for the removal of volatile organic compounds (VOCs) from groundwater supplies located throughout the State of New Jersey.  Both Granular Activated Carbon (GAC) and packed-tower aeration were employed to remove VOCs to comply with the New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection’s stringent VOC standards.  In New Jersey, the Maximum Contaminant Level (MCL) for Trichloroethylene (TCE) is 1 part per billion (ppb) as compared to the Federal MCL of 5 ppb.  As such, the VOC removal facilities were operated to yield maximum removal efficiency.\r\nThe selection of GAC or air-stripping technology was based upon a number of factors including the concentration of VOCs in the raw water, site dimensions, access constraints, and permitting requirements.\r\nAdditionally, he has conducted research supporting water utility operations for more than nine years. His research and operational experience has led to national recognition as an expert in water quality and regulatory matters. Specific areas of expertise include: water supply management; pilot and full-scale process evaluations; treatment plant and distribution system operations; drinking water laboratory management; regulatory analysis and implementation of measures to achieve regulatory compliance; customer service expertise; significant experience in media relations; development of water quality-related communications pieces including Consumer Confidence Reports; and 20 years of dealing with issues related to radionuclides and radon in water supplies. Kevin currently serves on two AWWA regulatory advisory groups dealing with current and developing regulations.\r\nRelevant Project Experience \r\nTampa Bay Water Regional Surface Water Treatment Plan Facility Modification – Transition Plan \r\nOngoing\r\nReview and development of the start-up and commissioning plan for the expansion of the Tampa Bay Water Surface Water Treatment Facility from a capacity of 99 million gallons per day to 120 million gallons per day.  Included are preliminary testing of the facility, transitional operation and Acceptance Testing.\r\nDevelopment of Chemical Specifications for Tampa Bay Water, Tampa Bay, FL \r\nOngoing\r\nAssisting Tampa Bay Water with development of the specifications for the twenty-two distinct water treatment chemicals that are utilized in the Tampa Bay Water system.\r\n\r\nEvaluation of Feasibility of Expansion of the Tampa Bay Water Seawater Desalination Facility\r\nFebruary 2009\r\nPerformed an analysis of the feasibility of expanding the Seawater Desalination Facility from 25 MGD to 35 MGD. The analysis included identification of process improvements that would yield product water quality that meets stringent water quality objectives, identification of infrastructure components that would establish a basic level of redundancy and enhanced facility reliability, an assessment of the space requirements associated with the facility improvements/expansion and cost estimates for each component of the expansion plan.\r\n\r\nEvaluation of Hydrogen Sulfide Removal Technology, Keller Water Treatment Plant, Tampa Bay Water, Tampa Bay, FL \r\nDecember 2008\r\nConducted pilot-scale evaluation of ozone for the removal of hydrogen sulfide at the Keller water treatment plant. The 30 day evaluation concluded that ozone was an efficient and cost-effective technology for the removal of hydrogen sulfide at the Keller plant. The project report recommends specific design criteria for the full-scale ozone facility.\r\nIntegrated Water Resources Plan, City of Ocala, FL\r\nOctober 2008\r\nConducted an evaluation and feasibility analysis of water supply and treatment alternatives as part of the long-term water resources plan for the City of Ocala. The evaluation concluded that development of additional Floridan aquifer supplies, with hardness removal treatment, was the most cost-effective long term water supply option for the City. A component of the evaluation was a detailed summary of current and future Safe Drinking Water Act regulations and their impact upon City operations.\r\nAnnual Operations and Maintenance Review – Tuas Seawater Desalination Water Treatment Plant – Singapore \r\nMay 2008\r\nConducted an on-site audit of the operations and maintenance practices employed at the 36 mgd seawater desalination facility \r\nZara Ma’in Desalination Project, Water Authority of Amman, Jordan\r\nApril 2008\r\nProvided technical basis for determination of recovery rates for the reverse osmosis membranes employed at the treatment plant.\r\nStart-up and Commissioning of the Tampa Bay Water Seawater Desalination Facility, Tampa Bay Water, Tampa Bay, FL\r\nOctober 2007\r\nProvided technical support during the construction and commissioning of the 25 mgd desalination facility.\r\nEvaluation of Hydrogen Sulfide Removal Technology, Lithia Water Treatment Plant, Tampa Bay Water, Tampa Bay, FL\r\nMay 2008\r\nConducted pilot-scale evaluation of microfiltration and ozone for the removal of hydrogen sulfide at the 45 mgd Lithia water treatment plant. The 180 day evaluation concluded that ozone was the preferred technology for the removal of hydrogen sulfide at the Lithia plant. The project report recommends specific design criteria for the full-scale ozone facility.\r\nAqua Pennsylvania – Shenango Valley Division System Check-Up\r\nAugust 2007 \r\nConducted an evaluation of Aqua Pennsylvania’s Shenango Valley System addressing source water management, water treatment plant operations, distribution system operations, and asset management. \r\nChemical Utilization Audit – Aqua Pennsylvania’s \r\nPickering Water Treatment Facility\r\nNovember 2006 \r\nLed the audit of Pickering treatment Plant. Included in the audit was evaluation of: chemical selection and utilization rates, opportunities for optimization of chemical utilization, monitoring procedures to ensure optimum feed rates and water quality, and chemical handling procedures. \r\nNew Jersey American Water Supply Development Plan\r\nJune 2006\r\nLed the evaluation of water supply alternatives for New Jersey American’s service territories in Atlantic and Cape May Counties. Evaluated regional pipeline, desalination, aquifer storage and recovery and purchased water options to meet New Jersey American’s water supply needs through 2020.\r\nPartnership for Safe Water Evaluation for Aqua Pennsylvania\r\nLed an evaluation of eligibility for the Partnership for Safe Water for Aqua Pennsylvania’s surface water treatment plants.\r\nEvaluation and Assessment of Synthetic Organic Contaminant Removal Technologies for New Jersey Drinking Water for the New Jersey Dept. of Environmental Protection\r\nAssisted with the evaluation of the effectiveness of various treatment technologies for removing organic chemicals to identify the best available technology for removal of organic chemicals from New Jersey drinking water. \r\nMaytum Water Treatment Plant Capacity Evaluation\r\nConducted a three-phase capacity evaluation of the Maytum Water Treatment (Tampa, FL) to determine capital improvement and treatment modification needs.\r\nCorrosion Control Evaluation for Brick Township MUA\r\nLed the evaluation of corrosion control issues following the MUA’s conversion to chloramines. Developed recommendations for monitoring strategies and optimization of corrosion control treatment.\r\nLead and Copper Rule Support for AWWA\r\nPrimary author on issue papers written for AWWA dealing with lead service lines, alternative sampling methods, simultaneous compliance issues and lead in schools. \r\nWater Quality Evaluation, Dover, DE \r\nAssisted with evaluation of corrosion control and distribution system water quality issues. Developed recommendations for optimization of treatment plant operations as well as operations and maintenance procedures for the distribution system.\r\nRegulatory Compliance Evaluation, United Water Delaware, Christiana Water Treatment Plant\r\nConducted tracer study evaluation and treatment plant optimization studies to position United Water for compliance with current and future regulatory initiatives.\r\nFacility Evaluation Team, Erie County Water Authority Acquisition Evaluation\r\nAssisted with evaluation of raw water supply, treatment, and distribution system facilities owned by the City of Buffalo, NY to determine viability of acquisition by the Erie County Water Authority.\r\nWorkgroup Leader, Raw Water Supply, United Water New Jersey-Haworth Improvement Project\r\nResponsible for evaluation of the condition of the Oradell Reservoir and development of recommendations to improve reservoir quality and minimize challenges to the Haworth Treatment Plant.\r\nNew Jersey-American Water Co., Haddon Heights, NJ \