 Mr. Schweizer’s professional experience includes:\r\n?UST Site Investigation and Remediation, Berkeley, California. Mr. Schweizer responded within 24 hours to the discovery of a trench filled with oil and soil sludge at a former UST site. The site was a former auto repair facility with a gasoline storage tank that had historically been used for retail sales of leaded and unleaded gasoline. The trench was uncovered during development of the site as a mini-mall. John provided extensive documentation to the owner for review by the lead agency. He reviewed previous UST investigation and removal reports, conducted additional soil and groundwater sampling and testing, and negotiated “No Further Action Required” with the responsible local agency with respect to soil and groundwater contamination. Waste materials in the trench were sampled and analyzed for waste characterization, and properly disposed under federal,\r\nstate and local regulations. The trench was demolished. Demolition debris and soil from site development was sampled, analyzed, characterized and properly disposed as non-hazardous industrial waste under California Department of Toxic Substances Control (DTSC) and local regulations.\r\n?Technical Adviser, AMCO Chemical Superfund Site, Oakland, California. Mr. Schweizer provided technical consulting and community relations support for the Remedial Investigation (RI) phase of a major Superfund project, and are continuing to provide these services during the Feasibility Study (FS) phase. Work has included participation at Community Action Group (CAG) meetings and preparation of newsletters. He has attended and manned an information booth at all EPA–sponsored community outreach events. John also prepared documents for public review. Other work included reporting to the community on review of historical site investigation reports, quarterly groundwater data, air sampling data, RI report, preparation of comments for agency review, and recommendations for remedial technologies to include in the FS. He also prepared a Risk Assessment (RA) study using California DTSC standards, and reviewed the RA prepared for the RI. John’s efforts on this project have built a high level of trust and confidence among a largely minority population.\r\n?San Jose, California NPL Site Mr. Schweizer was responsible for the management and coordination of all site activities related to facility closure. Investigative activities included soil and groundwater sampling and analysis of suspected source areas, the preparation of Closure Plans for submittal to DTSC, and the preparation of Closure Reports. Remediation of VOCs included a 10,000-gallon per minute (gpm) groundwater extraction and treatment system, soil excavation, a slurry wall to contain the source area, and (at the time) the largest SVE system to have been constructed in the US. Project manager for closure of RCRA permitted facilities at the site. Negotiated a risk-based closure standard with the DTSC to replace "no impact", background-based standard in soils naturally containing heavy metal contaminants of concern, including chromium. Closure plan and report were accepted by the DTSC for public review and closure certification.\r\n?Mountain View, California NPL Site Mr. Schweizer has been responsible for management and coordination of all site activities related to facility closure. Investigative activities included soil sampling and groundwater investigation at waste management units that were suspected source areas for subsurface contamination. Remedial activities for VOCs included design and construction of 25 groundwater extraction wells and three air-stripping groundwater treatment systems, two SVE systems and three soil-bentonite underground barrier walls up to 45 feet deep. Mr. Schweizer demonstrated that two drum storage areas and two underground concrete tanks were not source areas. Closure plans and reports were accepted by the DTSC for clean closure of these former RCRA-permitted facilities. Mr. Schweizer also provided technical support to outside counsel for the client in an investigation of a concrete wastewater pit at one building at the site that was suspected of being an unpermitted RCRA waste management unit. The investigation was terminated after in informal hearing with the DTSC and the state Office of the Attorney General at which Mr. Schweizer presented his findings.\r\n?Middlefield-Ellis-Whisman (MEW), California. Mr. Schweizer was responsible for management and coordination of investigative and remedial activities at the MEW site, which was a 7-party site that also included coordination with NASA and U.S. Navy. The work included installation of more than 600 soil borings, more than 350 monitoring wells, potential conduit investigations, construction of a database containing more than 25,000 records, and collection and review of more than 2,500 groundwater samples. Mr. Schweizer resolved a potential cost allocation dispute among the parties by showing that one building at the site had not been a VOC source area. Mr. Schweizer also developed and implemented the water reuse program for the site, which included provisions for reclaiming treated groundwater as cooling tower make-up for the NASA wind tunnel.\r\n?Soil Vapor Extraction (SVE) Pilot Test, San Jose, California. Conducted a successful soil vapor extraction pilot study for a site contaminated by VOCs from manufacturing operations. Work included extensive documentation of site operations, review of site investigation reports and data, preparation of a HASP and pilot test work plan, operation of a portable vacuum extraction system, sampling and testing, air permit, and pilot test report.\r\n?UPRR-Norden and Dunsmuir. Mr. Schweizer was the program manager for project design and installation of a replacement wastewater treatment plant at the UPRR Norden site, and for design of automation upgrades to an existing plant at the Dunsmuir site. At the Norden site, an existing treatment plant was completely replaced with an upgraded, automated system designed and installed. Mr. Schweizer was responsible for handling all contractual and business matters, including negotiating contracts, and for mobilizing resources as required to meet client needs.\r\n?DTSC RCRA Facility Permit, Hollister, California. Wrote the Interim Status Document (ISD) RCRA Part “B” application for the McCormick-Selph facility in Hollister, California. Work included investigation and documentation of site conditions, regional setting, waste management unit design, operating procedures, and other parameters required for submittal to the State of California Department of Toxic Substances Control (DTSC) (formerly Toxic Substances Control Division) with the application.\r\n?RI/FS Pocatello, Idaho. Mr. Schweizer reviewed remedial investigation (RI) documents and prepared feasibility study (FS) documents for a site with air, groundwater, surface water, and ecological pathways. Contaminants include metals and other inorganics including low-level radioactive wastes. Applied "reverse engineering" techniques for investigation of innovative technologies. He spearheaded a review of the RI report (prepared by another consultant) that put the client in a much better position to negotiate remediation goals with the U.S. EPA.\r\n?Groundwater Extraction and Treatment System, Singer Friden Site, California. Mr. Schweizer acted as project manager for construction of a fully automated groundwater extraction and treatment system at a DTSC site in San Leandro, California. The fully automated system, which provides remote access to DTSC site managers in Sacramento, was recently completed within budget and on schedule.\r\n?Feasibility Study, Oyster Bay Former Landfill, California Mr. Schweizer served as project manager for a Feasibility Study (FS) to select and optimize a remedy for long-term management of landfill leachate, to prevent its migration to the San Francisco Bay. Options being investigated include barriers, grading, drainage improvements and phytoremediation (the use of plant species) to reduce infiltration into the waste. The objective of the FS was to find a cost-effective innovative means to reduce long term costs of operating and maintaining the existing leachate management system.\r\n?Hazardous Waste Removal from Abandoned Warehouse, Union City, California. Project manager for inspection of an abandoned warehouse that had gone into foreclosure to determine the presence of hazardous wastes. Wastes were characterized, profiled for disposal, transported, and properly disposed in accordance with applicable regulations.\r\n?Lead Contaminated Soil Removal, San Francisco, California. Project Manager for a lead-contaminated soil removal at Parcel “A”, Hunters Point Shipyard, San Francisco, California. Soil hot spot removal was one of several tasks performed along with hazardous material abatement and demolition of buildings, shrub removal, and other site services. Staked out hot spot areas in accordance with drawings provided by another consultant, and excavated lead contaminated soil to line and grade in accordance with plans and specifications. Soil was stockpiled, sampled and analyzed, transported and disposed in accordance with regulations.\r\n?Storm Water Pollution Prevention Plan Implementation, San Francisco, California. Installed and maintained surface runoff controls for a residential development project at Parcel “A”, Hunters Point Shipyard, San Francisco, California. Work included installation of barriers, a surface water collection and treatment system, operations, and maintenance. The work was performed as part of an as-needed services contract that included emergency response.\r\n?Allocation Studies, California and Pacific Northwest. Mr. Schweizer was a consultant to clients at National Priority List (NPL) sites in California and the Pacific Northwest that involve multiple PRPs. He was the manager for review of remediation investigation 