drocarbon Tank Leak, Sylmar, California. Project manager for closure of underground gasoline tank leak at national manufacturing company site in Los Angeles County. Site was closed by the lead regulatory agency following remediation and regional groundwater assessment.\r\n?Federal EPA Emergency Response, Merced, California. Technical manager for cleanup of soil and groundwater contaminated by chlorinated solvents, primarily PCE and TCE. Project work included characterization of soil and groundwater, and cleanup. Remedial design incorporated existing solvent recovery equipment into a unique, innovative vapor extraction system, which resulted in minimal capital expenditure.\r\n?Biological Treatment, Visalia, California. Technical manager for design and implementation of an innovative bioventing process at the underground tank leak site for a Fortune 500 food processing company. Cleanup of diesel fuel-contaminated soil by the in-situ bioventing process has saved the client more than one million dollars in remedial action cost. Project work included a risk assessment, which resulted in negotiation of the no-action alternative for and a second underground tank leak at the same facility.\r\n?Phase I Environmental Assessment, Pocatello, Idaho. Provided consulting services and assessment for a property transfer at an NPL site.\r\n?Contractor QC at Superfund Site, Selma, California. Program manager for QC for a major federal Superfund site. Project work involved excavation, stabilization (solidification) and on-site emplacement of over 10,000 cubic yards of soil contaminated by pentachlorophenol, arsenic and chromium. Contractor QC work included preparation of QC plans, chemical data acquisition plan, sampling, analysis, physical and chemical testing of stabilized material and geotechnical studies.\r\n?Biological Treatment of Hydrocarbon-Contaminated Soil, Hayward California. Biological treatment of approximately 1,000 cubic yards of soil contaminated by organics. Achieved n