1038	Sabine	E	Martin	smartin1@k-state.edu	785-532-6474		104 Ward Hall	Center for Hazardous Substance Research	Manhattan	KS	66506	0	TAB Coordinator	Kansas State University	25	Sabine E. Martin\r\nProfessional Preparation\r\nEducation: Degree(s)/Specialization/Year\r\nPh.D./Hydrogeology/1990/Justus-Liebig-Universitaet, Giessen, Germany\r\nM.S./Geology/1985/Justus-Liebig-Universitaet, Giessen, Germany\r\nHealth and Safety Training Registration and Certification\r\n40 Hour OSHA 29 CFR 1910.120, 6/90 Professional Geologist, State of Nebraska\r\n8 Hour OSHA Annual Refresher, annually License # G-0117\r\n8 Hour OSHA Manager Training, 12/90 Professional Geologist, State of Kansas\r\nFirst Aid and CPR Training, 2/08 License # 109\r\n8 Hour Competent Person Excavation, 2/93\r\nAppointments and Experience\r\nSince November 2002 to present Dr. Martin is employed by the Center for Hazardous Substance Research at Kansas State University. Currently, Dr. Martin is the TAB (Technical Assistance to Brownfields communities) Coordinator for EPA Regions 5 and 7. Tasks include technical outreach services to communities and other stakeholders to assist them with a variety of environmental and revitalization issues. Reviews of technical documents (such as Phase I and II environmental site assessments, RI/FSs, CMSs, RFPs, workplans), organizing educational workshops, presenting at relevant workshops/conferences as well as serving as liaison between stakeholders, responsible parties, and regulatory agencies are part of the responsibilities. In addition, she provides technical assistance to communities dealing with Superfund sites, which, in the past, included sites located on Native American land.\r\nAs a member of the U.S./German Bilateral Working Group, Dr. Martin is involved in the development of SMARTe, an electronic resource tool for the revitalization of brownfield sites.\r\nSince 1999 to present, Dr. Martin is a hydrogeologist with Enviro Tech Services, Inc. in Salina, Kansas, providing technical assistance with site assessments and remedial projects mostly involving agricultural chemicals.\r\nFrom August 1997 to May 1999, Dr. Martin was a Temporary Assistant Professor at Kansas State University, Manhattan, Kansas, and taught Hydrogeology and Environmental Geology. During that time she was an investigator for an environmental impact research grant project at Fort Riley, Kansas.\r\nFrom January 1994 to August 1997, Dr. Martin worked as an independent geologist, based in Manhattan, Kansas. During this time period she was involved with cost and work plan preparations regarding the assessment and remediation of petroleum hydrocarbon impacted sites and the resulting on-site activities.\r\nFrom July 1994 to January 1996, Dr. Martin lived in Germany, a result of her husband’s sabbatical. While there, Dr. Martin conducted research regarding remediation techniques employed by German environmental companies.\r\nFrom September 1990 to July 1994, Dr. Martin was employed by Riedel Environmental Services, Inc. in Chesterfield, Missouri. As Manager of Remedial Services with Riedel Environmental Services' Midwest Region, Dr. Martin was responsible for the research, development and implementation of alternative remediation techniques such as bioremediation and soil vapor extraction. Dr. Martin provided consulting services and coordinated remedial activities with clients from government agencies and private industry.\r\nAs a Senior Hydrogeologist for the Region, her responsibilities included hydrogeological site investigations, remedial design, field operations, aquifer modeling, the interpretation of hydrological and geological data and the management of projects involving groundwater and hazardous wastes.\r\nDr. Martin was involved in all aspects of project management ranging from preliminary client contacts/site visits and preparations of cost estimates to the actual on-site work and subsequent evaluation/interpretation of obtained data. Final report preparation and communication with the respective clients and regulatory agencies throughout the projects were also a part of her responsibilities.\r\n1987 - 1990, Dr. Martin was a Graduate Research Assistant with the Kansas Geological Survey.\r\nDr. Martin has attended several EPA (Environmental Protection Agency) seminars: Hazardous Waste, Transport and Fate of Contaminants in the Subsurface, Groundwater Monitoring, Non-Point Source Pollution, Site Characterization for Subsurface Remediation, and Bioremediation of Hazardous Waste Sites.\r\nDr. Martin is a 1988 and 1989 recipient of the Kansas Geological Survey Frank C. Foley Award presented by the Kansas Geological Survey and a recipient of the 1985-1986 Kansas State University/Justus-Liebig-University Exchange Fellowship.\r\nSelection of Representative Environmental/Private Sector Projects\r\n•Hydrogeologist, U.S. Army, Ft. Riley, Kansas. Evaluation of geological, hydrological, and hydrochemical data collected over a time period of seven years with subsequent recommendations for further action. A detailed report was prepared.\r\n•Hydrogeologist, confidential client, Kansas. Delineation of nitrate and pesticide plumes in soil and ground water for various sites in Kansas. Involved in the preparation of work plans, reports, on-site work a well as the presentation of remedial alternatives.\r\n•Project Manager/Hydrogeologist, confidential client, Missouri. Site assessment and remediation involving impact from leaking underground storage tanks on soil and ground water underneath a commercial building. The tanks were closed in place and a vapor extraction system was designed and installed. Responsible for all aspects of the project, including subcontractor procurement, remedial system design, on-site supervision, cost tracking, interfacing with state regulatory agency, and final report preparation.\r\n•Specialized Response Manager, U.S. EPA Region 5, Michigan. Design and implement ex-situ bioremediation system for soils impacted 