1044	Mark	J	Maxwell		720-834-4200		6000 South Syracuse Way	Suite 300	Englewood	CO	80111	195	Project Manager	B&V	33	Mark J. Maxwell, P.E.\r\nProject Manager\r\nSpecialization:\r\nFacility Planning, Water and Wastewater Treatment, and Sludge Management\r\nOffice Location\r\nDenver, Colorado\r\nEducation \r\nB.S., Civil Engineering, Ohio State University, 1972.\r\nM.S., Environmental Engineering, University of Colorado, 1975.\r\nProfessional Registration\r\n1977, Colorado, #15036\r\n1993, Wyoming, #6427\r\n1993, South Dakota, #5496\r\n2009, New Mexico #19457\r\nTotal Years Experience\r\n33\r\nJoined B&V\r\n1975\r\nProfessional Associations\r\nAWWA, WEF\r\nCitizenship\r\nUnited States of America\r\nLanguage Capabilities\r\nEnglish\r\nSince joining Black & Veatch in 1975, Mr. Maxwell has been project manager or engineer on more than 100 water, wastewater, distribution, collection, and financial planning studies, including numerous EPA facility plans and I/I studies.  As an environmental/process engineering specialist, he is knowledgeable in regulatory and permitting issues.  Mr. Maxwell has also managed the planning and design of numerous water and wastewater treatment projects, including pilot plant studies to select among alternative technologies and optimize design parameters.  This includes alternate deliver (design-build) projects as well.\r\nRelevant Project Experience\r\nWastewater Facility Planning for the Metro Wastewater Reclamation District in Commerce City, Colorado\r\nProject Manager – In the mid-1980s, Mark developed the 201 Facility Plan and Preliminary Design Report for the nitrification and denitrification improvements to Metro’s Robert W. Hite Wastewater Treatment Plant, which is currently (in 2008) rated for an annual average flow of 161 mgd.  To meet ammonia and nitrate limits, Mark developed a plan to incorporate anoxic reactors and mixed liquor recycle pumping into the existing three-pass air activated sludge aeration basins in the 70 mgd North Complex.  Centrate from dewatering of anaerobically digested sludge, which can contain up to 2000 mg-N/L of ammonia, is flow-equalized and then routed directly to the North Complex aeration basins for ammonia and nitrate removal.  A small slipstream of non-nitrified secondary effluent from the South Complex is blended into the North Complex effluent to make sure there is sufficient ammonia for chloramine disinfection.  \r\nIn 2008, Mark led the team that updated Metro’s Facility Plan, which was also configured so it will serve as the five-year update of the Utility Plan that is maintained by the Denver Regional Council of Governments.  The 2008 Update forecasts capacity, compliance, and fixed asset replacement needs in five-year increments.  Predesign of the largest project to emerge from the 2008 Update was initiated before the report was completed.  This project is replacement of the pure oxygen reactors in the South Complex with a new three-stage air activated sludge system designed for nitrification, first-stage denitrification, and biological phosphorous removal for an annual average flow of 100 mgd.  Trace amounts of ammonia will be fed to the fully nitrified North and South Complex secondary effluents so chloramine disinfection can be continued.  Annual cash flow requirements were projected through 2017 (10 years), and in five year increments through 2033.  Capital expenditures were projected to be over $800 million during the first 10 years, and over $1.8 billion through the entire 25-year planning period.     \r\nOther MWRD assignments include a mixing study for the anaerobic digesters; an investigation into the causes and solutions to the District’s consistently low effluent pH; and expansion of the primary treatment facilities, which includes conversion to the thin sludge pumping mode of operation and installation of separate gravity thickeners.\r\nRegulatory Support, Snake River Wastewater Utility and Frisco Sanitation District, Summit County, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Working with Dr. William Lewis of the University of Colorado over a 10-year period, Mark developed an Alternatives Analysis approach to complying with Anti-Degradation Rule requirements for WWTP discharges to Lake Dillon.  Through a rigorous mixing zone analysis, \r\nDr. Lewis and B&V were able to demonstrate that ammonia removal should not be a permit requirement and an alternative copper standard will fully protect the lake without the need for supplemental reverse osmosis heavy metal removal treatment at the two WWTPs.  This work culminated in the spring of 2005 with the State’s acceptance of the Alternatives Analysis reports and issuance of discharge permit amendments to reflect their results.\r\nWWTP Process and Regulatory Support, South Adams County Water and Sanitation District, Commerce City, Colorado\r\nProcess and Regulatory Specialist - In the spring of 2005, Mark provided process and regulatory direction for a Capacity Analysis and Re-Rating Study of the Williams-Monaco WWTP.  Interim re-rating of the plant from 7.0 to 8.0 mgd is needed to accommodate growth and bridge the period between now and the year when a regional WWTP comes on line.  Re-rating is possible because performance of the MBBR process is better than predicted when design of this new technology was completed in 2002.  In addition, a performance review and modeling of the existing biotower indicates it can achieve substantial ammonia removal at flows up to 2.5 mgd.  The State awarded site application approval of the re-rating request in 2006, and the interim increase in capacity will be incorporated into the 2008 renewal of the discharge permit.  When the regional plant is on-line, the design maximum month flow for the Williams-Monaco facility will drop to 6.0 mgd, which must be further upgraded to meet the pending nitrate waste load allocation for Segment 15 of the South Platte River.\r\nPotable Water Supply Project, Town of Lyons, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Mark provided technical and managerial direction for a new finished water pumping station and transmission line project by which the Town of Lyons conveys potable water from City of Longmont.  This project allowed the Town to decommission, rather than upgrade, its aging WTP.  Three, 100-horsepower and adjustable speed pumps deliver finished water through a 12-inch high pressure transmission main to the Town’s upper pressure zone.  Permits and approvals for this project, which was financed with a state revolving loan, were required from numerous local, state, and federal agencies, including the Corps of Engineers and the U. S. Fish and Wildlife Service.  Mark helped the Town select a construction manager and negotiate a guaranteed maximum price for the work.  He also assisted the Town in negotiating its initial tap fee and intergovernmental agreement with Longmont.\r\nUV Disinfection Project, City of Bozeman, Montana\r\nProject Manager - Working with Great West Engineering, Black & Veatch prepared a preliminary design report (PDR) for conversion from gaseous chlorine and sulfur dioxide to UV disinfection at the WWTP that serves the City of Bozeman, Montana.  Integral to conversion to UV is the need for the City to have an alternate form of chlorine for odor and activated sludge filament control, plus a larger and more reliable standby generator.  Key features of the preliminary design include:\r\n•\tShould effluent quality improve through the future use of advanced nutrient removal technologies, the initial 14.4 mgd UV capacity may be sufficient to meet the 25 mgd ultimate design condition.\r\n•\tWith some code-compliance modifications, the existing garage can be converted to an economical site for a sodium hypochlorite system, and is conveniently located so chlorine solution can be distributed through the same network of feed piping.\r\n•\tThe distribution of standby power to controllable loads will be through the plant SCADA system, and the restart sequence will be prioritized to maintain continuous operations and make best use of generator capacity.\r\nDue to funding and timing considerations, the City elected to defer these improvements and will integrate them into a larger biological nutrient removal (BNR) upgrade and expansion. \r\n2003 Water/Wastewater Master Plan, Cheyenne Board of Public Utilities, Cheyenne, Wyoming\r\nProject Manager - Managed the preparation of a comprehensive Master Plan that encompassed all utility functions, from water supply, treatment, and distribution to wastewater collection, treatment, and ultimate utilization of the final effluent and biosolids.  Other elements included development of short and long-term demand management (conservation) measures, and evaluation of the BOPU’s non-potable water supply (including wastewater reuse) and financial planning systems.  Even the size and makeup of the BOPU’s workforce was considered in this master planning effort.  Computer models that were developed to assist in analysis and decision-making include the following:\r\n•\tStrategic water supply system model to predict surface water yields under alternative snow pack scenarios.  This model is also used to forecast whether the BOPU will be entering/leaving one of five defined drought conditions based on projected surface water yields, ground water pumping, system-wide demands, and the use of non-potable water supplies, such as raw surface water and reclaimed wastewater, at major greenbelt sites.\r\n•\tWater distribution system model to identify existing and future deficiencies and develop recommended improvements to ensure water is delivered at adequate pressure and volume to where it is needed.  An “all-pipes” model was developed to refine the analysis and provide comprehensive maintenance management database.  \r\n•\tWastewater collection system model to help ensure that adequate capacity is available throughout the BOPU’s service area.  While an “all pipes” model was developed for maintenance purposes, the hydraulic analysis was run on a sub-set of the pipe network that comprises the major lateral, trunk, and interceptor lines.\r\n•\tFinancial planning models for both the water and wastewater funds.  Black & Veatch helped the BOPU develop prioritized capital improvement programs and the rate increases needed to implement them.  \r\nDuring the course of the study, it became apparent that wastewater reuse should be a component of the BOPU’s future water supply system.  Accordingly, reclaimed wastewater treatment facilities were designed as bid alternative to a concurrent project to upgrade and expand both WWTPs.  Final copies of the Master Plan, including figures, were delivered to the BOPU in both hard copy and CD format.\r\nSherard Raw Water Delivery Pipeline, Cheyenne Board of Public Utilities, Cheyenne, Wyoming\r\nProject Manager - Managed the design and construction of 14.0 miles of \r\n36-inch diameter, cathodically protected pipe to deliver raw water from Crystal Reservoir to the new Sherard WTP.  The new conduit generally runs parallel to an existing 30-inch line, which could not meet maximum day production requirements for the new WTP.  Due to strong competition between steel and ductile iron pipe suppliers, construction bids were more than $3 million under budget, allowing Cheyenne to install more of the line than it anticipated during this phase of the project.  Black & Veatch and its subcontractors successfully handled a wide array of permitting, easement, environmental, and property owner issues, helping the contractor to deliver the project ahead of schedule.\r\nUpgrade and Expansion of the Crow Creek and Dry Creek WRFs for the Cheyenne Board of Public Utilities in Cheyenne, Wyoming\r\nProject Manager - Managed two projects to upgrade and expand the two water reclamation facilities (WRFs) that serve the Cheyenne Board of Public Utilities (BOPU).  Construction of the first project was completed in 2001, and the second in 2006.\r\n•\t2001 Expansion of the Crow Creek WRF.  This rock media trickling filter facility, most of which was first constructed in 1949, was expanded from 4.5 to 6.5 mgd.  Features include replacement of the original screening, grit removal, and primary clarification equipment, plus renovation of the headworks building to meet current codes.  In addition, the design provided for retrofit of vertical UV disinfection equipment into the chlorine contact basin.\r\n•\t2003 Design of Improvements to the Crow Creek and Dry Creek WRFs.  In 2001, the receiving stream (Crow Creek) was reclassified by the State for aquatic life protection, which required that ammonia removal be provided at both plants.  Based on cost evaluations and pilot plant studies, it was recommended that the nitrification capacity of the Dry Creek WRF be expanded to 10.5 mgd by conversion of the existing aeration basins to an integrated fixed film activated sludge (IFAS) process, and inclusion of mixed liquor recycle pumping and pre-denitrification basins.  The IFAS conversion was accomplished through the addition of buoyant plastic carrier elements, a new diffused aeration system, and stainless steel sieves to retain the media within the aeration basins.  Similar to the 2001 project at the Crow Creek WRF, the Dry Creek design provided for retrofit of vertical UV disinfection equipment into the chlorine contact basin.\r\nThe Crow Creek WRF has always been a fixed film facility and the BOPU wants to retain a simple biological treatment process so this plant could be staffed with a minimum complement of operators, and run unattended at night.  As a result, B&V recommended that the trickling filters be replaced with a MBBR system.  This process uses the plastic carrier elements, diffused aeration system, and sieves, but there is no recycle of solids from the secondary clarifiers.  The MBBR process is a once-through biological system and the BOPU can continue to use their shallow secondary clarifiers since the waste sludge is similar to the slough from trickling filters.\r\nCapacity Expansion and Regulatory Upgrade for the Project 7 Water Authority, Montrose, Colorado\r\nProject Manager – In 2000, Mark managed and provided technical direction for a study to reassess the adequacy of the existing WTP to meet future capacity and regulatory requirements.  Raw surface water, which is diverted from the Gunnison River, is stored in a small terminal reservoir prior to coagulation, solids contact sludge blanket clarification, and dual media filtration.  The study indicated that short-term capacity requirements could be met by renovating the two oldest filters.  Due to the far flung nature of its service area, near-term regulatory compliance recommendations focused on improving free chlorine contact time and reducing distribution system disinfection byproducts by adding ammonium sulfate to create a chloramine residual.\r\nIn response to record water demands, Project 7 retained Black & Veatch in 2008 to provide a design-build expansion and upgrade of the WTP from 18.6 to 27.6 mgd.  While a membrane addition was considered, economics and operational issues favored the addition of two more granular media filters.  Other elements of the project include construction of a new, well-baffled chlorine contact basin to replace an aging reservoir and to meet the State’s new disinfection requirements, which will now mirror those of EPA.  In addition, the plastic tube settlers had reached the end of their useful life and will be replaced.  The guaranteed maximum of $8.9 million was about $0.4 million under budget and includes a shared savings provision which could result in a further reduction in cost to the Owner.  Black & Veatch committed to complete the project in less than one year so the additional capacity will be available for the peak demand season in 2009.     \r\nWastewater Master Plan, Cheyenne Board of Public Utilities, \r\nCheyenne, Wyoming\r\nProject Manager - Managed comprehensive study of Cheyenne's wastewater collection and treatment systems, including a 201 Facility Plan in 1995, which was updated in 1998 to reflect Wyoming’s proposed new stream reclassification system.  A linked GIS/hydraulic computational model was developed to evaluate the collection system.  This model was also updated in 1998 to reflect the results of a special sewer flow monitoring and rainfall data collection program.  This data enabled Black & Veatch to develop specific infiltration inflow rates for each of the major drainage basins that comprise Cheyenne’s collection system.  Wastewater management alternatives included conventional treatment and discharge, as well as transbasin disposal and wetlands creation in lieu of meeting effluent ammonia limits that could potentially be as low as 0.20 mg-N/L.\r\nLevel I Water Master Plan, Cheyenne Board of Public Utilities, Cheyenne, Wyoming\r\nProject Manager - Directed comprehensive study of Cheyenne's water supply, treatment, and distribution system.  Prepared future potable water demands and revenues considering the impact of programs for water conservation and the substitution of raw water or reclaimed wastewater for potable water currently used to irrigate major park/greenbelt areas.\r\nPilot Plant Study and Preliminary Design Report, Cheyenne Board of Public Utilities, Cheyenne, Wyoming\r\nProject Manager - Directed multiple pilot plant studies to evaluate technology to be incorporated into the expansion of the 18 mgd Sherard WTP, which will increase net throughput capacity to 32 mgd in Phase 1, further expandable to 50 mgd in the future.  Using pilot units supplied by both Black & Veatch and potential equipment suppliers, the following processes were evaluated over multiple seasons to evaluate variable water quality conditions: dissolved air floatation, aided sedimentation, ballasted flocculation, ozone disinfection, microfiltration and dual and mixed media filtration.  Based on a farsighted set of water quality goals developed by the client and Black & Veatch, a recommended set of water treatment processes was selected, for which a preliminary design report was prepared.\r\nWater Reclamation Facility Upgrade and Expansion, City of Broomfield, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Managed design and construction for the Phase 1 and Phase 2 improvements to the Broomfield WRF.  The $28 million Phase 1 expansion increased capacity from 4 to 8 mgd, went on-line in 2004, and made maximum use of existing aeration basins through the implementation of an Integrated Fixed Film Activated Sludge (IFAS) process.  Through the addition of plastic carrier element media, the IFAS basins will be able to handle twice their original design load while fully nitrifying the flow.  Other project components include:\r\n•\tIFAS pilot study to confirm design loadings and expected performance.\r\n•\tAdditional influent pumping, screening, and primary clarification capacity.\r\n•\tTwo new high solids centrifuges.\r\n•\tAnaerobic and anoxic basins for biological phosphorus and nitrate removal system.\r\n•\tOne more secondary clarifier and a new UV disinfection system to meet more stringent E.Coli requirements.\r\n•\tChemical feed and filtration facilities to produce up to 6 mgd of reclaimed wastewater for reuse.  The reuse water will also meet the City's phosphorous removal objectives for discharge to Great Western Reservoir (GWR), which will become a reuse water storage impoundment.\r\n•\tExpanded odor control system that incorporates a new biofilter.\r\nBlack & Veatch assisted the City of Broomfield with local, regional, and State permitting requirements, which included site approval for the WRF, notice of authorization for the farm site facilities, approval to discharge to GWR, and authorization to apply reclaimed wastewater to reuse sites.  The $27 million Phase 2 project provides for expansion to 12 mgd, and includes more IFAS and UV capacity, a new preliminary treatment complex, major renovation of the anaerobic digester complex, covering the sludge storage lagoon, and expansion of the odor control biofiltration system.  Construction of the Phase 2 improvements is scheduled to be complete in 2010.      \r\nReclaimed Water System, City of Westminster, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Managed the construction of an $18 million advanced wastewater treatment plant and distribution system to supply 6 mgd of reclaimed wastewater for irrigation of major park, golf course, school, athletic field, streetscape, and business greenbelt areas throughout the City.  The new plant includes chemical coagulation, continuous contact filtration, chlorine disinfection, equalization storage, and high service pumping facilities.  Over 75,000 feet of transmission and service line pipes were installed, along with a companion fiber optics system to provide for SCADA communication between the plant and all reuse sites, where metering and flow control equipment were installed.\r\nWater Reclamation Facility Master Plan, City of Pueblo, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Managed and provided technical direction for a detailed evaluation of Pueblo's 19 mgd filter/solids contact (TF/SC) contact treatment plant.  Task 1 focused on evaluating the major unit processes considering design, regulatory, hydraulic, operational, and redundancy factors.  In \r\nTask 2, B&V developed alternatives to eliminate capacity bottlenecks and prepared a staged and prioritized capital improvements program (CIP) for the WRF.\r\nThe first CIP project to be implemented was renovation of the headworks, which became operational in 2004.  New facilities include step screens and washing/compaction equipment to clean and dewater the screenings.  The compactor was designed and specified to successfully push the compacted screenings over 50 feet to an existing truck loading bay.  Two types of raw wastewater pumps were added as well.  Vertical centrifugal units were installed in the new building to augment screw pumps.  During construction, one of the enclosed screw pumps became inoperable.  The City elected to retire this unit and B&V designed two submersible pumps to replace it, which were installed as a change order without disruption to the schedule.\r\nB&V was also asked by the City to design two interceptor sewer replacement projects.  The first was for a segment of the City's 30 inch corrugated metal pipe interceptor sewer.  A portion of this interceptor lies along and under the Arkansas River.  Installation of the new 36- and 42-inch corrosion-resistant HOBAS pipe was completed in 2004.  Project permitting and construction scheduling was closely coordinated with numerous local, state, and Federal agencies.  The project was financed through a low interest state loan that B&V helped the City secure.  The second project involved upsizing of the Northern Interceptor, which required two tunnels, one of them under I-25.  Consisting of 21-inch HOBAS pipe, the first phase of this project will allow the City to handle flows from the more rapidly growing northern sector of the City, while buying time for Pueblo to generate the funds needed to upsize lower portions of this line.   \r\nWater Quality and Treatment Consultation, City of Golden, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - In response to a boil order from the State of Colorado, the City of Golden asked Mark to lead a team of B&V specialists and restore the normally excellent performance of its WTP.  The City’s WTP, which treats surface water from Clear Creek, had experienced simultaneous failures in its coagulation, manganese removal, and granular media filtration processes.  By switching coagulants and adjusting the City’s manganese monitoring and oxidation strategy, the WTP was able to quickly come back into compliance.  During the following 3 months, B&V served as the chief plant operator and developed a report to assist the City and its new plant superintendent in improving both the physical facilities and operations at the WTP.\r\nStrategic and Forward Planning Studies, City of Henderson, Nevada\r\nProject Engineer - In 1997, in response to growth rates in excess of \r\n10 percent per year, Mark developed a fast-track Strategic Plan to double the biological capacity of the Wastewater Reclamation Facility (WRF) from \r\n10 to 21 mgd while complying with stringent ammonia and phosphorous removal standards.  These Bridging Capacity Improvements, the unit costs for which are under $0.80 per gpd, were placed into service in the fall of 1998.  They provided the time for Henderson to plan, design, and stage additional improvements to its advanced waste treatment plant.  This facility must meet stringent nutrient standards for discharge to Lake Mead, and pathogen standards for landscape reuse sites.\r\nMark subsequently prepared a Forward Planning Study, the intent of which was to enable the City to increase capacity and meet regulatory requirements in a timely and logical manner.  Design of the recommended project, the Phase 3 improvements, was completed in 2000.  However, due to site acquisition delays, construction of the Phase 3 project was delayed until 2004.  Accordingly, another interim capacity project, further increasing the WRF capacity to 24 mgd, was conceived in 2001 and placed into service in 2003.\r\nThe Phase 3 improvements were completed in 2007 and resulted in a 32-mgd complex that provides for full biological nutrient removal with chemical treatment and filtration for polishing of effluent phosphorous residuals.  Low pressure/high output UV equipment provides for disinfection of all flows to pathogen standards suitable for discharge to Lake Mead.  That portion of the effluent pumped to reuse through a multi-zone distribution system receives supplemental chloramination by means of sodium hypochlorite and sodium bisulfite.  Waste biological and chemical solids are dewatered using belt filter process and hauled by a private contractor to a local landfill.\r\nIn 2008, Mark led the development of an executive summary briefing document regarding emerging contaminants of potential concern in the Las Vegas Valley.  In addition to the trace organic compounds that are being scrutinized worldwide for their potential endocrine disrupting characteristics, selenium loads to Lake Mead are being evaluated on a regional and statewide basis.  The summary includes forecasting emerging contaminant removals, including the impact of potential supplemental treatment processes as the Henderson WRF may be modified in the future to meet more stringent regulatory requirements.  The executive summary will be used by City officials during discussions with regional and state water quality agencies and will be updated and incorporated into the 2009 Update of the WRF Master Plan.        \r\nWater Distribution, Stormwater, and Wastewater Collection System Master Plan Updates, Casper Public Services, Casper, Wyoming\r\nProject Manager - Managed the preparation of the 1997 updates to the computer models and master plans for the entire water distribution system and East Casper stormwater collection facilities.  The modeling efforts included utilization of existing GIS and development plans to allocate population and land use to the areas under consideration.  Prioritized capital improvement plans were developed and staged improvements were bracketed to growth milestones.  A preliminary design was also prepared for water facilities needed to serve the rapidly growing East Casper area.  As part of the wastewater collection system study, rain gages and portable flow meters were installed to determine basin-specific infiltration and inflow rates to help calibrate the model to Casper’s site specific conditions.  The collection system model was completed in 2001. \r\nWellhead Protection Plan, Casper Public Utilities, Casper and Natrona County, Wyoming\r\nProject Manager - Developed the scope and managed the preparation of a comprehensive study to expand the CPU's water supply and develop a wellhead protection program to protect local groundwater resources.\r\nLevel II Water Master Plan, Wyoming Water Development Commission; Casper and Natrona County, Wyoming\r\nProject Manager - Black & Veatch prepared the SDWA and WTP assessments and economic evaluation for a regional water supply master plan.  The study developed preliminary design criteria and costs for renovation and expansion of surface and groundwater supply systems to serve a future population of over 80,000 people in more than six communities/districts.\r\nWTP Improvements, City of Glenwood Springs, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Managed a site evaluation study and design of coagulation, flocculation, and plate settling improvements to an 8.6 mgd \r\nin-line filtration WTP.  Raw water, which is derived from several creeks that drain the Flattops Watershed, is subject to seasonal turbidity spikes.  The original plant could not handle these spikes, resulting in reduced throughput and passage of Giardia cysts into the finished water.  The new pretreatment facilities were successfully built on a steeply sloping, geotechnically challenging site adjacent to the original filtration plant.  The project also included a backwash equalization basin, control valve, and sewer line to convey WTP residuals to the City’s WWTP.\r\nWastewater Facility Plan and Treatment Plant Design, Town of Berthoud, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Managed and provided technical process engineering support for the preparation of a 201 Facility Plan and design of a 2.0 mgd WWTP.  The new facility, which is expandable to 3.0 mgd, utilizes a plug flow, nitrifying activated sludge treatment train with disinfection provided by self-cleaning, low pressure/high output UV lamp modules.  The site was laid out to facilitate the future addition of biological phosphorous and nitrate removal.  If needed, chemical addition and filtration can be added to achieve (1) low phosphorous residuals prior to discharge or (2) reclaimed wastewater for landscape reuse.  Black & Veatch also helped the Town complete the site approval applications required by both the State and Weld County.  Other services included preparation of a draft FNSI for use by the State in approving the project and making it eligible for a low-interest SRF loan. \r\nWastewater Treatment Plant Improvements, Summit County Board of Commissioners, Summit County, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Since 1976, Mark has provided technical direction and management for three Facility Plans and seven expansions or modifications to the Snake River WWTP.  This facility provides an extraordinary high degree of phosphorous removal prior to discharge to Lake Dillon.  Unit processes include plug flow activated sludge; flow equalization; sodium hydroxide, alum, and polymer addition; flocculation; aided sedimentation; and mixed media filtration.  Filtered effluent turbidity and total phosphorous residuals are typically less than 0.25 NTU and 20 µg-P/L, respectively.  Waste biological and chemical sludges are aerobically digested prior to centrifuge dewatering and composting at the nearby County landfill.  The sixth expansion project was completed in 2002 and increased overall WWTP capacity to handle buildout flows, which are expected to be 2.6 mgd.  While supplemental disinfection has not been necessary or utilized for the last 20 years, a medium pressure in-vessel UV system was added in 2008 because the State is now applying the anti-degradation rule to Lake Dillon and fecal coliform/E.coli limits are becoming progressively more stringent.  \r\nWastewater Treatment Plant and Interceptor Sewer, City of Gunnison, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Managed the completion of a 201 Facility Plan and design of a 4.2-mgd oxidation ditch plant and 13,000 feet of 27-inch interceptor sewer.  The recommended plan provided for abandonment of the City’s WWTP, as well as the aerated lagoon facility that served the County’s \r\nDos Rios Sanitation District.  The Dos Rios WWTP site was utilized for construction of the City’s new regional facility, which serves the City and County customers that have municipal sewer service.  The new plant uses a variety of special features for Gunnison's high-altitude, cold-weather climate and received innovative and alternative funding from EPA, plus the Consulting Engineer’s Council design award in 1988.\r\nThe 1983 Facility Plan was further updated in both 1998 and 2001 as part of City/County efforts to connect three small treatment plants, plus numerous septic systems located in high groundwater areas, to the City’s regional WWTP.\r\nWastewater Treatment Plant Improvements, Frisco Sanitation District, Frisco, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Managed the design of improvements that (1) increased secondary treatment, aerobic sludge digestion, and advanced waste treatment capacity and (2) improved plant safety and reliability. Specific improvements included covered secondary clarifiers, modification of an existing package plant to provide more aeration capacity, and replacement of a decaying wooden roof with a geodesic aluminum dome. AWT capacity was increased by retrofitting adsorption clarification and filtration processes into an unused flocculation/sedimentation complex.  In 2001, Mark managed the retrofit of two high solids centrifuges and shaftless screw conveyors into the existing solids handling building.  In 2008, two secondary effluent flow equalization basins were placed into service.  Smoothing out peak flows eliminated the need to built more AWT units, which were several times more expensive than the new concrete basins and a companion site dewatering system.   \r\nWastewater Treatment Plant Preliminary Design Report, City of Laramie, Wyoming\r\nProject Manager - Managed a 201 Facility Plan and preliminary design report that evaluated both conventional and nonconventional alternatives for expanding capacity and improving performance of the City's wastewater treatment plant.  The recommended plan called for replacement of the City's aerated lagoon and rapid infiltration facilities with an oxidation ditch that will provide for secondary, ammonia removal and denitrification treatment in the same basin.\r\nIron and Manganese Water Treatment Plant, Steamboat Springs Water, Steamboat Springs, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Provided process expertise for the design of a 2 mgd iron and manganese removal WTP for the Yampa River Infiltration Gallery.  Severe site and building elevation constraints led to the selection of a monomedium anthracite filter with a gravel-less underdrain that provides for both air and water backwash capabilities.\r\nIron and Manganese Water Treatment Plants, Town of Monument, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Provided process direction and managed the design of facilities to treat high concentrations of iron and manganese in both alluvial and deep, nontributary groundwater.  The more recent Well No. 8 project included in-situ precoating of silica sand instead of using conventional, but less durable, greensand material.\r\nWater and Wastewater Master Plans, City of Longmont, Colorado\r\nProject Manager - Managed the preparation of master plans for Longmont's water treatment and distribution systems, as well as its wastewater collection and treatment facilities.\r\nPublications and Presentations\r\nPhillips, H. M., Mark J. Maxwell, et. al., “Optimizing IFAS and MBBR Designs Using Full-Scale Data,” Presented at WEFTEC 2008, Chicago, Illinois, October 2008.\r\nMaxwell, M.J., “Balancing Growth and Water,” Contributor to the Article in the Colorado Public Works Journal, January 2008 Edition. \r\nMaxwell, M.J., “Recycled Water Treatment,” Presented at the Wyoming Water Association Meeting in Cheyenne, Wyoming, October 2007.\r\nMaxwell, M.J. and Blair Corning, “The TF/MBBR Process at the Williams Monaco WWTP,” Presented at the Rocky Mountain AWWA/WEA Joint Technical Activities Committee Meeting in October 2006.  \r\nMaxwell, M.J., “Lake Dillon Marathon: 12-Year Trek to Final Effluent Limits,” Presented at the 2006 Rocky Mountain AWWA/WEA Conference in Vail, Colorado, September 2006. \r\nMaxwell, M.J., “Total Nitrogen and Phosphorous Control with Emphasis on Nitrate Reduction,” Presenter and Moderator at the Rocky Mountain WEA Operator/Engineer Workshop in Denver, Colorado, July 2005.  \r\nMaxwell, M.J., “Clean Up Your Act with UV Disinfection,” Presented at the Montana WEA Conference in Billings, Montana, April 2005.\r\nMaxwell, M.J., et al., “Thin Sludge Pumping and Superclarifier Primary Clarifier Testing at MWRD’s Central Plant in Commerce City, Colorado,” Presented at the 2004 Rocky Mountain AWWA/WEA Conference in \r\nGrand Junction, Colorado, September 2004.\r\nMaxwell, M.J. and Ken Rutt, “Full-Scale Performance of the IFAS/BNR and Reuse Treatment Facilities at the Broomfield, Colorado Wastewater Reclamation Facility,” Presented at the Utah WEA Conference in St. George, Utah, April 2004.\r\nMaxwell, M.J. and James P. McQuarrie, “Pilot-Scale Performance of the MBBR Process at the Crow Creek WWTP, Cheyenne, Wyoming,” Presented at WEFTEC 2003, Los Angeles, California, October 2003.\r\nMaxwell, M.J., “Distribution System Water Quality Concerns in Cheyenne, Wyoming,” Presented at the 2003 Rocky Mountain AWWA/WEA Conference in Casper, Wyoming, September 2003.\r\nMaxwell, M.J., “Manganese Removal Using Granular Media Filtration,” Presented to the Colorado School of Mines and City of Golden, March 7, 2003.\r\nMaxwell, M.J., “Hybrid Systems for Enhanced Nutrient Control,” Presented at the University of Colorado Environmental Engineering Student Forum, March 5, 2003.\r\nMaxwell, M.J., “WWTP Upgrades Using Moving Bed Biofilm Reactor Systems, “ Presented at the Vail Operator Training Seminary, Vail, Colorado, October 11, 2002.\r\nMaxwell, M.J., et.al., “Biological Nutrient Removal Process Selection for the Broomfield, Colorado WRF,” Presented at the 2001 Rocky Mountain AWWA/WEA Conference in Angel Fire, New Mexico, September 2001.\r\nParsons, Lela S. and Maxwell M.J., “Mem