1155	Douglas		Mckechne	dmckechnie@asl.edu			1169 Edgewater Drive		Grundy	VA	24614	0	Assistant Professor of Law	Appalachian School of Law	0	(Source: http://www.asl.edu/faculty/index.aspx)\r\n\r\nProfessor McKechnie joined the Appalachian School of Law faculty in 2008 after private practice with Healey & Hornack, P.C. in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. Professor McKechnie's practice focused on labor law, employment law and civil liberties litigation. He represented labor unions in a variety of matters including collective bargaining enforcement, Unfair Labor Practice charges, and claims under the Employee Retirement Income Security Act.  He also represented employees in both individual and class action claims under various federal and state employment laws.  As a legal committee member and cooperating attorney with the Pittsburgh chapter of the ACLU, Professor McKechnie also litigated First Amendment issues with a focus on free speech.  In addition to practicing law, Professor McKechnie was a recurring guest lecturer on civil rights and civil liberties for an American Government course at the University of Pittsburgh.  Before entering private practice, Professor McKechnie spent a year as a judicial clerk in the Superior Court of Connecticut.  Professor McKechnie graduated summa cum laude from Ohio University where he earned a B.A. degree in political science with a minor in philosophy.  He received his J.D. degree, cum laude, from the University of Pittsburgh School of Law where he received several scholarship awards as well as recognition for his performance in advanced legal writing and alternative dispute resolution courses.  As a research assistant, Professor McKechnie conducted research on how police interrogation methods have evolved since the Miranda decision.  Professor McKechnie teaches Pretrial Practice, Business Associations and Legal Process.	2015-02-27 05:25:01.052362	2015-02-27 05:25:01.052362	463
1156	Adam	R	Saslow	adam.saslow@plexusli.com	678-388-1670	770-377-5613	1600 Parkwood Circle	Suite 310	Atlanta	GA	30339	150	Vice President - Sustainability Programs	Plexus LI	12	General Qualifications\r\nMr. Saslow is a senior facilitator, public policy expert, strategist, and builder of collaborative solutions.  He has a long history of working with a variety of environmental and natural resource statutes, regulations, and programs.  He currently serves as Vice President of Sustainability Programs for Plexus Leadership Innovations, a subsidiary of Plexus Scientific Corporation.\r\n\r\nSummary of Capabilities\r\n?\tFacilitation – Creates environments where legitimate stakeholders make their own best decisions.  Professional structure and guidance of meetings, workshops, conferences and stakeholder dialogue\r\n?\tConflict Analysis – Assessments of the political, economic and/or environmental context for business, policy, and strategy.\r\n?\tPublic Involvement Process Design – Plans and structures means and methods for robust and constructive community engagement.\r\n?\tPolicy Development and Analysis – Works with Federal, state, and local government to develop innovative policies and programs that achieve stated goals.\r\n?\tStrategic Planning – Aligns vision, mission, goals, objectives and performance metrics through the use of group dynamics, organizational understandings and technology.\r\n?\tSustainability Assessment – Evaluates the opportunities for simultaneously achieving economic, environmental, and social goals and objectives.\r\n\r\n \r\nProfessional Experience\r\nBefore joining Plexus, Mr. Saslow was a Special Assistant with the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, the President and CEO of Consensus Solutions, Inc., and a Senior Principal with the NewFields Companies.  He is nationally renowned as a process designer and guide who helps clients through the maze of collaborative processes.  Many of his cases involve some form of regulatory or natural resource management and policy.  He currently serves as Vice President of Sustainability Programs for Plexus Leadership Innovations, a subsidiary of Plexus Scientific Corporation.  He also serves as the outsourced Executive Director of the States’ Association for Natural Resources—a collective of Cabinet-level state officials responsible for managing one or more elements of the natural resources portfolio.\r\nRelevant Projects\r\nNatural Resource Management Conflict Assessment, Process Design and Guidance\r\n\r\nPublic Hearing:  Mountain Top Removal in West Virginia, US EPA R3, Charleston, WV\r\nMay, 2010 to June, 2010 -- Senior Process Designer and Facilitator\r\nDesigned and guided one the most controversial public hearings of the decade for US EPA.  The Agency is rumored to be planning on denying a permit for surface mining at Spruce No. 1 in Logan County, WV in the Spruce Fork Watershed, an area highly impacted by previous mining activities. The public hearing took place on May 18 in Charleston, WV.\r\n\r\nThe Spruce No. 1 Mine is one of the largest surface mining operations ever authorized in Appalachia.  The Mingo Logan Coal Company has already been authorized by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, Huntington District (Corps) to construct six “valley fills” and numerous sedimentation ponds in Seng Camp Branch, Pigeonroost Branch and Oldhouse Branch and certain tributaries to those waters by discharging excess spoil generated by surface coal mining operations.  These on-site streams are tributaries of and exhibit surface water connections to Spruce Fork of the Little Coal River, which ultimately flows into the Coal River.\r\n\r\nEPA has reason to believe that the Spruce No. 1 Mine, as currently authorized, could result in unacceptable adverse effects to fish and wildlife resources.  EPA has issued a public notice of a proposed determination to restrict or prohibit the discharge of fill material at the Spruce No. 1 Mine project site consistent with their authority under Section 404(c) of the Clean Water Act.  EPA is concerned that the project could result in unacceptable adverse effects on the aquatic ecosystem, particularly to fish and wildlife resources and water quality.  EPA is also concerned that the project may have cumulative adverse impacts.  EPA believes that the Spruce No. 1 project, in conjunction with numerous other mining operations either under construction or proposed for the Coal River sub-basin, may contribute to the cumulative loss of water quality, aquatic and forest resources. The Coal River sub-basin is already heavily mined and demonstrates impacts associated with surface coal mining.\r\n\r\nMr. Saslow, Nora Chiong and Dan Gerszewski designed the process for registration and the deliverance of public testimony at this hearing.  Mr. Saslow moderated/facilitated the speakers throughout.  Over 800 people attended the scheduled five hour hearing – and over 125 people spoke.  Security levels were high with over 75 uniformed and plain clothes offers in attendance.  The hearing went off without a hitch.  Mr. Saslow and his staff received high compliments from the US EPA Regional Administrator from Philadelphia and others.\r\n\r\nStates’ Association for Natural Resources (SANR), National Locations\r\nOctober, 2008 to Present – Outsourced Executive Director\r\nResponsible for all operations, logistics, and facilitation and for the conveyance of member opinions to national and regional policy makers.  SANR is a Cabinet-level voice for natural resource management and sustainability, as regional and national policy evolves in the following areas:\r\n?\tLand valuation and carbon sequestration as it relates to climate change\r\n?\tClimate change resilience strategies – adaptation\r\n?\tFederal spending and its impact on natural resource agencies\r\n?\tPolicy on renewable energy opportunities on public lands (particularly state lands) and the connection to opportunities on Federal lands\r\n?\tChildren in nature\r\nStrategic Planning, Hawai`i DLNR, Honolulu, HI\r\nMay, 2007 to June, 2008 -- Senior Facilitator\r\nCompleted a strategic planning project for the Natural Area Reserves System (NARS) in Hawaii’s Department of Land and Natural Resources.  Designed and guided a facilitated process intended to define the NARS mission, vision, and responsibilities and the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities and threats to program effectiveness and success.  Identified the gaps between NARS programs and the group’s mission/vision/assigned responsibilities and values.  Worked with stakeholders to identify strategies to address gaps in programming, the vision, and mission.  Conducted dialogue on the topic of appropriate performance metrics.  (Employed by the NewFields Companies during this effort)\r\n\r\nCooper River Natural Resource Management Plan, SC DHEC, Berkeley County, SC\r\nNovember 2003 to December, 2004 -- Senior Facilitator\r\nWhile contracted by the South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control/Oceans and Coastal Resource Management, addressed the goals of the Cooper River Special Area Management Plan (SAMP) by guiding a Natural Resources Subgroup charged with developing a Natural Resource Management Plan (NRMP) for delivery to the SAMP Steering Committee.  The subgroup included stakeholders from Federal, state, and local government, development, industry, and the environmental community.  Designed and guided this process over a period of more than one year.  The final NRMP included detailed chapters on an historical review of natural resources, goals for maintaining or enhancing the natural resource base, and recommendations addressing water quality, wildlife habitat and diversity, land use and conservation, and specific actions to manage the rice impoundments in the SAMP area.  This 100+ page document was ultimately endorsed by all 27 participants.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nWatershed Protection in Illinois, IL EPA, Throughout Illinois\r\nSeptember 2003 to June, 2004 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nDesigned and guided a process convened to transition the State of Illinois to a watershed-based protection framework – a more holistic and interconnected watershed planning and protection framework.  Illinois EPA convened a carefully selected group of stakeholders.  This group, known as the “Basinwide Management Advisory Group” (B-MAG) included balanced representation from every side of water quality planning and protection.  This group was supported by a larger collection of water quality planning and protection specialists who were available to provide real time answers to the questions posed by the B-MAG membership.  After only seven months, 29 of 30 participants agreed to the 80-page final document.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nRobust Redhorse Conservation Committee, USFWS, Central Georgia\r\nSeptember to December, 2003 -- Senior Facilitator\r\nCollected background information and data on stakeholder interests (as provided by USFWS and others).  Facilitated and moderated the annual meeting and developed a meeting summary of major themes and findings.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nState Water Plan, GA DNR/Environmental Protection Division, Throughout Georgia\r\nJanuary 2006 to July, 2007 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nFacilitated dialogue for the Georgia Environmental Protection Division’s Chattahoochee River Basin Advisory Committee.  This effort was designed to funnel watershed specific commentary on the possible components of the first Comprehensive Statewide Water Plan to the Georgia Water Council (the coordinating committee for the Comprehensive Statewide Water Management Planning Act).  The four major discussion areas addressed how to:\r\n?\tMinimize withdrawals of water by increasing conservation, reuse, and efficiency\r\n?\tMaximize returns to the basin through managing interbasin transfers and uses of on-site sewage disposal systems, and land application of treated wastewater where water quantity is limited\r\n?\tMeet instream and offstream demands for water through surface storage, aquifer management, and reduction of water demands\r\n?\tProtect water quality by reducing discharges of pollutants to streams and runoff from land, so as not to exceed the assimilative capacity of the streams\r\n(Employed by the NewFields Companies during this effort.)\r\n\r\nGeorgia Marsh Hammocks, GA DNR/Coastal Resources Division, Coastal Georgia\r\nJune 2002 to July, 2003 -- Senior Facilitator\r\nDesigned and guided a group of stakeholders in a process convened to create a fair and equitable approach to marsh hammock conservation and management while protecting the integrity of the Georgia Coastal Marshland Protection Act.  As directed by the Georgia Department of Natural Resources, stakeholders were assembled to develop specific public policy recommendations for the protection of coastal marshlands and the future management of Georgia’s coastal marsh hammocks.  After 10 months of deliberations, all 24 participants agreed on recommendations protecting private property rights, conserving precious coastal resources, and creating incentives for proper stewardship.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nStatewide Stormwater Management Program, NC DENR, Throughout North Carolina\r\nDecember 1999 to October 2000 -- Senior Facilitator\r\nGuided North Carolina’s Department of Environment and Natural Resources (NC DENR) and other stakeholders in developing a statewide stormwater management program.  The promulgation of U.S. EPA’s Final Rule for Phase II’s NPDES Stormwater Program provided the impetus for NC DENR to strategically view its stormwater management program.  In doing so, it decided to apply the Enlibra Principles to the development of a comprehensive stormwater program based on the most current and best available science.  The negotiated baseline program will be expandable to incorporate additional elements and accommodate economic development and growth.  It provides for the new efficiencies via the consolidation of existing stormwater programs.  The 62-page agreement represented the views of 27 of 28 stakeholders from local government, the environmental community, development interests, and the state, among others.\r\n(Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nGroundwater in Texas, TX Water Development Board, Austin, TX\r\nOctober, 1999 to March, 2000 -- Senior Facilitator\r\nDesigned the collaborative process to study the management of groundwater resources for the Texas Water Development Board.  Developed, organized, and managed a groundwater management workshop for more than 125 attendees and participants.  Subsequently convened a series of meetings to discuss critical issues, including:\r\n?\tGroundwater district operation\r\n?\tPotential for greater cooperation between neighboring and distant districts\r\n?\tRecommendations to the Texas Senate Natural Resources Committee on the future of strategic and sustainable groundwater management\r\n(Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\n \r\nEstuarine Shoreline Protection, NC DENR/Division of Coastal Management, Coastal, NC\r\nMay, 1999 to August, 1999 -- Senior Facilitator\r\nNavigated a dialogue for North Carolina DENR’s Division of Coastal Management, working with partners and other stakeholders to maintain water quality and protect estuarine habitats via a Shoreline Protection framework.  An 80-page agreement was signed by 27 of 28 stakeholders.  This agreement presented statutory, regulatory, voluntary, conservation, and research policies and activities for protecting the resource.  Agreements forged here resolved historical water quality disputes and will helped define growth and development in the region.\r\n(Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nRegulatory Conflict Assessment, Process Design and Guidance\r\n\r\nInvasive Species:  Golden Algae in Dunkard Creek, WV DEP, Charleston, WV\r\nNovember, 2009 to February, 2010 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nProvided consultative services in connection with facilitating meetings and discussions, and the free exchange of data and information among agency scientists, outside experts, and others for investigations of the presence and source of Prymnesium parvum (a.k.a., golden algae) in Dunkard Creek, and other scientific issues relating to the occurrence of toxic blooms of that algae, appropriate protocols for sampling and analyses, potential preventive and abatement measures, and related matters as agreed to by the Principals.  \r\n\r\nCWA Section 401 and 404 Guidance in WV, WV DEP, Charleston, WV\r\nNovember, 2007 to March, 2008 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nDesigned and guided a dialogue intended to establish an improved framework for joint review processes that satisfy WV DEP/Department of Mining Resources and the United States Army Corps of Engineers for mitigation requirements under the Clean Water Act Sections 401 and 404 regulatory programs.  Contributors to this guidance came together in the spirit of remedying a trying process in which the Federal and state regulatory bodies oftentimes were in conflict in the development, certification and approval of mitigation plans created by the coal industry before a mining company commenced operations.  This guidance document was crafted with an eye toward creating a “comprehensive, doable mitigation program that is consistent with Federal and state requirements and keeps all parties out of the judicial process.” \r\n\r\nSE Diesel Collaborative, US EPA Region IV, Atlanta, GA\r\nApril, 2006 to September, 2006 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nProduced a two-day kickoff meeting of the Southeast Diesel Collaborative.  This meeting was designed to highlight strategies that promote clean renewable diesel and emerging technology for the agriculture, construction, and on-road sectors.  The April, 2006 conference provided opportunities for regulatory agencies, non-governmental organizations, industry representatives from the agriculture, construction and on-road sectors, and other stakeholders to actively learn how to reduce diesel emissions through alternative fuels and retrofit devices, and successfully collaborate on clean air initiatives.  Through education and information exchange, participants acquired the tools necessary to begin identifying cost-effective strategies to reduce diesel emission pollution.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nContamination in Anniston, Alabama, U.S. EPA Region IV, Anniston, AL\r\nJanuary, 2006 to April, 2006 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nDesigned and facilitated dialogue on behalf of the Anniston Community Advisory Group to the Consent Decree at the Anniston/Solutia Superfund site.  Managed community input on a variety of issues at its monthly meetings.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nLandfill Siting in Clayton, County GA, Schreeder, Wheeler and Flint, Clayton County, GA\r\nApril, 2005 to July, 2005 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nFacilitated a “Facility Issues Negotiation” between Clayton County residents and a landfill company seeking to site a construction and demolition waste landfill in a low income, ethnically diverse community.  Successfully executed four sequential tasks Project Planning, Dialogue Design, Facilitation; and Summary Reporting.  His approach maximized the understanding and involvement of critical constituencies and increased the ability of the state and the landfill company to manage the project’s pace, direction and resources.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nEPEAT, US EPA Headquarters, National Process\r\nJanuary, 2003 to January, 2004 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nWorked with the U.S. EPA’s Office of Solid Waste to assess the collaborative environment for developing an “Electronic Product Environmental Assessment Tool” (EPEAT).  This Conflict Assessment SM related where the various interest groups were with regard to ideologies and the end-of-life management of electronics products in the United States.  In conjunction with our experiences in facilitating other sector-based environmental initiatives and our involvement with the EPEAT Steering Committee, developed recommendations for a road map for the future of this project.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nFacility Planning Area Program in Illinois, IL EPA, Throughout Illinois\r\nFebruary 2003 to July, 2003 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nOriginally, IEPA’s role in facilities planning was directed by §208 of the Federal Clean Water Act.  The FPA process was largely created to satisfy the requirements of the Federal Construction Grants Program.  Faced with questions on how to improve or possibly eliminate the program, was asked to conduct stakeholder interviews and complete a state-by-state comparative analysis to inform recommendations for managing the future of the program.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nPolicy Analysis/Sustainability\r\n\r\nSEE Change Program, WV DEP, Throughout West Virginia\r\nJune, 2009 to December, 2009 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nHelped the West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection to develop a Sustainability and Environmental Excellence Program, an initiative that will reward government and industrial facilities for going beyond compliance in their environmental protection policies.  Interviewed stakeholders on all sides of the issue to develop a clear understanding of potential conflicts.  Designed and guided a stakeholder dialogue in the summer of 2009.  Drafted legislation for consideration in the 2010 Legislative Session.\r\n\r\nGreen Accounting, United States Air Force, Langley, Virginia\r\nNovember, 2008 to March, 2009 – Sustainability Analyst \r\nWorked with a team to develop the constructs for modeling environmental financial statements for the United States Air Force in a Demonstration Project at Barksdale Air Force Base.  Used various documents and financial estimates to help the team determine the appropriate “currency” for the environmental accounting system—deciding between dollars, carbon, sustainability units, or other considerations.  Used the information to develop an accounting system that linked a newly designed Chart of Accounts with a double-sided journal entry system supported by a General Ledger and Trial Balance.  These were created to feed into an Income Statement and Balance Sheet.  Presented the results to U.S. AF Executives at Langley Air Force base in Virginia.  (Served as an independent consultant during this effort)\r\n\r\nStrategic Highway Corridors NC DOT, Raleigh, North Carolina\r\nMarch, 2005 to June, 2005 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nCompleted a Conflict Assessment for the North Carolina Department of Transportation (NC DOT) prior to designing the process for a Strategic Highway Corridors Summit.  NC DOT adopted the Strategic Highway Corridors (SHC) concept as a part of the Statewide Transportation Plan.  The SHC concept, when implemented, will protect and maximize the mobility and connectivity on a core set of highway corridors, while promoting environmental stewardship by maximizing the use of existing facilities (to the extent possible), and fostering economic prosperity through the quick and efficient movement of people and goods.  The concept offers NCDOT and its stakeholders’ opportunities to consider long-term vision when making land-use decisions and design and operational decisions on the highway system.  The creation of a long-term vision identifies the ultimately desired facility type (freeway, expressway, boulevard, or thoroughfare) for each corridor.  Using the Conflict Assessment SM, designed a productive dialogue—one that lays out the roadmap for all partnering agencies to take part in the implementation phase.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nAtlanta Downtown Bus Study, Atlanta Regional Commission, Atlanta, GA\r\nApril, 2005 to October, 2005 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nGuided a study devising a mutually agreeable solution that accommodated existing and future bus transit service while protecting the character and pedestrian environment of the thoroughfares in the Peachtree Street Corridor in downtown and midtown Atlanta.  The study resulted in new bus routes and stops in downtown and midtown Atlanta and supported a livable community while improving access and travel.  Through facilitated dialogue, participants identified and consolidated transportation and community development goals and objectives, evaluated the study area's physical and operational characteristics, gathered public input, developed and assessed potential alternatives, and proposed short- and long-term recommendations in the corridor for bus transit services and access to those services.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nSorting Tools Dialogue, Multistate Working Group, White Plains, NY\r\nJanuary, 2005 to September, 2005 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nDesigned a dialogue that launched a discussion on how to construct an understandable and effective sorting process—for policy, regulatory, and management purposes—that recognizes the full range of innovative tools and allows organizations and individuals to better determine which tool or tools are most apt in a particular set of circumstances.  These tools range from traditional enforcement mechanisms, compliance assistance programs, auditing, and environmental management systems to corporate social responsibility mechanisms, insurance considerations, public reporting, public access to data, and many others.  It was considered imperative to use a broad range of tools in fashioning tailor-made responses to specific risks to solve environmental problems.  The MSWG noted that the tools are not an end in and of themselves and that a problem-solving approach (to environmental issues) selects the most important tasks and then the appropriate tools in each case, rather than deciding on the important tools and selecting the tasks to fit.  The tools were deemed to be part of a strategy designed to maximize environmental outcomes.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nSustainability Assessment, WV DEP, Throughout West Virginia\r\nApril, 2004 to November, 2004 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nHelped the West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection to develop a Sustainability Assessment.  Sustainable Development is a broad concept that addresses the way in which activities impact the economy, the environment, and social well-being.  While it is generally accepted that development should be sustainable in all three of these dimensions, practical application of the concept is both complex and challenging.  During the course of this project, more than 150 leaders from in and around West Virginia were contacted, many of whom spent a significant amount of time contributing to the contents of this assessment.  Although their understanding of sustainability greatly varied, all presented valued perspectives.  Commonly, several “drivers and barriers” were consistently referenced factors across the many interviews—among them, the “mountaineer” culture that pervades cities and suburbs.  These were the most important factors in the development of a “Road Map for Sustainability.”  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nVirginia CAN, VA DEQ (throughout Virginia)\r\nMarch, 2004 to June, 2004 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nServed Virginia’s Department of Environmental Quality as it worked to establish the Virginia Comprehensive Assistance Network (VA CAN).  A partnership between representatives of state, Federal, local, and not-for profit organizations, VA CAN's mission is to develop and promote communication that allows for the expansion of participants' knowledge.  VA CAN provides a vehicle for its partners to cooperate and leverage their individual resources for the benefit of the Commonwealth's business community.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\n \r\nSector Strategies and Voluntary Programs, US EPA Headquarters, National Processes\r\n1998 to 2002 (Multiple Contracting Vehicles and Task Orders) -- Senior Facilitator \r\nManaged all discussions relative to the regional implementation of U.S. EPA’s Strategic Goals Program of the Metal Plating and Finishing Sector in New York, New Jersey, Virginia, Missouri, and, occasionally, California.  These efforts brought together all stakeholders in the regions (for the first time in history) in a voluntary program that delivers cleaner, cheaper, and smarter ways of doing business across the industry.  Designed and guided dialogue related to the Printing Sector of the Common Sense Initiative and the Meat Processing Sector in the Sector Strategies Initiative.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nA Framework for Cooperation, GA DNR/Environmental Protection Division, Atlanta, GA\r\nFebruary, 1999 to September, 1999 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nFacilitated meetings involving the directors of air quality organizations in metropolitan Atlanta.  This process addressed inefficiencies in organization and communication between entities and resulted in the completion of a Master Plan for coordination and communication between entities.  The Master Plan restructured many of the activities of individual organizations in an effort to maximize the effectiveness of Federal CMAQ resources.  Following the development of the Master Plan, agreement was forged on two more pragmatic, Operational Plans—Public Outreach and Employer Services.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nStrategic Planning \r\nStrategic Planning, Hawai`i State Office of Planning, Honolulu, HI\r\nNovember, 2006 to March, 2007 -- Senior Facilitator\r\nCompleted a strategic planning project for the State Office of Planning (OP) and Coastal Zone Management Program (CZM) in Hawaii’s Department of Business, Economic Development and Tourism.  This process involved (1) the collection and analysis of information and staff and external stakeholder perspectives related to OP and the CZM program, (2) performance of an interactive and iterative strategic planning process for OP as a whole and the CZM program to clarify OP and CZM mission, vision, values, and functions; formulate strategies to improve organizational and program effectiveness; and increase coordination and collaboration across OP programs, and (3) the preparation of organizational strategic plans for the CZM program and OP, which set forth five-year action agendas and timetables for implementation.  (Employed by the NewFields Companies during this effort)\r\n\r\nEnvironment, Energy and Transportation, Environmental Council of the States, Washington, DC\r\nJuly, 2002 to September, 2002 -- Senior Facilitator\r\nWorked with ECOS, AASHTO, NASEO, and NARUC to build on the success of the National Energy, Environment, and Transportation Summit.  Continued dialogue among key participants through a series of meetings that results in a common vision and a set of operating principles for energy, environment, and transportation.  Built bridges and relationships between the state associations responsible for energy, the environment, and transportation.  Developed a common vision and operating principles between state officials responsible for each of these issue areas, and created a final product—a Memorandum of Understanding—that became a touchstone for all concerned.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nStrategic Planning for an NGO, GDDF, Charleston, SC\r\nMarch, 2005 to May, 2005 -- Senior Facilitator\r\nDesigned and guided a strategic planning dialogue for the Gaylord and Dorothy Donnelley Foundation.  Assisted the group in achieving all goals, including the furtherance of collaborative relations within the group, productive strategic discussions on future financial flows between the organization and its grantees, achieving mutual understandings for the decision criteria that applied in evaluating individual and collaborative project proposals, defining the “form and feel” of the reciprocal relations between the organization and its grantees, and the development of a set of goals for the group’s collaborative efforts.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nGA Solid Waste Trust Fund, GA Department of Community Affairs, Atlanta, GA\r\nJuly, 2002 to August, 2002 -- Senior Facilitator\r\nDesigned and guided discussions geared toward developing a Strategic Plan for the management of Georgia's Solid Waste Trust Fund.  While working for the Georgia Department of Community Affairs, helped gather an interagency group and manage dialogue structured to overcome territorial boundaries, maximize cooperation, and leverage limited funding dollars.\r\n(Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nStrategic Planning for Environmental Justice Group, US EPA Region IV, Atlanta, GA\r\nMay, 1999 to July, 1999 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nImproved relations, effectiveness, and efficiency among members of the Environmental Justice Cross-Divisional Team for U.S. EPA Region IV.  Through structured dialogue, participants developed goals, strategies, and tactics, decided their own best organizational structure, and began the process of developing systems for accomplishing their many duties.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nLarge Conferences and Workshops\r\n\r\nGreen Microfinance Conference, Wharton School, Philadelphia, PA\r\nJanuary, 2006 to June, 2006 – Senior Facilitator \r\nDesigned and guided the Green Microfinance Roundtable for the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania.  The purpose of the roundtable discussion was to provide practitioners, donors, and researchers an opportunity to discuss the opportunities and challenges in the area of microfinance and environmental sustainability.  The overarching theme was dialogue on whether or not microfinance could address environmental problems, and thereby contribute to Millennium Development goal number seven concerning environmental sustainability.  This roundtable built on the 2004 Microenterprise and the Environment Conference held at Valley Forge, Pennsylvania, which resulted in the formulation of the Microenterprise and Environment Guiding Principles, developed by the conference participants.  The set of key principles provide guidance for microenterprise and microfinance initiatives in protecting the environment.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nBreaking New Ground Brownfields Conferences, Wildlife Habitat Council, Washington, DC, New Orleans, LA and Seattle, WA\r\n2001 to 2005 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nServed as Lead Facilitator on Breaking New Ground:  The Benefits of Ecological Enhancements in Brownfield Development & Superfund/RCRA Remediation Projects for the Wildlife Habitat Council.  The conference was structured to be both presentation-oriented and interactive.  The conference was designed to provide a forum for participants to:\r\n?\tConsider how Federal, state, and/or local rules and regulations help or hinder wildlife habitat restoration and/or improvement\r\n?\tIdentify drivers and barriers to ecological enhancement in RCRA, Superfund, and Brownfields redevelopment\r\n?\tIllustrate and present examples of restored habitat and redevelopment from specific cases across America\r\n?\tShare the wealth of technical, social, and institutional knowledge, along with available resources, that can assist in overcoming barriers for ecological enhancements\r\n\r\nWorked with the Wildlife Habitat Council on its third and fourth Restoring Greenspace conferences held in Region VI and U.S. EPA Region IX in 2005 and 2006, respectively.  These annual conferences are convened to encourage and enable site managers, local planners, and communities to incorporate ecological reuse as part of remediation techniques or end uses in their Brownfield, RCRA, Superfund or Leaking Underground Storage Tank properties.  Each year, these regional conferences present a first-hand look at innovative programs, new initiatives, and case studies that highlight the incorporation of ecological reuse practices in site restoration and identify strategic methods associated with the implementation of ecological enhancements on contaminated lands based on the white paper, “Making the Case for Ecological Enhancements.”  The conference objectives were to: \r\n?\tIdentify ecological approaches to cleanup and the cost benefits of ecological reuse through case studies\r\n?\tIdentify performance metrics for success in ecological restoration\r\n?\tAssess regulatory obstacles to using ecological enhancements on contaminated properties\r\n?\tEvaluate approaches for obtaining constructive and meaningful stakeholder involvement\r\n(Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nPrivate Lands Conference, National Governors’ Association, Phoenix, AZ\r\nNovember, 2000 to April, 2001 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nManaged dialogue during a landmark summit designed to spark nationwide dialogue about publicly supported (and voluntary) working lands conservation.  Conservation on our privately owned working land provides clean water and clean air, keeps soil healthy and productive, provides habitat for fish and wildlife, and contributes to our overall quality of life.  The second day of the National Governors’ Association Conference (Private Lands, Public Benefits:  A Policy Summit on Working Lands Conservation) was a workshop discussion involving approximately 60 invited attendees.\r\n\r\nDeveloping and Strengthening State Growth Initiatives, National Governors’ Association, Minneapolis, MN and Washington, DC\r\nNovember, 2000 to April, 2001 -- Senior Facilitator \r\nFacilitated sessions on Smart Growth designed to seek opportunities for Governors and their Senior Staff to bring smart growth policies into practice.  Discussions at both the Eastern and Western Regional Policy Forums centered on information sharing and the application of tools across state boundaries.  (Employed by Consensus Solutions, Incorporated during this effort)\r\n\r\nTraining\r\n\r\nEnvironmental Finance, US EPA Headquarters, Central and Eastern Europe\r\n1995 to 1998 – Special Assistant\r\nDesigned, developed, refined and taught “Financing Environmental Investments” course to foreign policy makers in Central Europe.  Sponsored by EPA/OIA and USAID, the material focused on the development of revenue raising instruments for environmental purposes.  The course was further adapted to audiences in Bulgaria, Poland, Malaysia, and Hong Kong.  (Employed by US EPA during this effort)\r\n\r\nPublications and Presentations\r\n\r\nLessons Learned from Collaborative Approaches developed for the National Opportunities Task Force of the President’s Council on Sustainable Development, April 1997.\r\nHarnessing the Region’s Brain Power, editorial written for the Atlanta Journal Constitution, October 21, 1998.\r\nCollaborative Processes at Work on the State Level:  A Case Study from North Carolina, article written for ECO States, October, 1999.\r\nState Scan:  A Compendium of State Information and Resources to Help Businesses Achieve Better Environmental Performance written for U.S. EPA’s Sector Strategies Division, October, 2001.\r\nCommunity Impact Assessment – Southern Regional Workshop; conducted an “Empathy Building Exercise” for more than 250 people.  Presented on the topic of “Illusion of Control.”  December 5-7, 2001.\r\nSustainable Land Development and Restoration:  Decision Consequence Analysis (Decision Implementation Chapter on Stakeholder Engagement), El Sevier, Summer, 2009\r\n	2015-02-27 05:25:01.133106	2015-02-27 05:25:01.133106	464
