1162	Malcolm		Shields	shiemalc@isu.edu	(208) 282-5719		Idaho State University 921 South 8th Avenue		Pocatello	ID	83209	0	Associate Professor of Microbiology	Idaho State University, Department of Biological Sciences	0	(Source: http://www.isu.edu/bios/Professors_Staff/shields_m.shtml)\r\n\r\nAssociate Professor of Microbiology\r\nMLS (ASCP)\r\n\r\nshiemalc@isu.edu\r\n(208) 282-5719\r\nRoom 604 Garrison Building\r\n\r\nResearch interests include: Bacterial toxin-gene movement and selection within microbial communities; The selective role of bacterial toxins of pathogenic bacteria outside the animal host; Engineering of bacterial fuel cells for generation of electricity; Mechanism of bacterial damage by water disinfection systems and their survival and release from municipal treatment systems; The role of regulatory gene products in the developmental cycle of Dictyostelium; Molecular diagnostic platforms for pathogen detection and identification; Design of genetic immunization vectors.\r\n\r\nEducation\r\n\r\nPh.D. (1985) Bacterial Genetics and Physiology, Department of Microbiology,  The University of Tennessee, Knoxville, TN\r\nM.S.  (1980) Microbial Physiology, Department of Bacteriology and Biochemistry University of Idaho, Moscow, ID\r\nB.S. (1978) Biology, Department of Biology, Virginia Tech, Blacksburg, VA\r\nB.S.  (2009) Clinical Laboratory Science, Idaho State University, Pocatello, ID\r\n\r\nBiographical Sketch\r\nDr. Shields has been in the Department of Biological Sciences at Idaho State University since December of 2001 as an Associate Professor. He earned tenure at ISU in 2008.  He came here following 10 years at the University of West Florida where he was a tenured Associate professor. He received his undergraduate degree in 1978 in Biology from Virginia Tech, Blacksburg, VA. \r\nHe received his Masters degree in Microbiology and Biochemistry from the Unversity of Idaho, Moscow, ID in 1980, where he worked on fungal metabolite identification of an antifungal compound produce by a soil Penicillium urticae in the laboratory of Dr. Al Lingg.  He received his Ph.D. in Bacterial Genetics and Physiology in 1985 from the Department of Microbiology of the University of Tennessee, Knoxville, TN.  Here he studied under Dr. Gary Sayler elucidating bacterial biodegradative pathways and genetics of bacterial polychlorinated biphenyl metabolism.  After coming to Idaho State University, Dr. Shields began a collaboration with Drs. Peter Sheridan, Cathy Spiegel and Larry Farrell to examine the genetics and physiology of bacterial toxins as they pertain to human health.  This quickly led to an interest in Clinical Laboratory Sciences in which Dr. Shields has now taught since 2007.  In order obtain his MLS certification, Dr. Shields completed the CLS program here at ISU, earning a second bachelors degree in the process.\r\n\r\nTeaching areas: Genetics, Microbiology, Molecular Biology Laboratory Techniques, Environmental Biotechnology and Medical Molecular Diagnostics.\r\n\r\nPublications (Indicates *undergraduate or **graduate student coauthors)\r\n\r\nEffects of electrode surface area on electricity generation in an air-cathode single chamber microbial fuel cell fed with potato processing wastewater.  Chikashi Sato, Rishika,Sharma Lamichhane**, Malcolm Shields  and  Yoshiko Fujita .  In Review\r\n\r\nIntragenomic heterogeneity of the 16S rRNA gene in strain UFO1 caused by a 100 bp insertion in helix 6, by Ray, Allison**; Connon, Stephanie; Gilbreath, Jeremy*; Shields, Malcolm; Newby, Deborah; Fujita, Yoshiko; Magnuson, Timothy; Sheridan, Peter. Submitted to FEMS Microbiology Ecology.  Accepted.\r\n\r\nChikashi Sato,  Reymer G. Martinez**, Malcolm S. Shields, Alba Perez-Gracia, Marco P. Schoen.  2009.  Behavior of microbial fuel cell in a startup phase. International Journal of Environment and Waste Management.   1:36-51.\r\n\r\nJeremy J. Gilbreath*, Malcolm S. Shields, Rebekah L. Smith**, Larry D. Farrell, Peter P. Sheridan, and Kat