1164	Charles	E	Feigley	cfeigle@mailbox.sc.edu	(803) 777-6360		Publich Health Research Center (PHRC), 501D 	921 Assembly Street	Columbia	SC	29208	0	Professor	University of South Carolina, Environmental Health Sciences	30	(Source: http://www.sph.sc.edu/facultystaffpages/facstaffdetails.php?ID=11)\r\n\r\nCharles  E.  Feigley  PhD\r\nProfessor\r\nPrincipal Investigator, Center for Public Health Preparedness\r\n\r\nPublich Health Research Center (PHRC), 501D\r\n921 Assembly Street\r\nColumbia, SC 29208\r\n\r\nSecondary Address:\r\nCenter for Public Health Preparedness\r\nSuite 700\r\n1233 Washington Street\r\nColumbia, SC 29201\r\n803-978-7578\r\n\r\nPhone: (803) 777-6360\r\nFax: (803) 777-3391\r\nEmail: cfeigle@mailbox.sc.edu\r\n\r\nInterest:\r\nCharles E. Feigley, PhD, CIH, is a Professor in the USC Department of Environmental Health Sciences, and is a Co-Principal Investigator of the USC-CPHP grant. He has over 30 years' experience in the areas of air pollution, industrial hygiene and exposure assessment. He is Director of the NIOSH-sponsored, ABET-accredited industrial hygiene training program at USC. He teaches classes in industrial ventilation, air pollution, evaluation of occupational environments, and aerosol science. In his early research, he led experimental studies of: evaporative emissions from painted surfaces, diffusive sampling devices, the permeation of polymeric materials used for chemical protective clothing, and the filtration of air for air cleaning and air contaminant sampling. Dr. Feigley has been Principal Investigator on several collaborative projects on human exposure assessment and environmental epidemiology including investigations of the health effects of hazardous waste incinerator emissions, and the impact of trichlorethylene exposure in children. His other research includes funded studies on chemical markers of airborne bacteria in schools, and improvement of occupational exposure estimation through investigations of the fundamental determinants of workroom exposure.\r\n\r\nDr. Feigley served on the NIOSH Study Section (for review of research grant applications). He was a member of the National Academy of Sciences (NAS) Committee on Toxicology (COT) for three terms of three years each. In conjunction with his work on the Committee, he has participated in: the development of exposure limits for the international space station (NASA), the review of the Army Environmental Hygiene Agency's Toxicology Program, the development of guidelines for setting Community Emergency Exposure Levels for hazardous substances, and the establishment of U.S. Navy Permissible Exposure Levels for JP-5 and JP-8 jet fuels. Also, Dr. Feigley chaired a COT subcommittee assessing risks from hazardous waste incinerator emissions to personnel at a Naval Air Station in Atsugi, Japan. He is currently a member of the NAS committee to review the Office of Management and Budget's Risk Assessment Bulletin.\r\n\r\nDr. Feigley co-led a network of CPHPs that produced the "Occupational Safety and Worker Preparedness Exemplar." The group developed a "Chemical/Radiation Preparedness Resource Kit" which was completed in October 2007.\r\n\r\nSelected Publications:\r\n\r\nBusbin, D., C.E. Feigley, D.W. Underhill, and D. Salzberg. A Second Look at the Palmes' Diffusive Sampler. J. Air and Waste Management Assoc. 56:1431-1439 (2006).\r\n\r\nLee, E., J.A. Khan, C.E. Feigley, M.R. Ahmed, and J.R. Hussey. An investigation of air inlet types in mixing ventilation. In press. Building and Environment, Available online January (2006).\r\n\r\nKhan, J.A., C.E. Feigley, E. Lee, M.R. Ahmed, and S. Tamana. Effects of inlet and exhaust locations and emitted gas density on indoor air contaminant concentrations. Buildings and Environment. 41:851-863 (2006).\r\n\r\nLee, E., C.E. Feigley, J.A. Khan, and J.R. Hussey. < a href="http://annhyg.oxfordjournals.org/papbyrecent.dtl">The effect of temperature differences on the distribution of an airborne contaminant in an 