sis among a large number of hypothesis tests and applied this method to estimate the number of carcinogens and anti-carcinogens among 400 chemicals studied by the National Toxicology Program.\r\n    * Assessed the risk from asbestos exposure to children in school buildings.\r\n    * Developed risk assessments for occupational exposure to numerous substances, including asbestos, benzene, and arsenic.\r\n    * Developed the "linearized multistage" approach to assessing carcinogenic risk from low exposures.\r\n    * Directed review of risk assessment approaches used by USEPA and made recommendations regarding these approaches.\r\n    * Developed the "benchmark method" used by regulatory agencies as a replacement for the NOAEL in safety assessment.\r\n    * Conducted benchmark analyses from epidemiological data on arsenic and mercury.\r\n\r\nEducation:\r\n\r\nPh.D., Mathematics, Montana State University; M.A., Mathematics, University of Denver; B.S., Electrical Engineering, Louisiana Tech University\r\n\r\nPractice Areas\r\n\r\nHealth Sciences: Applied Epidemiology\r\nHealth Sciences: Risk Assessment & Risk Management	2015-02-27 05:25:02.821877	2015-02-27 05:25:02.821877	481
