1191	Arthur	Chuck	Gordon	cgordon@terranext.net	480-496-4100	602-377-3169	4050 E Cotton Center Blvd	Ste 73	Phoenix	AZ	85040	90	Senior Geologist	Terranext LLC	30	Arthur J. Gordon, R.G.\r\nOffice Manager, Senior Geologist   \r\n\r\nEducation\r\n- M.S. Geology  - Arizona State University – Tempe, AZ (1977)\r\n\r\n- B.A. Geology  - San Francisco State University – San Francisco, CA (1974)\r\n\r\nRegistrations\r\n- Registered Geologist, Arizona (13937, 1981)\r\n\r\n- Registered Geologist, California (3671, 1981)\r\n\r\n- Registered Geologist, Wyoming, (3455, 2002)\r\n\r\n- Registered Geologist, Utah, (6908225-2250, 2008)\r\n\r\n-Certified Environmental Manager, Nevada (EM-2133, 2008)\r\n\r\nSUMMARY:\r\nMr. Gordon has 30 years of hydrogeological and environmental experience.  He has managed a wide variety of projects including remedial investigations/feasibility studies (RI/FS), remedial actions, environmental assessments of mining and other properties, negotiation and litigation support, removal oversight, community involvement, sampling/analyses of environmental media, records management, real property acquisition support, and integrated Phase I/II site assessments/ investigations.  Project management responsibilities include planning, scheduling, budgeting, personnel supervision, and report writing/editing.\r\n\r\nEXPERIENCE:\r\n\r\n1999-Present: Terranext, Phoenix, Arizona\r\nMr. Gordon provides senior project management on hydrogeologic, remediation, and Brownfield project sites contaminated with metals, PCBs, and volatile organic compounds (VOCs). His responsibilities include development of site investigation/remediation strategies, preparation of work, sampling/analysis, quality assurance, and health and safety plans, management of subcontractors, estimation of project costs, hydrogeologic interpretation, and report issuance. \r\n\r\nBureau of Indian Affairs (BIA) Site Characterization, Gallup NM\r\nMr. Gordon managed a site characterization of the Gamerco Warehouse site located near Gallup, NM.  Operations at the site included incineration of out-of-date/specification items and burial of drums, metal, products, and other waste.  Terranext performed the following scope of work:\r\n\r\n•\tPrepare work plan, and sampling and analysis plan\r\n•\tExcavate backhoe trenches at suspected waste areas and characterize waste\r\n•\tCharacterize/profile investigative-derived waste for off-site disposal\r\n•\tPerform sampling/analysis of excavated material, and native soils at base of trenches\r\n•\tPrepare report identifying recommended soil cleanup levels and presenting specific recommendations for site closure\r\n\r\nBIA LUST Site Characterization Projects, Arizona and Utah\r\nMr. Gordon managed a LUST site characterization in Poston, Arizona (Colorado River Indian Tribe) and an identical project in Fort Duchesne, Utah (Ute Indian Reservation).  The facilities are primarily maintenance/ construction yards.  A site reconnaissance, review of existing records, and interviews with BIA site personnel were first performed to identify historic operational, chemical use/storage, and waste disposal activities.  The results were presented in work plans.  \r\n\r\nSubsurface investigations using Geoprobe and hollow-stem auger drilling technology were performed.  Depending on the area being investigated, collected samples were analyzed for total petroleum hydrocarbons, purgeable aromatic compounds, and total lead.  In addition, based on past site agricultural use, samples from certain areas also were analyzed for chlorinated and/or organophosphorous pesticides, chlorinated herbicides, VOCs, and/or semi-VOCs.  Groundwater monitor wells were then installed/sampled.  Reports were prepared for review by BIA and EPA.  \r\n\r\nWest Van Buren Area State Superfund Site, Phoenix, Arizona\r\nProject manager for RI of 15 square mile area in west Phoenix with extensive groundwater contamination.  Chlorinated solvents from multiple sources contaminate the upper and middle alluvial units.   Project tasks included installation of over 50 monitor wells ranging up to 400 feet in depth installed using rotosonic, dual wall percussion, and mud rotary drilling methods.  The existing monitor well network currently numbers over 100 wells and sampling is performed semi-annually; groundwater monitoring reports are prepared after each sampling round.  The draft RI report was prepared, issued by ADEQ for public comment, and included:\r\n\r\n•\tEvaluation of site history\r\n•\tDescription of site characteristics, including physiography, meteorology, surface water features, geology, hydrogeology\r\n•\tEvaluation of the nature and extent of contamination, including identification of contaminants/sources, and evaluation of ground and surface water quality\r\n•\tContaminant fate and transport evaluation, including potential routes of migration and factors affecting contaminant migration\r\n•\tLand and water use evaluation\r\n\r\nEast Washington Fluff State Superfund Site, Phoenix, Arizona\r\nProject Manager for the early response action (ERA) at this WQARF site near downtown Phoenix.  The objective of the ERA was to design and construct a compacted soil cap to eliminate the direct exposure pathway to contaminated media.  The following remedial activities were performed prior to cap construction:\r\n\r\n•\tPermits/waivers to implement the ERA were obtained\r\n•\tAutomobile shredder fluff required removal and off-site disposal as RCRA/TSCA waste; 5,900 tons of waste was transported/ disposed at permitted facility in Beatty, NV\r\n•\tSurficial solid waste was also removed and disposed off-site\r\n•\tThree USTs were removed from the site \r\n•\tAlmost 600 tons of off-site soils exceeding the residential SRL for lead were excavated/disposed off-site \r\n\r\nSubsequently, an RI was performed that included the following:\r\n•\tPrepare work, sampling, and quality assurance project plans\r\n•\tPerformance of a surface geophysical survey\r\n•\tGeoprobe investigation and soil boring drilling/sampling\r\n•\tDescription of site stratigraphy and hydrogeology\r\n•\tEvaluation of nature and extent of contamination, including preparation of depth-specific isochemical contour maps \r\n•\tFate/transport modeling addressing  infiltration/percolation of contaminants and potential for groundwater contamination \r\n•\tHuman health risk assessment consisting of exposure and toxicity assessments, and health risk characterization \r\n•\tPreparation of draft and final RI reports\r\n\r\nBased upon the findings of the RI, a feasibility study and preliminary remedial action plan were prepared. \r\n\r\nCooper Road/Commerce Avenue State Superfund Site, Gilbert\r\nProject manager for this site where groundwater is contaminated with VOCs and municipal production wells are located in close proximity. Prepared workplan for the project.  Planned/ implemented the installation of two monitor wells, including a deep well to 750 feet below ground surface utilizing mud rotary drilling method, obtained a right-of-way permit from the Town of Gilbert, managed investigative-derived waste, performed/interpreted geophysical logging, performed well development and groundwater sampling, and prepared reports.  \r\n\r\nDepartment of Economic Security Fueling Facility, Coolidge\r\nProject manager for LUST site characterization and corrective action plan preparation.  Characterization included subsurface soil sampling, analysis using a mobile laboratory, and monitor well installation/sampling.  The presence of free product necessitated implementation of free product removal utilizing passive free product recovery. Based on the findings of the site characterization report, a corrective action plan was prepared. Also performed was a pre-design investigation consisting of the installation of soil vapor extraction and air sparge wells, pilot-testing these wells, and utilizing the pilot-test results to perform remedial design.\r\n\r\nFormer Miller Valley Exxon, Prescott, Arizona\r\nProject manager for LUST site characterization/corrective action plan preparation.  Characterization of this site included work plan preparation, and monitor well installation and sampling of both alluvial and bedrock wells.  Planned/implemented installation of monitor wells utilizing both air rotary and hollow stem auger drilling methods, managed investigative-derived waste, performed well development/groundwater sampling.  Based on the findings of the site characterization report, a corrective action plan was prepared. \r\n\r\n1996-1998: Self Employed/Community College Teacher\r\n\r\nWest Central Phoenix WQARF Site, Phoenix, Arizona\r\nPrepared Phase II RI/FS workplan for facility in North Plume Area of West Central Phoenix site.  Designed hydrogeologic investigation including monitor well placement, aquifer testing, and selection of wells for groundwater monitoring network. \r\n\r\n1995-1996:  Earth Tech, Phoenix, Arizona \r\n\r\nSouth Mesa State Superfund Site, Mesa, Arizona\r\nProject Manager for interim remediation of this site.  The site was contaminated with VOCs in both soil and groundwater.  Interim remediation was performed for source reduction by removing VOCs from the vadose zone. Tasks included workplan preparation, design of vapor extraction and treatment system, permitting, soil sampling, construction of vapor extraction wells and treatment system, preparation of operation and maintenance manual, and system start-up, operation, monitoring, and reporting. Also performed was a pre-design investigation.\r\n\r\n1992-1994:  Malcolm Pirnie, Phoenix, Arizona \r\n\r\nPhoenix Goodyear Airport (North) CERCLA Site, Goodyear, AZ\r\nSenior hydrogeologist responsible for hydrogeologic aspects of remedial design and construction at TCE-contaminated groundwater site.  Responsibilities included quarterly groundwater monitoring, the installation of monitor wells, design and construction of injection and extraction wells for groundwater treatment/disposal, and technical negotiations with EPA.  Also performed was a pre-design investigation.\r\n\r\nWhite Tanks Facility, Maricopa County, Arizona\r\nSenior hydrogeologist for Resource Conservation And Recovery Act (RCRA) Closure.  Preparation and implementation of RCRA closure plan for hazardous waste treatment facility.  Key features of this project included delineating extent of hazardous waste contamination, regulatory negotiations, remediation subcontractor selection, removal oversight, and closure report preparation.  Also performed were sampling/analytical support and an integrated site assessment/investigation.\r\n\r\n1988-1991: SCS Engineers, Phoenix, Arizona\r\n\r\nState Land Property, Tucson, Arizona\r\nProject manager for the RI/FS of waste aluminum dross deposits near Davis-Monthan Air Force Base, Arizona.  Specific tasks performed included an environmental assessment, surface and subsurface soil sampling, laboratory analysis, development of a three-dimensional computer model identifying the extent of contamination, risk assessment, and feasibility study.  Based on the findings of the feasibility study, prepared remedial action plan. \r\n\r\nManufacturing Facility, Springfield, Missouri\r\nProject manager for RI at printed circuit board manufacturing facility.  Former/current facility operations were evaluated and historical waste disposal practices identified. Soil gas/geophysical surveys were performed.  The regulatory history of the facility was also assessed.  Based on this information, surface soil, water, and sediment sample locations were identified/sampled. Fourteen monitor well locations were also selected and the wells installed/sampled. Soil/groundwater samples were analyzed for cyanide, metals, and VOCs. \r\n\r\nBulk Fuel Storage Terminal, Savannah, Georgia \r\nProject manager for a hydrogeologic investigation of bulk liquid storage terminal containing 70 above-ground tanks in Savannah, Georgia.  Following a review of historical storage records, ten monitoring wells were installed throughout the site to evaluate groundwater quality and flow direction.  Conclusions regarding extent/magnitude of groundwater contamination were presented. \r\n\r\nReal Property Acquisition Support, Nationwide Hotel Chain \r\nProject manager for simultaneous environmental assessments of 30 hotels in 20 states.  Site reconnaissance, historical aerial photography review, and records searches performed nationwide under direction/coordination/ management of Mr. Gordon.\r\n\r\nU.S. Naval Facilities, Puerto Rico and Panama \r\nProject manager for environmental assessments of 1,300 acres adjacent to U.S. Naval facility in Puerto Rico and six active U.S. Naval sites in Panama Canal Zone totaling approximately 3,000 acres.  Workplans were first prepared, followed by review of U.S. Navy records.  Reconnaissance of the sites was then performed.  Historical aerial photographs were obtained and reviewed.  Reports were prepared identifying potential contaminant sources.\r\n\r\n1986-1988: Woodward Clyde Consultants, Phoenix, Arizona\r\n\r\nReal Property Acquisition Support, Phoenix, Arizona\r\nProject manager for numerous environmental assessments in Arizona.  Tasks performed included site reconnaissance, historical aerial photography review, and records searches. \r\n\r\n1981-1985: Arizona Department of Health Services, Phoenix\r\n\r\nCopper Mining Facilities, Arizona\r\nNegotiated technical aspects of three-way consent decree between ADHS, EPA, and Phelps Dodge addressing acid mine drainage in Chase Creek at the Morenci Mine.  Mr. Gordon was also an invited participant in an EPA-sponsored Mining Waste Forum, a meeting of industry, states, and EPA to discuss approaches to dealing with mining waste.\r\nPUBLICATIONS/PRESENTATIONS:\r\nThe East Washington Fluff Site, A State Commitment to Public Health; Proceedings Phoenix Brownfields 2002 Conference.\r\n\r\nGeologic Guide to Grand Canyon National Park, Kendall Hunt Publishing Co., 2000.\r