Confederated Tribes Soil Assessment\r\nWas part of a two person team on the Colville Reservation in eastern Washington during four months establishing baseline conditions for soil and vegetation. Worked in extreme weather conditions and rugged backcountry terrain for days at a time including navigation and operation of four wheel drive vehicles off-road. Required sound on-the-fly judgment to adjust sampling strategy to constantly changing conditions. Executed sound wilderness navigation and map reading in a variety of terrains and conditions. Soil parameters observed included soil temperature and texture, excavation and description of soil profile, determination of the presence or absence of organic horizons and depth if present, and identification of any disturbance (soil compaction) or erosion features on site. Native vegetation was identified to genus while non-native/invasive species were identified to species. Canopy, where present was recorded and identified to genus as well. Other related vegetative parameters recorded included size and decay class of coarse woody debris and snags where present. Photographic documentation of site location was performed at each site along with photo documentation of soil profiles, snags, and transect end points.  Site slope, aspect, and location was recorded at each site. Logistics were reviewed on both a daily and weekly basis as effective and timely completion of the project relied on creative planning and coordination with other teams. Sampling project was completed almost two months ahead of schedule allowing for an advanced project completion and significant savings for the client.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSkagit County Clean Samish Initiative\r\nPerformed weekly water quality sampling runs at 64 sites in the Skagit and Samish River watershed to monitor nutrient and fecal coliform levels. Two water samples were taken at each site; one to be analyzed in the lab and another to use for measuring temperature, dissolve oxygen, salinity,