 and current project statuses. Uploaded all materials to USDFW’s online Habitat Work Schedule which tracks and displays all salmon recovery projects in the State of Washington for the general public.\r\n\r\n \r\nOther Relevant Experience\r\n\r\nGIS Mapping for Master’s Thesis: “Gene flow and habitat connectivity for cougars in Washington and southern British Columbia”.\r\nCreated shape files of potential cougar locations in each WDFW game management unit in Washington State and southern British Columbia. Location estimations were based on knowledge of cougar behavior and habitat as well as hunting reports, WDFW siting’s, and anecdotal evidence. Performed over 150 hours of mapping in total. \r\n\r\nASHRAE Commercial Building Energy Audit Certificate\r\nCompleted parts 1 and 2 of ASHRAE’s Commercial Building Energy Audit certificate course (Nov. 2013). Subjects covered included: preliminary energy use analysis, calculating energy use intensity (EUI) building benchmarking, estimating rough costs and savings for EEMs, O&M adjustments, end-use energy break downs, identifying capital improvement projects, etc.\r\n\r\nFEMP Planning an Energy Assessment for Federal Buildings Certificate\r\nCompleted the Federal Energy Management Program energy assessment planning certificate course (Nov. 2013) Subject covered included: selecting the proper energy assessment type and prioritizing the facilities most in need of an energy assessments, understanding how key building components such as building envelope and electrical and mechanical systems are assessed, developing the master list of findings from the energy assessment and prioritizing an operational list of improvements, and measurement and verification activities.\r\nAssessment of Renewable Energy Production Facilities\r\nMade site visits to numerous renewable energy production facilities to view operations and talk with engineers and operators about how energy is produced, transmitted, and delivered along with the viability of production and growing pains of developing new energies. Site vistits included: micro-hydropower (and turbine production facility), biofuels refinery, aenerobic digester, residential solar installation, ground-source heat pump system, steam-powered district heating, and a newly constructed Living Building Challenge applicant. Research about the technologies was performed pre and post-site visit with particular attention paid to the production type’s respective impact on the environment.\r\n\r\nBullit Center Docent Training & Tours\r\nOfficial docent at the Bullit Center, the largest commerical “Living Building” in the world. Gives in-depth tours to the general public, school groups, and industry professionals. Go over the strict requirements of the challenge and how zero-net energy is achieved in the buiding.  Subjects covered in the tours include: ground source heatings, composting toilets, heat exchange, greywater filtration, photovoltaic solar installations, composting toilets, resource conservation, sustainable sourcing of materials, HVAC systems, and biomimicry. \r\n	2015-02-27 05:25:08.754167	2015-02-27 05:25:08.754167	596
