minary Assessments and Site Inspections of Willamette Valley Projects, US Army Corps of Engineers.  Ms. Cochrane is currently part of a team performing a Preliminary Assessment/Site Inspection (PA/SI) at three dams within the Willamette Valley Basin, Oregon, in accordance with the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Guidance for Performing Preliminary Assessments under CERCLA (EPA, 1991) and with the EPA Guidance for Performing Site Inspections under CERCLA (EPA, 1992). The PA involves reviewing readily available information to describe potentially hazardous waste releases that occurred at these Projects throughout their history of operations, including during its construction in order to evaluate whether contamination might be present at each facility that may harm human health and the environment. Also included was a site visit with the Client to observe areas of concern, and a review of publicly available, reasonably ascertainable federal, state, and local government records (or databases) for the subject and surrounding properties in order to develop an opinion on the presence and extent of any contaminants at the Project and to develop a conceptual site model (CSM).\r\nMs. Cochrane aided in evaluating the presence of contamination as part of the Site Inspections.  Sampling will consist of collecting surface and subsurface soil samples and sediment samples.  Samples will be analyzed for a wide-variety of constituents because contaminant sources are unknown in many of the areas.\r\n\r\nEnvironmental regulatory compliance audits of Federal Facilities, General Services Administration.  Ms. Cochrane is currently part of a team performing on-site environmental regulatory compliance audits at GSA-owned Federal buildings in California and Nevada. These audits assess potential environmental liability in current and future use and operations at each facility with consideration to applicable federal, state, local regulations, and with the associated U.S. TEAM Guides and State Supplements. The project requires experience or familiarity with the following environmental media: air quality and Title V permitting, water programs, pesticides programs, solid waste, universal and hazardous wastes, above ground and underground storage tanks, hazardous substances and chemicals, and toxic substances including asbestos, PCBs, and lead based paint in facilities. Ms. Cochrane evaluates the effectiveness of active environmental management systems and assesses risks from regulated and unregulated materials and practices through research on facility background and compliance history, onsite inspections, personnel interviews, and evaluation of findings. Team findings are compiled into detailed technical reports including advice on improvements, for which Ms. Cochrane demonstrates experience in technical writing and technical editing. \r\n\r\nConceptual site model development in litigation support, Colville Confederated Tribes.  In 2013, Ms. Cochrane co-authored a memo developing a conseptual site model for contaminant release from soils in the Upper Columbia River ulands as part of litigation support for the CCT. Ms. Cochrane researched and authored a literature review on transport mechanisms of heavy metals in soils, providing scientific basis for assumed release of smelter-associated contaminants into the uplands environment via erosion and runoff into fluvial systems, leaching into groundwater, root uptake by vegetation, and resuspension by wind erosion into air. \r\n\r\nField crew supervisor and manager for soil condition assessment, Colville Confederated Tribes (CCT).   In 2013, Ms. Cochrane worked as a field crew supervisor and manager of field operations of three teams performing field data and soil sample collection at 450 sites on forested lands within the Colville Indian Reservation, in order to establish soil baseline conditions to assist in natural resource management. Ms. Cochrane researched and acquired survey instruments and supporting materials needed for assessment implementation, designed a quality assurance/quality control protocol to CCT standards and requirements, ensured all field work was completed to standard and field personnel remained safe and in good health, and performed database data entry and management. The position required proficiency in GPS data collection using top-quality Trimble equipment and software; determining soil parameters including soil temperature and texture, excavation and description of soil profile, identification of organics, and documentation of surface disturbances; soil sample collection methods  preventing cross-contamination and other sample invalidations; identification to genus of native vegetation and canopy cover, and to species of invasive vegetation; orienteering, navigation and operation of four wheel drive vehicles over very rough terrain; and working and living in the field in all conditions. When field data collection was completed, Ms. Cochrane performed Nitrogen-Phosphorus-Potassium lab analysis of soil samples as part of a two person team and executed all post-processing of lab and field data, including differential correction of GPS data and export to ESRI-compatible formats. All field and lab data was compiled into a database and GIS layer created by Ms. Cochrane, which she used to design and produce visualizations of correlations between variables and assessment results. Ms. Cochrane participated in writing a detailed report of the assessment, for which she researched and authored the project background, and described all methods and theory of the field operations, lab analysis, and post-processing of GPS data, including difficulties encountered. \r\n\r\nField data management for habitat restoration efforts, Great Basin Institute (GBI).  As a volunteer with the AmeriCorps in 2012, Ms. Cochrane was responsible for collecting and managing field data of a habitat restoration project west of Las Vegas, Nevada. She maintained daily logs of project progress, including photo documentation and area surveyed using GPS; ensured necessary caution was exercised where endangered species were identified; and delivered in-field  lectures on the geology of the project area to fulfill the education requirements of participants in AmeriCorps programs. Ms. Cochrane’s data was compiled by GBI senior staff for reports to the National Forest Service.\r\n\r\nFairhaven Shipyard as a point source for metal ion contamination of Bellingham Bay, Washington.  As part of a team in 2011, Ms. Cochrane developed and implemented a study of heavy metal contaminants in Bellingham Bay. She performed the field data collection, consisting of surface water samples taken at locations of various distance from the Fairhaven Shipyard, thought to be a possible point source of contamination. Ms. Cochrane assisted in lab analysis of the samples, in which laser-ablation inductively coupled plasma-mass spectroscopy (Agilent 7500ce with a New Wave UP213 laser) was used to determine levels of arsenic, lead, copper, zinc, and mercury. In a detailed report, Ms. Cochrane and team compared these results to levels of metal contaminants averaged across random Puget Sound locations near Bellingham Bay, discovering that concentrations were no higher near the shipyard than are average for the area.\r\n\r\nGIS analysis and recommendation of locations for new facility.  Using ESRI GIS core programs in 2010, Ms. Cochrane produced a detailed report outlining possible locations for construction of a new facility, with detailed recommendations stating pros and cons of five location options based off of interpretations she developed from GIS data. The report packet included maps drawn by Ms. Cochrane to assist in visualization of the variables considered when determining possible locations.\r\n\r\nExamination of environmental risks and benefits of current aquaculture practices.  In 2011, Ms. Cochrane researched environmental impacts of current aquaculture practices, compiling findings in a report used to help students make educated decisions when purchasing seafood. She considered six studies into various aspects of aquaculture, and included data from three sea farms to describe the environmental risks and benefits related to human health, biodiversity including transgenic fish, sustainability and large pollutant production. The final report was made available to students of Western Washington University in Bellingham, Washington.\r\n\r\nSequence of epibiont colonization of Mercenaria mercenaria as evidenced by trace fossils.   In a study of trace fossils on an edible, hard-shelled species of mollusk in 2011, Ms. Cochrane identified possible causes of death and developed a sequence of colonization of the fossil by epibiont organisms. The study required knowledge of marine macro-organism lifestyles, characteristics, identification to genus or species where possible, and identification of trace fossils, what organism caused them and how it came to be. Findings were photo documented were complied with interpretations in a report authored by Ms. Cochrane. \r\n\r\nEnvironmental risks and benefits of net-zero energy residential homes.  In 2011, Ms. Cochrane researched environmental impacts of several new residential constructions designed to use combinations of alternative energy options such as solar, wind, geothermal, paired with top-of-industry energy efficient construction methods to reduce dependence on traditional energy sources to zero. She compiled her findings into a report to be used in a presentation on alternative energy options for future housing developments.\r\n\r\nPetrography of rocks of the Coast Arc Complex, Porteau Cove area, B.C.  In 2010, Ms. Cochrane developed a petrographic study of rocks sampled from north to south along the Porteau Cover region of the Coast Arc Complex in an effort to identify mineralogical changes during geologic development of the complex. She planned and coordinated fieldwork including locations of data collection and methods to ensure validity, and performed the fieldwork over several days. Rock samples collected in the field were brought to a lab facility at Western Washington University, where Ms. Cochrane produced multiple thin sections for mineral identification and description, documenting findings using a Zeiss polarizing photomicroscope. Findings were compiled into a detailed report and presentation.\r\n\r\nOrigin of clay minerals in sandstone of the Eocene Chuckanut Formation, northwestern Washington.  As part of a team in 2010, Ms. Cochrane developed a study of sedimentary rocks sampled from the Chuckanut Formation in Bellingham, Washington in order to determine possible origins of clay minerals identified. Ms. Cochrane performed the sample collection in the field and lab analysis using rock powdering equipment, a Rigaku X-ray diffractometer and a Cambridge stereoscan scanning electron microscope. Results and interpretations were compiled into a report and presentation delivered at a stratigraphy and sedimentation meeting at Western Washington University. \r\n\r\n\r\nGeologic structures mapping of California-Nevada-Utah regions of the Cordillera.  Ms. Cochrane spent 6 weeks mapping geologic structures and rock types of several areas of the Cordillera in 2011, producing three geologic maps with cross-sections showing interpretations of structures at depth. These materials were incorporated as field evidence into a report she authored on the large scale geologic history of the Cordillera, with focus on the geologic processes displayed by smaller-scale structures. Included in the report was full photo documentation of rock types, mineral identifications, small and large scale structures, fossil identifications and visible relationships between strata with interpretations for each. \r\n\r\n  \r\nStatus and opportunities for remediation of coral reefs offshore of Puerto Rico.  In 2011, Ms. Cochrane compiled findings of coral reef decline offshore of Puerto Rico from five studies conducted in the area over ten years. She developed interpretations based off of those results for possible causes of the decline including, increased sedimentation of ocean water and increased nutrient content from agricultural runoff, related to an increase in urbanization of Puerto Rico. Her interpretations were included in a report with research results of opportunities for remediation that could improve the health of Puerto Rican coral reefs.\r\n	2015-02-27 05:25:08.879647	2015-02-27 05:25:08.879647	597
