1222	Betsy	M	Vance	betsy.vance@eiltd.net	2065253362		1305 NE 45th Street	Suite 206	Seattle	WA	98105	144.610000000000014	Project Scientist	Environment International Ltd.	5	SUMMARY OF QUALIFICATIONS\r\nBetsy Vance is a recent graduate from the University of Washington’s School of Environmental and Forest Sciences where she completed her master’s degree with a focus on forest soils. While at the University she was trained on a wide range of laboratory techniques for analyzing soils and is comfortable analyzing soils for both physical and chemical parameters including those assessing common macro- and micronutrient levels as well as  determination of contaminant levels including heavy metals. \r\nShe has extensive fieldwork experience, successfully executing a variety of time-sensitive field projects as quickly as possible without neglecting the quality of the project or the safety of her crews. She has worked in both front and backcountry settings including extreme environments in both the desert southwest and the Pacific northwest collecting soils and vegetation data, both tabular and spatial. \r\n\r\nEDUCATION\r\n2013 M.S. Forest Resources, University of Washington, Seattle, WA\r\n2008 B.A. Geology, French, Mount Holyoke College, South Hadley, MA\r\n\r\nRELEVANT COURSE WORK\r\n \r\n•\tGraduate studies for soils\r\n•\tForest soils and site productivity\r\n•\tBiogeochemical cycling in soils\r\n•\tAdvanced soil genesis and classification\r\n•\tAdvanced soil and plant analysis\r\n•\tStructural Geology\r\n•\tRocks and Minerals\r\n•\tIgneous/Metamorphic petrology\r\n•\tMapping and Spatial Analysis\r\n•\tPhysical Geology\r\n•\tSoil chemistry\r\n•\tStatistical inference in applied research I: Hypothesis testing and estimation for ecologists and resource managers\r\n•\tStatistical inference in applied research II: Regression analysis for ecologists and resource managers\r\n•\tStatistical analysis techniques for community ecology\r\n \r\n\r\nPROFESSIONAL EXPERIENCE (Selected Relevant Projects)\r\n\r\nSoil condition assessment for the Confederated Tribes of the Colville\r\n\tLed one of three two-person crews on the Colville Reservation in eastern Washington to establish soil and vegetation baseline conditions designed to assist the tribe with natural resource management. As one of the three crew leads, Ms. Vance was responsible for developing the weekly itinerary for her and her junior crew member, designed to maximize sampling efficiency and to adhere to a sampling schedule developed during the project design. Any sampling issues or discrepancies encountered in the field were recorded and communicated with the survey design team to discuss any potential survey modifcations necessary. Ms. Vance was responsible for organizing data collected by her crew, managing and delegating data entry tasks between herself and the junior crew member, and following strict quality control protocols to ensure the integrity and accuracy of all field data collected. Upon completion of field operations, Ms.Vance supported the writing of the draft report regarding data collection and management procedures.\r\n\r\nSoil parameters observed included soil temperature and texture, excavation and description of soil profile, determination of the presence or absence of organic horizons and depth if present, and identification of any disturbance (soil compaction) or erosion features on site. Back in the lab, Ms.Vance tested the soils for the macronutrients Nitrogen, Phosphorus, and Potassium. Native vegetation was identified to genus while non-native/invasive species were identified to species, and canopy, where present was recorded and identified to genus as well. Other related vegetative parameters recorded included size and decay class of coarse woody debris and snags where present.\r\n\r\nUplands vegetation and soils monitoring \r\nMs. Vance led crews on front and backcountry trips to establish long-term standardized protocols for monitoring soils and vegetation of the 11 national parks and monuments within the Sonoran Desert Network, located in the southwestern United States. Crews recorded terrestrial vegetation cover for common perennial species and for uncommon and non-native species (both annual and perennial); terrestrial soil cover described by substrate classes, and soil aggregate stability described based on a standardized scale of 1-6;  cryptobiotic soil crust cover and frequency and morphological group; and landscape characteristics related to both geomorphological and erosion features. Soil samples collected from each monitoring plot were brought back to the lab and analyzed for bulk density, total carbon, pH, particle size distribution and electrical conductivity. Upon completion of fieldwork, Ms.Vance worked with colleagues to ensure all of the data was enetered quickly and accurately implementing a quality control pathway in which at least two employees reviewed the data before sending it off for final review to a higher official. She also took charge of compiling, entering and organizing all of the soils data generated in the lab. She built a database to organize and manage the data and then geo-referenced all of the data to create soil data maps for the National Parks and Monuments within the network using ArcGIS.\r\n\r\nStream quality monitoring in the Sonoran Desert\r\nMs.Vance worked with senior aquatic ecologists to characterize the ecological and hydrological conditions of rivers located in culturally significant National Parks and Monuments of the desert Southwest. She took water quality measurements that  examined turbidity (suspended solids), pH, electrical conductivity, toxins, microbial populations, and selected inorganic nutrients. Water quantity was established through monthly, seasonal and annual stream discharge measurements of means and totals. Channel morphology and channel habitat was determined through the mapping of channel cross-sections, slope, sinuosity and continuity. As part of the ecological condition assessments, she conducted riparian vegetation surveys to describe the vegetation communities, including both native and non-native species, in tems of the their structure and recruitment status. Native and non-native fish abundance and richness were recorded. Macroinvertebrates were collected to determine taxa abundance and richness as well. \r\n\r\nInventory and quality assessment of seeps, springs, and tinajas of the Sonoran Desert\r\nAs part of a field team, Ms.Vance conducted surveys characterizing critical surface water sources in the Sonoran Desert and Apach Highlands ecoregions, critical to supporting flora and fauna in the area. Seeps, springs and tinajas were located and ground-truthed based on old park records, interviews with hikers and park personnel, and through the analysis of aerial photographs. At each of the various water sources, Ms.Vance and her team collected data concerning the water dynamics, quality and persistence of water throughout the year. Additionally, aquatic invertebrates were collected to evaluate community composition of these localized water sources. Each seep, spring and tinaja was mapped and recorded using GPS units. Where possible, water depth, weatted area and soil moisture data was collected. Any perennial riparian vegetation observed was recorded by species to describe community composition and species abundance of common spring species. \r\n\r\n\r\nEPA Sub-contractor for Disaster Debris Removal post Hurrican Katrina\r\nOversaw deactivation and demolition (D&D) of homes damaged by the 2005 Hurricane Katrina in New Orleans and surrounding parishes deemed to contain asbestos. She followed strict protocols to ensure that all demolition crews were successfully upholding the Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality and EPA requirements regarding the proper handling and disposal of asbestos containing materials (ACM). Any violations by demolition crews were recorded and reported to the EPA.\r\n\r\nRELATED FIELD EXPERIENCE\r\nMaster’s thesis research: “An examination of the soils supporting Hackelia venusta, Washington State’s most endangered species”\r\nIn conjunction with the U.S. Forest Service, U.S. Fish and Wildlife and the Washington State Department of Natural Resources, helped in the design and installation of field research techniques to carefully establish the characteristics of the soil supporting Hackelia venusta, an endangered species endemic to Washington state. Four site locations were established within the known population of H.venusta and soil pits were excavated at each site. Within each soil pit, descriptions of soil horizons and depths were recorded (including continuity, color, structure and aggregation), bulk density was collected where possible and bulk soil samples were collected by depth until continuous or nearly continuous bedrock was reached. Samples were taken back to the lab and analyzed for physical (bulk density, particle size distribution, and color) and chemical (pH, total carbon, plant-available nitrogen and phosphorus, cation exchange capacity and percent base saturation) parameters. Continued monitoring efforts included monthly visits to four site locations in eastern Washington to gather data concerning soil temperature and erosion. Upon completion of field work, Ms.Vance wrote a comprehensive report on her work including a thorough literature review, detailed description of methods, and an in-depth analysis of her results. The report was submitted to authorities at the U.S. Forest Service and the U.S. Fish and Wildlife offices for their records.\r\n\r\nQuantifying the fate of applied N fertilizer over a one-year period in Douglas-Fir plantations using stable isotope technology\r\nAssisted in execution of NSF-funded project through both the installation and monitoring of field sites located in Douglas-fir plantations distributed throughout the Pacific northwest. Ten field sites were established and 5 plots were set up within each site, each plot being centered around a single target tree. Fieldwork included establishment of 100 m2 circular plot, and within each plot the application of nitrogen fertilizers, DBH measurments for all perennial, woody species within the plot, ocular estimates of vegetation cover by species,  collection of soil cores down to 60 cm depth, tree cores from the target tree, foliage from target tree from the top 1/3 of the tree in an effort to capture the newest growth, and forest floor samples. Foliage samples were dried, divided into age classes, and analyzed for 15N using isotope-ratio mass spectrometry (IRMS). Forest floor samples were dried and weighed and analyzed for bulk volume and 15N using IRMS. Soil cores were dried, sieved, and prepared for 15N analysis by IRMS technology. In addition to the fieldwork component of this project, Ms.Vance supported the writing of status reports and gave multiple presentations to discuss the project and anticipated results at conferences, including the annual Soil Science Society of America conference and the North American Forest Soils Conference.\r\n	2015-02-27 05:25:09.045132	2015-02-27 05:25:09.045132	599
1223	John	W	Mason	john.mason@eiltd.net	5034845711		11845 SE Morrison St. 		Portland	OR	97216	165.5	Senior Scientist	Environment International	20	Summary of Qualifications\r\nMr. John W. Mason is an ecologist and biostatistician with over 20 years of experience in sample and experimental design as applied to biological and epidemiological field data.  As a consultant, Mr. Mason worked on a NRDA for a site in Maine with potential petroleum contamination and recently completed work on an NRDA for a CERCLA site.  Mr. Mason has reviewed remedial investigation technical reports and site assessments for CERCLA sites for various physical media including sediment, surface water, groundwater, and pore water, as well as bioassay toxicity testing.  He has worked with multiple Native American tribes and has provided statistical and experimental design support at Superfund and Targeted Brownfields Assessment sites contaminated with metals, radiologicals, and organics.  As a result of recent work on CERCLA sites and his vast experience conducting biological surveys, Mr. Mason is highly experienced with NRDA procedures involving CERCLA regulations as well as those pertaining to the ESA.  He has designed sample plans for the determination of background levels at multiple sites and evaluated and formally commented on multiple technical RI/FS documents from CERCLA sites including QAPPS, SAPs, and Phase I and II reports. He has conducted biological surveys to monitor the success of restoration projects conducted as part of NRDA settlements and he has coordinated successfully with federal, state, and tribal trustees in connection with potential injury assessment.  He is also familiar with the state companion laws for both acts for California and Washington and well versed in the use of EPA guidances pertaining to determination of background levels, use of statistics for biological samples, and human and ecological health assessment.  He has worked collaboratively with multiple federal agencies including the US Army Corps of Engineers, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, US Geological Survey, US Fish and Wildlife Service, and Minerals Management Service.  He has presented his work to a broad spectrum of audiences ranging from informal public gatherings and meetings to scientific conferences and symposia and has composed multiple reports and summaries.\r\nEducation \r\n2006\tMaster of Science, Epidemiology and Minor, Biostatistics, University of California, Davis\r\n1997\tMaster of Marine Science, California State University, Fresno (Moss Landing Marine Laboratories)\r\n1987\tBachelor of Arts, Biology, University of Texas, Austin\r\nRelevant Project Experience \r\nStreamlined Assessment of Potential Impacts from Federal Facility Operations on the Environment and Protected Treaty Rights.  For the U.S. Department of Energy, analyzed one of the largest environmental data sets known to consider potential impacts from federal facility operations over the last 50 years and those planned for the next 50.  Potential impacts considered involved those to resources and uses of concern to three Tribes in the Pacific Northwest including those protected by Treaties, e.g., fisheries.  Analysis formed the basis of a clear and reasonable approach to potential injury assessment in a project running high with emotionalism.  \r\n\r\nMarine Mammal Monitoring Plan, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.  Collected data for a six month marine mammal monitoring project for the National Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration counting whales and dolphins. In the Eastern Tropical Pacific.  Spent six months at sea conducting line transects for whales and dolphins in the eastern tropical pacific off of a 200 foot vessel. Assisted with strip transect survey of seabirds and small boat captures of sea turtles for distribution study. Also, conducted net tows for fish and assisted with CTD (device measuring conductivity, temperature, and depth) deployments.\r\n\r\nSupport for the Upper Columbia River Remedial Investigation/Feasibility Study (RI/FS) and Related NRDA Matters at Superfund Site.  Mr. Mason is providing biological and statistical support to the Confederated Tribes of the Colville Reservation (Colville Tribes) on the Upper Columbia River, Washington in relation to ongoing RI/FS and related NRDA matters.  Support includes analyzing previous studies and collected data; developing statistically defensible beach and sediment sampling designs; providing comments on surface water and fish tissue quality assurance project plans (QAPPs) and sampling assurance plans (SAPs) and other documents developed by the responsible parties; and supporting human health risk assessment.\r\n\r\nSupport on NRDA Matter at Superfund Site.  Mr. Mason provided support for an ongoing NRDA matter involving hazardous substance releases to soil, groundwater, sediments, and surface water.  Support included providing advice on appropriate background levels for purposes of injury determination and quantification and assisting in calculating injuries to both abiotic and biotic resources using media benchmarks and GIS mapping techniques.  Project completion relied heavily on interpretation of CERCLA and NRDA regulations as well as the application of statistical and database management principles.\r\n\r\nStatistical and Study Design Support for NRDA Matter in Maine.  Mr. Mason provided support to the Maine Department of Environmental Protection for an NRDA matter involving an abandoned marine oil terminal in Hampden, Maine.  His support included analysis and assessment of biological receptors and exposure pathways, contaminant data, and creation of a study design to adequately assess potential injuries related to releases of oil in a riparian environment with heavy tidal influences.  Relevant previous studies were evaluated to collect the necessary data on biological receptors in the area.  These data were used to inform the NRDA process and evaluate the potential risk to various ecological receptors.\r\n\r\nData collection for NRDA Common Murre Restoration Project.  Mr. Mason assisted with data collection on a Common Murre restoration project on Devil’s Slide Rock off of the California coast.  Common Murres were counted from photographs and observed from shore.  The project was part of an NRDA settlement concerning an oil spill off of the California coast in 1986 and subsequent restoration.\r\n\r\nQuestionnaire Survey Design for Assessing Risk to Colville Tribe Members.  Mr. Mason assisted in developing a resource usage questionnaire for Colville Tribal Members.  The questionnaire was designed to assist the Colville Tribes in assessing potential risk to tribal members from fish and wildlife consumption and the use of various river resources in connection with tribal rites and ceremonies.  He reviewed the questionnaire for potential biases and to ensure that it was targeting the appropriate population segment and provided advice on appropriate sample size of those interviewed.  He also evaluated fish tissue contaminant data to assist the Colville Tribes in developing guidelines for consumption of certain species.\r\n\r\nDistribution and Abundance of Seabirds in the Southern California Bight.  Mr. Mason collected data for and authored a peer-reviewed article presenting aerial survey data collected off of the southern California coast.  Three years of surveys were conducted at sea and along island and mainland coastlines from fixed-wing aircraft from the California/Mexico border to central California and 100 km out to sea.  Seasonal maps using GIS were generated for individual species and the study was accepted for publication in Studies in Avian Biology.  Mr. Mason also counted breeding seabirds from photographs to assess breeding success and population status of pelicans and cormorants on the California Channel Islands.  He coordinated with several state (e.g., California Department of Fish and Game) and federal agencies (e. g., the US Geological Survey, Minerals Management Service, US Fish and Wildlife Service, and US Navy) and local landowners to facilitate access to restricted areas.\r\n\r\nStatistical Analysis Regarding Breeding Ashy Storm-Petrels.    Mr. Mason collected and statistically analyzed data on breeding Ashy Storm-Petrels in several southern California offshore caves.  Caves were visited several times a year for multiple years and storm-petrel adults, chicks and eggs were counted and evaluated to determine breeding status and success and to document instances of predation.  Data analysis indicated a stable population of storm-petrels existed with fluctuations attributable to survey effort and predator interactions.\r\n\r\nAnalysis of Data on Mercury Levels in Benthic Infauna.  While obtaining a Master’s degree in epidemiology/biostatistics collected and analyzed data on mercury levels in benthic infauna of California’s southern San Francisco Bay. Operated trucks and small boats to access sites and trained new workers in field methods and identification techniques using microscopes. \r\n\r\nStudy on Distribution and Abundance of Seabirds and Marine Mammals on Monterey Bay.  Designed a study to assess changes in distribution and abundance of seabirds in Monterey Bay, California. Made statistical comparisons to historical data and found population number increases in Sooty Shearwaters and Western Grebes and decreases in Common Murres and Cassin’s Auklets. Also, conducted shore surveys for dead birds to assess use as estimator of at-sea abundances and impacts of gill-net fishing in the bay. Found Common Murres to be the most susceptible species to gill-netting and shore surveys to be poor indicators of at-sea abundance for most species. \r\n\r\nNorthern Fur Seal Study, Pribilof Islands, Alaska.  Conducted a population census and studied the impact of solid waste and other human development on juvenile Northern fur seals in the Pribilof Islands.  Work was conducted on behalf of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA).  The project involved field work over two one-month periods including fur seal observations, captures, tagging, and freeing from entanglements (e.g., fishing lines and packing bands).  The population census consisted of a pup mark-recapture study involving the entire Pribilof population. \r\n	2015-02-27 05:25:09.202267	2015-02-27 05:25:09.202267	600
