od at low concentrations but yields a 4-fold \r\nreduction in analytical effort. Supervised analyses of thousands of samples received for asbestos \r\nanalysis by PLM, TEM and phase-contrast light microscopy (PCM). Evaluated new methods for \r\nquantitating asbestos fiber releasability as a consultant to the EPA. Served on EPA panels which \r\ndeveloped methods for analyzing asbestos in vermiculite attic insulation. Served as Peer Review \r\nGroup Leader for review of EPA’s Final Report on the World Trade Center (WTC) Dust Screening Study \r\nand for EPA’s Draft Final Report Comparison of the Alternative Asbestos Control Method and the \r\nNESHAP Method for Demolition of Asbestos-Containing Buildings. Appointed to EPA Science Advisory \r\nBoard that reviewed the EPA’s Proposed Approach for Estimation of Bin-Specific Cancer Potency \r\nFactors for Inhalation Exposure to Asbestos\r\nPhone (518) 210-8295\r\nE-mail\r\njswebberasbestos@gmail.com\r\n\r\nand the EPA’s Toxicological Review of Libby Amphibole Asbestos. Panel member of NIOSH Roadmap on \r\nAsbestos.\r\n\r\nAsbestos Analysis Certification Developed criteria for EPA accreditation of asbestos labs during \r\nappointment by National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) to Asbestos Criteria and \r\nOperations Review Committee. As an independent Technical Expert for NIST, assessed performance of \r\nmore than 120 TEM/PLM labs nationwide. Instituted the nation's most comprehensive state asbestos \r\nlaboratory certification program for incorpora- tion into New York State Department of Health's \r\nEnvironmental Laboratory Approval Program (ELAP). Evaluated and defined analytical procedures \r\nmandated for use in ELAP. Inaugurated a proficiency-testing (PT) program for determining the \r\nanalytical quality of hundreds of asbestos laboratories. Administered the formulation and \r\ndistribution of tens of thousands of PT samples for analysis by PLM, PCM, and TEM. Designed aerosol \r\ngenerator that produces homogeneous fiber loadings on more than 100 filter-loaded cassettes \r\nsimultaneously.\r\n\r\nEnvironmental Chemistry PT Supervised laboratory that annually generates and distributes 15,000 \r\nchemistry and radioisotope PT samples to\r\n500 laboratories worldwide.\r\n\r\nStandards Development Serving (or served) as: Chair (formerly Secretary), ASTM International \r\nCommittee D22, Air Quality; Secretary, ASTM International Subcommittee D22.07, Sampling and \r\nAnalysis of Asbestos; Secretary of US Technical Advisory Group to ISO TC 146, Air Quality; Member, \r\nINELA Institute Proficiency-Testing Expert Committee.\r\n\r\nAerosol Research Developed procedures for identifying airborne particles by electron microscopy for \r\ncorrelation with bulk chemical data collected in long-range sulfate (acid-rain precursor) transport \r\nsamples. Utilized microdiffraction, energy-dispersive x-ray spectroscopy and morphology \r\nmeasurements. Published direct evidence of a coal-combustion source of acid rain by identifying \r\ncoal fly ash at high concentrations in high-sulfate air masses reaching the acid-stressed \r\nAdirondack Mountains. Designed an automated sequential split-sample inertial impactor for \r\ncollecting aerosols\r\nfor direct analysis by TEM. Developed software to automate particle analysis via stage automation, \r\nimage analysis of electron-diffraction patterns, x-ray analysis, morphology-based image analysis, \r\netc.\r\n\r\nComputer Programing Programmed PCs and SUN workstations using VisualBASIC, FORTRAN and C++ to: \r\ninterface analytical instruments; calibrate and file raw analytical data on disk; directly \r\ncalculate calibrated lattice spacings from electron diffraction patterns on a digitizer; search all \r\npossible zone axes of a known mineral for fit to measured values, generate random TEM grid squares \r\nfor routine asbestos and microparticle analysis; automatically iterate gran function values for \r\nacidity/alkalinity determinations of acid